secretary of state george p. shultz will have to overcome yitzhak shamir's growing opposition if he expects the new u.s. peace proposals to get anywhere
the 72-year-old prime minister, a former underground fighter and senior spymaster, has a reputation for being tough-minded. aides say he will not yield to the pressure of negative publicity or diplomatic arm-twisting
shamir has expressed serious reservations, and some annoyance, about american ideas for reviving progress toward peace in the middle east. to clear the air in advance of the shultz visit next week, he sent emissaries to washington to declare what he would and would not accept
one envoy was ehud olmert, a senior figure in shamir's conservative likud bloc, who said he told shultz the prime minister would not agree to territorial compromise in advance of peace talks
territory for peace is a non-starter,'' olmert said in an interview. ``we are ready to negotiate on the territorial issue, but that doesn't mean we are ready to accept withdrawing from the territories before negotiations.''
israel has occupied the west bank and gaza strip since capturing them from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
shultz suggested the land-for-peace formula in a speech to the council on foreign relations in washington and it apparently upset shamir
the timing, manner and phrasing was inappropriate, inasmuch as he wants to have the prime minister in the process,'' olmert said, adding that he believed the secretary of state realized his ``mistake.''
shultz's plan calls for:
_ an international forum that would convene by april to launch arab-israeli negotiations. the soviets would likely play an equal role with washington
_ an interim solution for the west bank and gaza in the form of self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians who live there. elections would be held by october to choose a self-governing body
_ talks on the final status of the occupied lands to start by december even without progress on autonomy
shamir initially indicated flexibility, to encourage negotiations, but the suggestion that he would agree to yield some of the occupied land caused a storm of protest among likud hard-liners
perhaps fearing concessions would be seen as giving in to arab rioters, shamir has drawn back, with tougher rhetoric and warnings between the lines that he will not accept pressure from the americans
he has been cool to soviet involvement, requested a clearer definition of the forum that would launch negotiations, and expressed opposition to linking talks on a temporary solution in the occupied territories with negotiations on a permanent settlement
he argues that several years of experience with limited self-rule is needed to build confidence for a stable solution
there is a need for a considerable period of practical experience, of coexistence between us and the palestinian arab authorities before the question of sovereignty can be approached,'' shamir said in a speech this week
shultz will begin a middle east shuttle thursday after a visit to moscow, using jerusalem as a base and traveling to jordan, egypt and possibly other arab countries, israeli officials said
his most intensive shuttle, however, may be between shamir and foreign minister shimon peres. the two partners and rivals in israel's coalition government and who disagree sharply on strategy for peace
they are miles apart,'' an official close to peres said privately. ``shultz will try to bring them to together as he has in the past.''
peres, leader of the center-left labor party, has endorsed jordan's proposal for an international conference, which shamir says would be biased against israel. labor accepts the land-for-peace formula but the likud fears giving up land would make israel vulnerable
aides to both leaders say shultz will concentrate on winning shamir's agreement, since peres already has accepted the shultz plan. ``shultz's major goal is to convince shamir,'' one official said
a senior aide to shamir, also speaking on condition of anonymity, said the prime minister views the shultz visit ``with caution'' but is ready to listen and give his position. ``some of his (shultz's) ideas are okay and others are not,'' the aide said
nicolas b. tatro is chief of the associated press bureau in jerusalem. delayed.</note>
the reputed leader of a chicago-area group called the skinheads and five other alleged white supremacists were indicted friday for attacking a woman and drawing a swastika on her wall with her blood
authorities believe the defendants beat the 20-year-old woman, with whom they were acquainted, because she had black friends, state's attorney's spokeswoman lisa howard said
the group's leader, clark martell, 28, and the others were charged with home invasion, robbery, theft and two counts of aggravated battery, ms. howard said
arrested with them jan. 25 was an unidentified 16-year-old whose indictment had been expected friday but was delayed until later this month because a special hearing must be held to charge him as an adult, ms. howard said
the victim was not identified to protect her from members of the white supremacist group, ms. howard said
the suspects are accused of pushing their way into the woman's north side apartment last april, forcing her to the floor and repeatedly punching and kicking her
after her attackers sprayed a mace-type chemical in her face, the woman managed to break free and lock herself in the bathroom, where she passed out, ms. howard said
the defendants allegedly ransacked her apartment, stole jewelry and clothing and drew swastikas throughout her home, ms. howard said
most of the nazi symbols were spray-painted or drawn with markers, but one swastika on the woman's living room wall was drawn with the victim's blood,'' ms. howard said
prosecutors believe the attack was motivated by the defendants' anger over the victim's friendship'' with blacks, ms. howard said. the victim had formerly associated with the skinheads, she said
this type of crime, which is nothing more than vicious race hatred, will not be tolerated in cook county, just as it cannot be tolerated anywhere in our society,'' state's attorney richard m. daley said in a statement
these defendants will be prosecuted to fullest extent of the law, as will anyone who dares to commit such a cowardly crime,'' he said
the home invasion charge, which is the most serious, has a maximum prison sentence of 30 years and a minimum of six years without probation, ms. howard said. the robbery charge can bring as much as seven years in prison and the theft and battery charges can bring as much as five-year terms each, she said
the others indicted were identified as morgan kipp, 18, her brother sean kipp, 20, cassandra clark, 20, tracy zajdel, 20, and kevin jamison, 26. they are scheduled to be arraigned march 11 before chief criminal court judge richard fitzgerald. all except martell are free on $50,000 bond
the state's attorney's office will seek to try the juvenile as an adult
martell is scheduled to appear in court twice on charges stemming from separate racial attacks before the hearing on the latest indictments
skinheads is a name some white supremacists across the nation have given themselves, in accordance with their practice of shaving their heads. but some people enjoy the music and fashion of the skinheads without sharing their racist sentiments, said terry levin, a spokesman for the state's attorney's office
spanish women will be able to enlist in the armed forces under a decree that takes effect next week, but they won't be eligible for combat or military academies
women will be allowed to serve in 24 noncombatant units in the armed forces and paramilitary civil guards, government spokesman javier solana told reporters friday after the weekly cabinet meeting
the cabinet had just approved a decree providing for volunteer female military service in keeping with an article in the constitution that prohibits discrimination on the basis of sex
women can sign up for military service after publication tuesday of the decree in the official state bulletin, but they will not be eligible for admittance to the country's three military academies
all spanish males over the age of 18 are required to serve one year in the military
panama, apparently seeking a way out of a legal and diplomatic predicament with the united states, made discreet inquiries about u.s. willingness to drop federal charges against military strong man gen. manuel antonio noriega, administration officials say
the state department confirmed friday that panamanian authorities had asked about that possibility and that assistant secretary of state elliott abrams raised the matter with the justice department
after being told that dropping the charges was ``technically possible,'' abrams relayed that message wednesday to panamanian president eric arturo delvalle during an unannounced meeting in miami
but during their discussion, abrams ``made no deal, offered no deal and was not in a position to offer a deal,'' state department spokesman charles redman said
redman added that the indictments against noriega are ``obviously based on strong evidence, and we have every intention on carrying through with them.''
the panamanian embassy had no comment on the miami meeting, saying only that delvalle had gone to miami for medical treatment
redman denied an account in the new york times that said abrams told delvalle the indictment might be dropped if noriega withdrew from politics and went into exile. the times cited as its sources u.s. officials and congressional staff members it did not name
the panamanian inquiry was made as a political crisis grew in panama, brought on in part by noriega's legal problems
indictments handed down in florida two weeks ago portrayed noriega as a key member of an international drug trafficking conspiracy
among other activities, he was accused of providing protection and other government services to international drug smugglers who shipped cocaine and marijuana to the united states through panama
u.s.-panamanian agreements do not provide for his extradition, making it virtually impossible for noriega to be brought to trial
at the same time, the reagan administration is deeply concerned about panama's political stability and has been encouraging noriega and his military allies to withdraw from politics
the administration believes that the security of the panama canal is best assured through elected civilian rule. delvalle is widely viewed as a figurehead president who bows to noriega's wishes
the times account said that under the formula abrams discussed, noriega could move to any country he wished without having to concern himself with the possibility of extradition to the united states
with noriega living in exile, this scenario also could enhance the possibility _ consistent with u.s. objectives _ of an evolution to a civilian-led government in panama
but redman insisted that the administration has no interest in any arrangement for noriega to be exiled in exchange for a drop of the charges
we all see the drug problem of tremendous importance in the united states as well as throughout the hemisphere,'' redman said, reaffirming that the indictments will not be withdrawn

