surgeon general c. everett koop says public health officials agree that heterosexuals are at risk for contracting aids, despite recent published accounts that give the impression heterosexuals are relatively safe
koop said friday that several articles, including one in cosmopolitan magazine, wrongly led women and heterosexual men to believe they are not at risk
the risk is real,'' koop told the house energy and commerce subcommittee on health. ``it is just not true that there is no danger from normal vaginal intercourse. what is unknown is the level of danger. there is always a danger whenever people engage in casual sex outside the marriage relationship, even if their promiscuity is heterosexual.''
as of feb. 15, there were 53,814 cases of acquired immune deficiency syndrome reported to the federal centers for disease control. about 65 percent were in homosexual or bisexual males, and 17 percent were in intravenous drug abusers
while only 4 percent of current aids cases are reported among heterosexuals, koop said that proportion is expected to rise to 5 percent in the 1990s
koop told the subcommittee that medical personnel generally have responded well to the aids crisis. but he said there is a minority of medical personnel who ``refuse not only to treat persons with aids, but also turn away patients alleged to be from population groups identified with those two high-risk behaviors: that is, homosexual and bisexual males and intravenous drug abusers.''
he characterized that behavior as ``unworthy of anyone in the health or social service professions.''
those who turn away aids patients use the excuse that the disease is fatal and contagious, koop said. ``but the plain fact is that the risk of contracting (aids) from an infected patient is extremely small and nearly always preventable.''
of nearly 7 million health professionals in the country, koop said, fewer than a dozen became infected with the aids virus while doing their jobs and, in most cases, that exposure could have been prevented if the person had followed guidelines published five years ago by the cdc
cdc director james mason, another witness, said more than 15 million americans are being tested anonymously each year for aids through blood banks and the military and in 30 communities
he said more anonymous testing should be done to get a better fix on the extent of aids infection in the united states, but he rejected rep. william dannemeyer's idea that anyone coming in contact with the health system be tested
dannemeyer, r-calif., has introduced legislation that would require testing of hospital patients, clinic patients, marriage license applicants and others. he also wants to require reporting by name of any positive test results
mason endorsed the general approach sponsored by subcommittee chairman rep. henry waxman, d-calif., which includes voluntary testing, confidentiality and anti-discrimination protection for those with the disease or virus
where there's worry about confidentiality or discrimination, there's a chilling effect,'' mason said
american military intervention may be needed in colombia to halt the flow of narcotics to u.s. cities, sen. john f. kerry says
we've gotten to the point where we have to be prepared to be tough. we cannot be patsies about this stuff,'' the massachusetts democrat said friday. ``we ought to make it permanently hot for them down there.''
kerry, chairman of the senate foreign relations subcommittee on narcotics and terrorism, said the united states should provide colombia with helicopters, communications equipment and other military systems to combat the region's drug czars. he said an estimated 80 percent of the narcotics entering the united states come from colombia
but the senator added that military assistance may not be enough and that the administration should be willing to send troops to the area, if necessary, to help colombian agents
i'm willing, and i think we ought to consider, the use of our southern command forces to assist in the interdiction effort on a case-by-case basis. they ought to be able to do that because what you have here is literally a paramilitary organization that you're fighting against,'' kerry told reporters
this is a very sophisticated effort we're working against, and if it takes the visibility of our military force ... that's worth it to me,'' he added
last april, 14 u.s. military advisers were sent to bolivia to help train bolivian anti-drug police
in july 1986, the united states sent 175 soldiers provide logistical support for bolivian anti-drug operations. that program ended in november 1986
meanwhile, kerry released a letter to sen. lawton chiles, d-fla., chairman of the senate budget committee, urging the immediate transfer of $50 million from the defense department to the coast guard, which is charged largely with battling drug trafficking at sea
kerry lambasted president reagan for a series of coast guard budget cuts
i'm tired of this phony war on drugs where they talk about it, where they stand nancy (reagan) up at the state of the union message and try to pretend the war on drugs is rampaging across the country, and meanwhile they cut the guts out of the law enforcement effort. that type of hypocrisy has simply got to stop,'' kerry said
he also called for a tightening of banking regulations for cash transactions and increasing penalties for drug trafficking
president reagan and west german chancellor helmut kohl are lauding a western effort to build a common arms control strategy so nato can manage the soviets with ``realism, strength and alliance unity.''
the two leaders ended talks at the white house on friday with a pledge to intensify the effort at a nato summit march 2-3
what we need now is an overall concept covering the whole field of disarmament, and there i do not see any difference between us and the americans,'' kohl told reporters before heading back to bonn
we agreed that we must deal with the soviet union from a position of realism, strength and alliance unity,''
since reaching agreement with the soviets to eliminate land-based nuclear missiles with ranges between 300 miles and 3,125 miles, the united states and its allies have been trying to set goals for further talks with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev and his aides
we want to get out of a situation where we merely react to proposals which have been submitted by gorbachev. we want to put down proposals and let him react to them,'' kohl said
secretary of state george p. shultz, who attended the white house meeting, left later in the day for another round of negotiations with the soviets in moscow. kohl said shultz pledged to convey to the soviets the west german concern about ethnic germans facing discrimination in soviet bloc countries
nato already has agreed on a first priority of a u.s.-soviet reduction in long-range missiles and bombers, while seeking cuts in conventional and chemical weapons
we were in agreement that all these disarmament questions and issues as well as the necessary measures to preserve our common security should be combined in form and overall concept for our alliance,'' kohl said
each of the 16 allies, depending on its politics and geography, has different interests to advance, and one of the key differences was reflected in comments after kohl's meeting with reagan
west germany is particularly eager for negotiations to reduce tactical nuclear weapons _ those with ranges below 300 miles _ and wants those talks included in any conferences that deal with conventional weapons. kohl, whose country would be threatened by such weapons if a war broke out in europe, reiterated the desire for quick and comprehensive talks on the short-range systems
the united states, which believes tactical nuclear weapons are necessary to deter a conventional attack, wants to defer negotiations to reduce the short-range systems. indeed, it is working on plans to modernize these weapons, with nato approval
during kohl's visit, the two sides sought to minimize the importance of the disagreement. kohl said he did not favor the elimination of the tactical nuclear weapons: artillery shells and short-range missiles
he does not seek a ``denuclearized zone, least of all in europe,'' kohl said
kohl was asked at the news conference about concerns that modernization of short-range weapons would touch off protests like those that rocked europe in the early 1980s after nato decided to deploy intermediate-range weapons
i don't share that fear,'' kohl said
in its efforts to play down the issue, the reagan administration noted during kohl's visit that further study is needed before the most powerful of the short-range systems _ a missile to replace the 75-mile-range lance _ is deployed and it may not go into operation before 1995
rep. newt gingrich, contending that published reports have outlined ``clear violations of house rules'' by speaker jim wright, says he intends to ask the house ethics committee next month to launch a formal investigation
gingrich, r-ga., told a news conference friday that the house needs to know the truth about the allegations of corruption that have been leveled at wright, d-texas, in news accounts over the past decade
we're going to have to at least at a minimum insist that we find out what the truth is, and on march 3, i intend to create that opportunity,'' gingrich said
wright's office did not return a telephone call friday seeking comment on gingrich's plan to seek an ethics committee investigation
gingrich said two specific published reports about wright provide clear evidence that he violated house rules. one involved wright's failure since 1980 to file the required financial disclosure reports for a company in which he is a partner
the other involved 55 percent royalties wright received for a book published by a friend whose printing company worked for wright's campaign committee. house rules prohibit members from receiving royalties in excess of ``the usual and customary value for such services,'' gingrich said, and most authors receive royalties of 6 percent to 8 percent
gingrich said the ethics panel also should investigate wright's connection to texas savings and loan association officials who are under investigation by federal authorities
the democratic congressional campaign committee last month accused gingrich and a political action committee he heads of mail fraud and asked the postal service to investigate. the dccc said the pac collected more than $200,000 through mail solicitations of contributions for conservative candidates, but provided only $3,000 to such candidates
gingrich, who has denied the accusations, said friday the dccc complaint was a ``smoke screen'' designed to discredit him politically so he could not pursue the ethics complaints against wright
under house rules, any member can ask the ethics panel to investigate another member. the committee, composed of six democrats and six republicans, can reject such a request only by a majority vote
gingrich said it would be ``inconceivable'' that the committee would refuse to investigate the allegations. but if that happens, he said he intends to force the issue on the house floor with a series of privileged votes that could tie up house business
gingrich tried unsuccessfully last year to persuade the house to create an outside commission to investigate ethics complaints against wright and other democratic leaders
he said he was announcing his intention to seek an investigation of wright now to give other house members time to familiarize themselves with the long list of allegations
gingrich has criticized the ethics committee in the past for its lenient treatment of democrats accused of wrongdoing. but he said friday he has more confidence in the panel after its recent votes to reprimand one democratic congressman and recommend the expulsion of another
he said he believes the panel can conduct a fair investigation of wright if it will agree to hire an outside attorney acceptable to both republican and democratic house leaders and to complete its investigation before congress adjourns for the year
a proposed merger between two of the nation's largest manufacturers of glass containers remains on hold today in the wake of a ruling by a federal appeals court
late friday afternoon, the u.s. court of appeals issued an administrative stay of a lower court decision that would have cleared the way for the merger between owens-illinois inc. and brockway inc
earlier in the day, the federal trade commission had asked the appeals court to extend until next tuesday a restraining order blocking the merger until the agency could decide whether to appeal a ruling by u.s. district court judge joyce hens green
on thursday, green refused the ftc's request for a preliminary injunction, ruling that the ftc had not proven the deal would harm competition
ftc spokeswoman susan tichnor said the agency will have until next tuesday to file an appeal and that the court will issue a decision sometime after owens-illinois files a response wednesday
attorneys for owens-illinois said there is no excuse for the ftc's ``unusual filing'' friday to keep the merger on hold until the agency can decide whether to appeal
the ftc has been acutely aware since the beginning of this case of the extreme time sensitivity surrounding the merger and, in that regard, has had ample time to prepare for the possibility of a decision adverse to it,'' said paul warnke, an attorney for owens-illinois
last september, the toledo, ohio-based owens-illinois proposed to buy brockway, of jacksonville, fla., for $750 million, or $60 per share
the merger would make the combined company the largest manufacturer of glass containers in the industry. the nation's top manufacturer is anchor glass container corp., which controls 23.7 percent of the market
the ftc has said the merger might violate federal antitrust laws by substantially reducing competition in the glass container industry and creating conditions for price discrimination. it wants to halt the merger until it can conduct an administrative review of the proposal
but green accepted the argument advanced by the two manufacturers that competition from the plastics and metal-packaging industry will hold down prices
peace talks between nicaragua's leftist sandinista government and contra rebels are right back where they began _ mired in a dispute over what comes first, democracy or a truce
cardinal miguel obando y bravo, the nicaraguan roman catholic church leader who has been mediating the negotiations, abruptly suspended the latest round of talks friday, indirectly blaming the sandinistas for their failure
obando y bravo said he was disappointed that both sides had not accepted, at least in principle, a proposal he put forth thursday in an attempt to break a deadlock that arose in the first hours of the talks
that impasse stemmed from what the cardinal said was the inability of the two sides to agree on whether they should negotiate a cease-fire to obtain democracy, or negotiate democracy to obtain a cease-fire
more than 40,000 people have been killed since november 1981, when the contras began fighting the sandinista government
the cardinal's plan called on the contras to accept a truce in exchange for four major concessions by the government. they were concessions the contras have long sought, and they quickly accepted the proposal in principle
but victor hugo tinoco, nicaragua's deputy foreign minister, said the cardinal suspended the talks in mid-afternoon friday before he could deliver his government's formal, written response, which also conditionally accepted the plan
the confusion apparently arose because president daniel ortega initially instructed his negotiators to reject obando y bravo's proposal as unsuitable for discussion at talks the sandinista leader felt should be aimed solely at the mechanics of achieving a cease-fire
the government apparently changed its mind later and authorized tinoco to accept conditionally the cardinal's plan. by then, obando y bravo had suspended the negotiations without setting a time or place for a new round of talks
contra negotiators announced their tentative acceptance of obando y bravo's proposal at a news conference thursday night. shortly afterward, tinoco told reporters the plan was ``interesting and constructive,'' but needed clarification
paul reichler, a washington, d.c., attorney advising the sandinistas, said ortega advised the government negotiators during a telephone conference later thursday evening to reject obando y bravo's proposal
reichler quoted ortega as saying that if obando y bravo felt the issues he raised in his proposal were of vital importance to the nicaraguan people, the president would discuss them with the cardinal personally
but reichler said ortega's initial reaction was that he would not discuss political issues at the bargaining table with the contras _ a position the nicaraguan leader has long held
obando y bravo's plan called for the contras to move into unspecified ``enclaves or zones'' with their arms and equipment during a 30-day truce, during which talks would continue toward a more lasting cease-fire
in exchange, the cardinal called on the nicaraguan government to:
_grant a ``full, general'' amnesty to the several thousand political prisoners in nicaraguan jails, including members of the national guard of former dictator gen. anastasio somoza, whom the sandinistas overthrew in 1979
_permit ``unrestricted'' freedom of the press, a right now granted only to a few mass media, including the opposition newspaper la prensa and radio catolica, the voice of the catholic church
_``reconsider'' mandatory military draft law, which has provoked violent disturbances by youths and mothers of draft-age people in several nicaraguan cities
_reopen a dialogue with its internal opposition, including 14 dissident political parties and a coalition of business, labor and political groups known as the democratic coordinating council. those talks broke down late last year
tinoco's initial response and the government's later written statement said the obando y bravo plan needed clarification on the size and location of the cease-fire zones, when the truce would start, how it would be verified and how the contras would be supplied during the cessation of hostilities
reichler said ortega suggested that roger fisher, a harvard professor who heads the center for conflict resolution in boston, draw up a new cease-fire proposal, drawing on plans already submitted by both sides
but in announcing suspension of the talks, obando y bravo issued a communique rejecting fisher's participation in the negotiations. the communique said such work was the proper task of each side's technical advisers
a european ariane rocket will launch an american and a french satellite into orbit next month from the program's french guiana space center, the commercial arm of the european space agency announced
the march 11 launch from the south american base is to be ariane's 21st and the first of eight planned for this year
it is to lift the american spacenet 3-r satellite and the french telecom 1c into orbit, arianespace said in its announcement friday
the 20th ariane shot on nov. 20 placed the west german satellite tv-sat1 into orbit. the launch was flawless, but one of the satellite's solar panels failed to deploy and it has not been able to carry out its function of direct television broadcasts
the u.s. space shuttle program was suspended after the january 1986 challenger disaster, making the ariane program the west's only regular vehicle for the lucrative satellite-launching market
siberia is the stroke capital of the world, and heavy drinking and cold weather could be partly to blame, researchers say
soviet stroke data, gathered as part of a world health organization program, were released for the first time friday at a stroke conference sponsored by the american heart association
we were surprised,'' said dr. kjell asplund. ``we thought that china and japan would be the higest.''
the study showed that canada and denmark are the safest places to live, at least as far as stroke is concerned, although the stroke rate is low throughout most of north america, southern europe and australia
asplund, a researcher at umea university in umea, sweden, said the data suggest that strokes must have several causes. while racial differences may play a role, they don't explain all of the variations in the risk of stroke around the world
the study found that in siberia, the stroke rate was 119 for every 100,000 men and 107 for every 100,000 women. these figures were the highest in the world and significantly ahead of china, the country with the second highest stroke rate
strokes are also common in japan, but data collected there were so sparse they were not included in the analysis
strokes among men are least common in canada, where they strike 21 in 100,000. in women they are least frequent in denmark, where they occur in 8 in 100,000
asked why strokes are so common in siberia, asplund said, ``at this point, we can only guess. we know that alcohol consumption is very high. high alcohol use among men is associated with a high risk for stroke. i also suspect that there are some climate factors involved.''
although there are exceptions, such as canada, he said it appears that strokes are more common in cold climates than in milder places. he noted that people are more likely to suffer strokes in northern sweden than in southern sweden and in scotland than in england
some experts suspect that asians are more likely to suffer strokes, at least in part, because of racial differences. however, asplund said that most people in siberia moved there from european parts of the soviet union
it's not only a racial thing,'' he said. ``it must have other determinants as well. the goal of this study is to find the determinants of the huge variations in stroke around the world.''
he said the researchers will be trying to learn why the stroke rate is falling rapidly in the united states, while it is stable or increasing in many other countries
the study found that in most places, strokes are more common in men than in women. the only exceptions to this were sweden, canada and israel, where strokes are slightly more common among women
the 10-year project, called monitoring of trends and determinants of cardiovascular disease, or monica, is being conducted in 26 countries and will conclude in 1994
contra rebels claim they downed a soviet-made sandinista air force helicopter in eastern nicaragua with a u.s.-made redeye missile this week
the rebels, in a statement released in san jose friday, said they used the heat-seeking anti-aircraft weapon last sunday to shoot down the mi-17 helicopter in chontales province
in the nicaraguan capital of managua, a defense ministry spokesman denied the rebel claim, saying mechanical failure caused the crash. the spokesman demanded anonymity
the defense ministry had reported on monday that seven people were killed in the crash, which occurred near the village of santo tomas, about 120 miles east of managua. the contras claimed 15 people
sandinista authorities said the helicopter was carrying new currency to the region to be exchanged for old bills. the contra statement said the rebels recovered 10 million new cordobas in the crash
the contras say they downed 26 helicopters with redeye missiles last year. foreign military observers put the number at a dozen. the sandinistas admitted to six
mexico and panama should not be penalized by the united states despite their failure to take adequate steps to control drug trafficking, according to a draft state department report
the new york times, citing unidentified administration officials, reported saturday that the report, prepared by the bureau of international narcotics matters, said ``other national interests'' warrant that the countries not be penalized
under a 1986 law, the president certifies countries that are ``fully cooperating'' in cracking down on the drug trade. those that don't qualify lose military and economic aid, trade preferences, loans and other economic advantages
the report charged that panama and mexico haven't made adequate progress in combating the drug trade but said they should be certified, the times reported
panama's military leader, gen. manuel antonio noriega, and some of his aides were indicted this month on drug and racketeering charges
it's ridiculous and stupid, absolutely ludicrous, and sends the wrong signals to both countries,'' sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., said of the report's recommendation
sen. john kerry, d-mass., said, ``it is totally outrageous, particularly in the case of panama.''
the report is provisional and subject to clearance by other governmental agencies and regional assistant secretaries of state. it would then be submitted to the secretary of state and the president, who is to announce his decision march 1
the report also recommended decertification of iran, afghanistan, paraguay, syria and laos. it said colombia, the bahamas and bolivia should be certified
three hospitals turned down the liver of a brain-dead baby whose body was being maintained on life-support systems to preserve his organs for transplant, officials said friday
baby john, who was born tuesday with most of his brain missing, a condition known as anencephaly, was pronounced brain dead thursday at loma linda university medical center
no other cases in which anencephalics have been kept on life-support for organ transplant have been announced in the united states, although dr. leonard bailey, chief of loma linda's heart transplant program, last year suggested there have been such infants
doctors plan to maintain the body on life support for up to seven days in hope of finding recipients for its organs, hospital spokeswoman anita rockwell said
one liver transplant candidate in pittsburgh was not an appropriate match and another in that city became infected, delaying any transplant, ms. rockwell said
a medical center in wisconsin also was unable to accept the liver for another candidate because it had committed itself to do another transplant and could not perform two in one day, ms. rockwell said
ucla medical center in los angeles turned rejected the liver as not an ideal candidate for their recipient, ms. rockwell said
anencephaly usually is fatal within days after birth. an anencephalic infant's organs can be transplanted only if organ damage is prevented by maintaining the infant on life-support from birth. debt swap</head>
mexico has asked the united states to give favorable treatment to banks that take part in the government's new program to exchange part of its foreign debt for long-term bonds, the treasury department said
finance secretary gustavo petricioli said in a statement that he discussed the plan with u.s. officials during president reagan's recent meeting with president miguel de la madrid in mazatlan, mexico
the mexican delegation,'' the statement said, ``emphasized that it is necessary that all parties involved continue working in the search for deeper and more permanent solutions to the problem of the foreign debt and financing.''
it said mexican officials acknowledged the u.s. help to mexico in restructuring foreign debt and in fashioning mexico's new debt exchange program. mexico has a foreign debt of $105 billion, the second highest in the developing world after brazil
the new program involves exchanging some of the debt mexico owes foreign commercial bankers for new, 20-year bonds that will be issued by the government
mexico has set feb. 26 as the date for an auction of the bonds
the bonds will be backed by $10 billion worth of special securities to be issued this year by the u.s. government. mexico is expected to pay about $2 billion for the 20-year, u.s. zero-coupon bonds, which pay no interest but are issued at a sharp discount of their face value
the government statement said petricioli asked u.s. officials at the mazatlan meeting ``that they give the most favorable treatment possible to the banks that decide to participate in this operation.''
some u.s. banks reportedly have expressed concern about taking part in the program because they are unhappy that mexico will continue obtaining loans at 100 percent of their value while paying back, through the bond program, its old loans at about half their value
they also are reportedly reluctant to accept losses of 50 percent or so on the loans entered into years ago, and worry about government regulations concerning accounting for the securities on their books
most of mexico's about 600 creditor banks have authorized the government to go ahead with the auction, which would apply to $51 billion of the foreign debt
under the program, banks would exchange their old debt for the new bonds, letting mexico recover 52 cents or so for each dollar in the secondary market. that means that mexico could retire part of its debt for half its face value
by reducing its debt, the government will also pare the amount of interest it pays each year on the loans. mexico has annual interest charges of $8 billion to $9 billion
heavy-metal rock group motley crue warned fans not to imitate its show stunts after a 12-year-old boy set his blue jeans on fire while trying to copy the group's ``human torch'' video act
bryan tucker, who had burns over 10 percent of his body, was reported in good condition today at memorial hospital after he poured rubbing alcohol on his jeans and torched them. he put the flames out in a filled bathtub
various of motley crue's show stunts require special equipment, clothing and other materials ... and should not be attempted at home,'' said the statement released thursday by management firm mcghee entertainment inc. in los angeles
bryan's mother, wendy tucker, said he was in great pain but that motley crue was not to blame for her son's experiment at their home wednesday
in my day, my mom would not let me watch superman, because he jumped out of buildings,'' she said. ``it's just a different time.''
