a nationwide lobbying campaign seeking a pardon for lt. col. oliver north for his involvement in the iran-contra affair has been launched by a conservative group that is working with activists from the rev. sun myung moon's unification church, the washington post reported saturday
we think north is a hero and he ought to be treated as such,'' said robert grant, chairman of the lobbying group christian voice and president of the new american freedom coalition
the coalition has extensive links to moon's unification church movement, according to the newspaper. it said bo hi pak, moon's top deputy and president of the washington times, which is owned by moon, was instrumental in founding the group and phillip sanchez, one of pak's chief political aides and president of causa usa, is a member of the coalition's national policy board
grant said causa has given the coalition a network of activists throughout the united states _ most of whom are unification church members _ to help build local support
however, the coalition's literature never mentions the unification church and pak's name is not included on the group's five-member board of directors, the post said
the coalition, chaired by former reps. richard ichord, d-mo., and bob wilson, r-calif., recently sent more than a million letters asking recipients to sign a ``pardon colonel north'' petition to president reagan
north is a target of the iran-contra investigation being conducted by independent counsel lawrence walsh but has not been indicted
michael dukakis, trying to add some midwestern momentum to his win in new hampshire, was pushed by democratic presidential rivals to defend his economic policies and complained during a debate that ``my name was taken in vain.''
missouri rep. richard gephardt, another democratic front-runner, also found himself in the cross fire friday during the latest debate of democratic presidential candidates, as jesse jackson asked if the missouri congressman was ``proud of your vote for the reagan tax cut in 1981.''
gephardt and dukakis, the governor of massachusetts, were the biggest targets in a debate that was freewheeling but less fiesty than a jangling exchange among the candidates in texas the day before
the st. paul debate came as the focus of the presidential campaign shifted briefly away from the super tuesday battlefield mainly in the south and returned to the midwest, where minnesota and south dakota hold contests on tuesday
though the delegates at stake from those two contests pale next to those to be allocated in the south, the closely bunched candidates are looking for a midwestern edge to propel them toward the march 8 super tuesday primaries and caucuses
in the latest debates, the candidates tried to block gephardt and dukakis from gaining more momentum. gephardt was hit on trade and taxes, while dukakis was forced to defend his budget plans
gephardt defended his overall tax voting record, saying most of the tax cut derided by jackson ``went to ordinary people.''
that was the trigger of this whole deficit crisis,'' jackson countered
and dukakis agreed: ``it wasn't just a bad vote as a matter of tax policy, it was the worst trade bill ever passed.''
the minnesota debate drew five of the six democratic contenders. tennessee sen. albert gore jr. was absent
dukakis fired one of the most direct shots of the debate at gephardt's trade policies, warning that ``we've got to do more than wave a fist at our foreign competitors.''
but gephardt queried: ``why is everyone defending unfair trade practices?''
after the candidates' exchange was interrupted by a moderator, gephardt predicted ``we'll never finish on trade.''
dukakis complained that ``my name was taken in vain'' by gary hart, who demanded to know why dukakis had not followed his example and released a budget proposal
the reason my colleagues have not put out budgets is because they don't want to tell the american people the facts,'' hart said
i'm the only person on this platform who has balanced a budget,'' retorted dukakis
turning to sen. paul simon, hart asked, ``why don't you put your budget out, paul?''
when a moderator interrupted the exchange with a joke about ``exchange your budgets tomorrow,'' hart complained: ``i thought that's what we were here to debate.''
the candidates paid homage to former vice president walter f. mondale, one of the ceremonial sponsors of the debate, with gephardt saying that mondale's call for a tax hike during his failed 1984 democratic presidential bid was ``to his everlasting credit.''
jackson noted that this campaign is the first in 20 years that minnesotans don't have a favorite son candidate to vote for
don't despair, let me be your favorite son,'' jackson said
i want to be your other favorite son'' interjected simon
friday's debate was sponsored by a series of groups, including the st. paul pioneer press dispatch and radio and television station wcco in minneapolis
marcel piattier cleared omaha beach of german mines the day after the allies stormed it on d-day, and went on to make a career out of defusing or detonating unexploded world war ii bombs
on friday, the 66-year-old piattier retired with a bang, safely exploding a 300-pound english bomb found in january in this town 150 miles north of paris
the live bomb couldn't be moved and was detonated near the center of town, causing no damage
in his last year as head of the regional bomb and mine clearing service, the man considered the dean of the 25 civil defense explosive experts in france was kept busy
in the second half of 1987, we received 560 calls to neutralize bombs found by individuals,'' piattier said
he says his work in his later years was safer than it used to be
in 1945, we probed mine fields with bayonettes,'' he recalled. ``in two years, 27 french mine clearers died, and that's not counting the german prisoners of war we used.''
to determine if the bomb detonated friday was still live, piattier used sophisticated x-ray equipment, similar to that used at nuclear power plants, to see inside to the strike-pin
normandy was the scene of the allied invasion in 1944 and saw intense fighting that left behind thousands of bombs and mines that often turn up unexpectedly. in the past year, bombs have been found by workers digging the english channel tunnel and near a hospital in caen
the most dangerous explosives still scattered throughout the verdant countryside are small anti-personnel bombs dropped in bunches from german planes
a woman had her leg torn away in june and a child died in september from these bombs,'' said piattier, who added that he has found ``several thousand'' bombs and mines in four decades of work
piattier's first task was clearing the german mines from omaha beach the day after u.s. forces landed on june 6, 1944
i was the first french soldier on the beach and even before the second soldier arrived i had found hundreds and hundreds of mines,'' he said
piattier was lucky to reach retirement. in the past two years, six of his colleagues have died in the line of duty, he said
my wife is happy. she thinks i'll be safe now at home, but i'm not so sure,'' he said. ``i'd like to stay in contact with the service and help out when i can.''
carrie,'' the $7 million broadway-bound musical based on the stephen king novel, received tepid reviews following its premiere at the royal shakespeare theater in stratford-upon-avon
jack tinker in the daily mail called the show, scheduled to open april 27 at new york's virginia theater, ``an expensive mess.''
but he praised 17-year-old newcomer linzi hateley as the telekinetic carrie of the title, a traumatized adolescent played by sissy spacek in the 1976 film version of the book
i hope sincerely that broadway takes miss hateley to its heart. it can take the rest wherever it pleases,'' tinker wrote of thursday's performance
milton shulman in the standard thought the show, presented in association with the royal shakespeare company, lacked ``that element of supernatural awe'' that made the movie memorable
he added: ``if `carrie' has to be transformed into a musical, (director) terry hands has probably done it as well as it can be done. but one has to ask whether the idea and the production were really necessary.''
originally mooted for broadway several years back, the show is now headed for new york in a cast made up equally of britons and americans under a special arrangement with the actors' union, equity
the behind-the-scenes talent is of mixed nationality, as well. choreographer debbie allen, composer michael gore and lyricist dean pitchford are all american. director hands and his design team _ ralph koltai and alexander reid _ are british
michael coveney in the financial times said the musical was ``enjoyable in a masochistic way,'' but lamented hands' participation in ``an utter cultural vacuum of dance studio robotics with a hint of cultural and classical pretensions.''
coveney and the other critics all had kind words for broadway veteran barbara cook, who plays carrie's mother margaret, the religious fanatic played on-screen by piper laurie
coveney said the 60-year-old miss cook was ``superb,'' and tinker called her ``broadway's reclaimed heroine.''
irving wardle in the times of london said the voices of linzi hateley and barbara cook provided ``the most thrilling sounds of the evening.''
carrie'' is the second mother-daughter musical to open back-to-back locally. wednesday night saw the london debut at the cambridge theater of ``the rink,'' the 1984 broadway flop that starred chita rivera and liza minnelli
the london bow received mixed marks for the material _ a maudlin reconciliation drama set in an abandoned roller skating rink _ but praise for the two leads: josephine blake and diane langton
president spyros kyprianou refused to back either presidential candidate in sunday's runoff elections after he lost a bid for a third term, throwing wide open cyprus' most hotly contested vote
kyprianou's centrist democratic party, diko, said friday that it did not agree with the stands of either glafcos clerides, leader of the right-wing democratic rally party, or millionaire businessman george vassiliou, an independent backed by the powerful communist party, akel
that left kyprianou's 91,000 supporters free to vote either way
diko's surprise move came after days of backroom bargaining. rivals were eliminated in a first-round ballot last sunday
kyprianou's third-place showing last sunday took him out of the race
the small socialist party, edek, announced it was putting the 9.4 percent of the vote it won sunday behind vassiliou in a leftist alliance
on paper, that guarantees vassiliou just under 40 percent of the vote when this mediterranean island's 363,000-strong greek cypriot electorate votes. vassilou gathered 30.11 percent of last sunday's vote
the conservative, pro-western clerides, 68, a veteran political warhorse, topped sunday's poll with 33.32 percent. but he will have to secure at least two-thirds of the votes kyprianou won to edge ahead of vassiliou this sunday
the election has developed into a straight left-right battle. for the first time in a cypriot presidential contest since independence from britain in 1960, the outcome cannot be predicted
political analysts believe the diko vote will split roughly down the middle, with just a slight swing toward clerides. that may not be enough to ensure him victory
the election has been dominated by the partition issue
cyprus has been divided since the turkish army invaded in july 1974 after a short-lived coup by militant greek cypriot supporters of union with greece
the turks overran the northern third of the island. the turkish cypriot minority declared a breakaway republic in 1983
clerides has pledged that if elected, he will form an all-party government of national unity to revive deadlocked negotiations between cyprus' greek and turkish communities to reunite the island
seeking to strengthen his national unity strategy, clerides announced in a television debate thursday night that he was resigning as leader of democratic rally to head into sunday's showdown poll as an independent
vassiliou dismissed that as an electoral ploy and pointed out that the other three parties have rejected clerides' coalition proposal as unfeasible
clerides and vassiliou, 56, earlier concentrated in knocking kyprianou out of the race and blocking his election for a third five-year term. with kyprianou out of the way, they are now slamming each other
clerides is accused of being a ``right-wing, anti-labor reactionary'' who heads a party that harbors the extremists who were behind the ill-starred 1974 coup that briefly ousted cyprus' first president, the late archbishop makarios
clerides rejects the charge and accuses vassiliou, a self-made millionaire making his first foray into politics, of being a communist pawn
both men, however, support the unconditional resumption of negotiations with the turkish side
kyprianou had insisted that talks should resume only after the withdrawal of the 35,000 turkish troops and 65,000 settlers shipped to northern cyprus from the turkish mainland
clerides and vassiliou also demand a turkish withdrawal, but do not make this a precondition for talks that have been stalled for the last three years
