senior conservatives are growing uneasy about the people's party backing president kurt waldheim, who for the first time in an opinion poll did not muster the support of a majority of austrian voters
the daily salzburger nachrichten today published a survey showing 45 percent of those who responded to the poll favored waldheim's resignation and 42 percent wanted him to stay
it said 31 percent of the respondents said they would vote for waldheim ``by all means'' if presidential elections were held, while 42 percent replied they would ``by no means'' elect him
the newspaper said 522 people were polled on feb. 18-19, but it was not known how representative was the sample nor give the margin of error
in previous polls, waldheim always had obtained the support of a majority of respondents
in an interview published in today's issue of the vienna conservative daily die presse, helmut kukacka, general secretary of the people's party, was quoted as saying that, for now at least, the party would give waldheim full backing
but waldheim must work ``to reduce his credibility deficits by an information strategy,'' the newspaper reported kukacka as saying
early this summer the party will decide whether it ``makes sense'' to further stand by waldheim or to ``signal a certain distance,'' kukacka said in the interview
kukacka pledged his party would do everything to strengthen the president's position, but noted waldheim has a responsibility to the people's party and to austria, ``so that all of us get out'' of the crisis
waldheim is not a member of the people's party but received its nomination in the june 8, 1986, presidential runoff, which he won with almost 54 percent of the vote
in a late friday night television interview, kukacka confirmed his comments published by die presse
the federal president has not yet sufficiently responded to the contents of the report of the historians' commission, while, on the other hand, a pressure of opinion, as it were ... was generated in the whole world,'' he said on the television
the historians' report presented no clear evidence to back allegations waldheim was directly involved in war crimes when he was a lieutenant with the german army in the occupied balkans
but the report left open the question of whether he was guilty of any crime. it said he was ``in close proximity'' to nazi atrocities, knew about them and did nothing to prevent them
the president must put forward all his arguments to restore his credibility, said kukacka
after a conservative national leadership caucus thursday, people's party chairman alois mock, waldheim's main defender, said the president's decision to remain in office must be respected
the conservative daily oberoesterreichische nachrichten in friday editions said segments of the people's party ``are crumbling away'' over waldheim
the socialist party, senior partner in the government coalition with the conservatives, has refrained from openly calling on waldheim to step down. but party officials have made clear they see his resignation as the best solution to the standoff
in an interview published in today's editions of the west german conservative newspaper die welt, waldheim said, ``(my) resignation from the office would throw the country into chaos.''
he said resigning would give the impression that ``not austrian voters but foreign media and groups decide who may be austrian head of state.''
mock, who is vice chancellor and foreign minister in the coalition government, apparently is coming under increasing pressure from waldheim critics in his party
mock is the keystone in this issue. he cannot move any more. if he were gone it would be easier'' to resolve the controversy over waldheim, a high-ranking people's party official told the associated press after the party caucus
meanwhile, public protests against waldheim continued throughout austria. those calling for his resignation friday included actors of a vienna theater and civil servants in four ministries
various petitions with signatures calling on waldheim to quit are circulating in vienna and elsewhere, including two separate lists of conservative and socialist university professors.  1 graf after 3rd graf to add quote from willett.</note>
a small plane crashed in dense fog and driving rain friday night in a wooded area near atlantic city, killing at least six people, officials said. there were no survivors
the twin-engine piper najavo en route from norwood, mass., to pomona went down about sometime after 10:10 p.m., when its radar signal was lost, said anthony willett, a federal aviation administration spokesman
willett said at least six people were killed. it was not immediately known how many people were aboard the plane, which went down about two miles from atlantic city airport, he said
i don't have a passenger manifest in front of me, so i can't be sure,'' he said. ``it's pouring rain down here, the plane is in the woods, it's just hard to be sure.''
willett said that the plane, 32 feet long with a 40-foot wing span, is of a type commonly used by commuter airlines, but that the aircraft may have been privately owned
the hour-long search for the wreckage was hampered by fog and rain, he said
mario vazquez rana, the mexican newspaper publisher, has announced he has sold his control of united press international. he said the former president of financial news network will take over direct operational control of the company
the transaction took the form of a sale by the mexican media executive of an ``irrevocable proxy'' of his stock ownership in upi to wnw group inc
upi, in an announcement moved on its news wires friday night, said the transfer is effective immediately
the announcement said vazquez rana relinquished his control over the news service in return for ``present and future financial considerations totaling more than $55 million.''
vazquez rana bought upi for $41 million in june 1986, ending bankruptcy court proceedings that began in april 1985, when the news service filed for protection from creditors
the announcement did not identify the owners of wnw. upi spokesman christopher smith said he believed wnw group inc. is an independent company with no connection to fnn but said he did not really know anything about them at this point
an irrevocable proxy represents a transfer of voting power represented by the ownership shares but not the shares themselves
smith said that vazquez rana ``considers his task of investment in upi completed at this time.''
smith said additional details would be released at a news conference, probably on monday
the agreement under which vazquez rana acquired upi after creditors approved a reorganization plan limited his ability to sell his interest in upi without first giving an employees stock ownership plan the right of first refusal during a 60-day period
the upi announcement said that the new president of the news service will be paul steinle, former president of financial news network, a 24-hour cable tv distributor of business news. the announcement said he would have ``total operational control of day-to-day management.''
the announcement identified the chairman of wnw group inc. as dr. earl brian, but provided no further identification
vazquez rana's statement said, ``this step was necessary because i could not devote a sufficient amount of time to hands-on management. i am pleased that in this agreement, we have assured the continuation of a venerable world news gathering and independent journalistic organization.''
in addition to steinle and brian, the upi announcement also listed three directors of wnw group inc. they are j. alexander mcmahon, chairman and professor of the health services administration department at duke university; james thistle, director of the school of journalism at the college of communications at boston university; and erik hendricks, executive director of the pennsylvania society for the prevention of cruelty to animals and a former journalist
three hospitals have turned down the liver of a brain-dead baby whose body was being maintained on life-support machines today, and tests indicated the organ was failing, a hospital spokeswoman said
the 7-pound infant known as baby john was born tuesday with most of its brain missing, and was pronounced dead two days later at loma linda university medical center
the baby was the first brain-absent infant in the nation to be placed on artificial life support to keep its organs healthy for transplant, hospital officials said. doctors had planned to maintain the body for up to seven days, but a blood test friday ``suggests that his liver is failing,'' hospital spokeswoman anita rockwell said
one prospective candidate in pittsburgh was not an appropriate match and another in the same hospital became infected, delaying any possible transplant, she said friday
a medical center in wisconsin also was unable to accept the liver for another candidate because they were committed to another transplant and could not do two in one day, ms. rockwell said
the doctors in wisconsin have refused the liver pending further studies,'' the spokeswoman said
ucla medical center in los angeles turned down the liver because they feel it is not an ideal candidate for their recipient, ms. rockwell said
baby john was born with only a brain stem, a condition known as anencephaly that usually is fatal within days of birth. an infant's healthy organs can be transplanted only if organ damage is prevented by maintaining the infant on life support from birth
loma linda is the nation's only medical center to experiment with using anencephalics as organ donors
the air force, concerned that it's losing too many pilots to higher-paying commercial airlines, is considering a bonus program to encourage its aviators to stick with the military
air force secretary edward c. aldridge said friday that while the details haven't been worked out, ``basically we would pay pilots something on the order of $9,000 to $12,000 per year for signing up for a period of time as bonuses to the basic pay that they would have.''
the $54 million bonus program is needed because stepped-up hiring by commercial airlines has caused the re-enlistment rate for military pilots to drop steadily, aldridge said at a news conference
whatever the air force recommends still would have to be approved by congress
the government's latest aviation forecast predicts that passenger travel via commuter aircraft will increase sharply in the coming years, outpacing growth in travel on commercial jetliners
in a forecast released friday, the federal aviation administration said commuter planes are expected to carry 58 million people annually by 1999, up from 27 million people last year
the number of people flying commercial jetliners is expected to grow from about 445 million passengers in 1987 to nearly 765 million in 1999
the faa forecast said air traffic controllers will be handling a third more planes in 1999 than they do now
an organization that represents foreign service officers is asking a federal judge to halt the government's practice of making some employees sign agreements not to disclose classified information
the american foreign service association filed a motion friday in u.s. district court for a preliminary injunction to force secretary of state george shultz to stop ordering state department employees to sign the non-disclosure forms
the injunction also would direct cia director william webster and steven garfinkel, head of the information security oversight office, to order other federal agencies to stop forcing employees to sign the forms
critics in congress contend the forms violate the first amendment rights of government employees
the justice department says it won't join in negotiating any additional settlements for the families of the astronauts killed in the challenger shuttle crash
the department, which negotiated settlements with four of the seven families in december 1986, feels it would be unfair to contribute to any settlements higher than those agreed to in 1986 and that the government has no legal liability in the accident, department spokeswoman amelia brown said friday
last week, the father and brother of mission specialist judith a. resnik signed an agreement with shuttle contractor morton thiokol inc. for payment of from $1.5 million to $2.5 million. the justice department declined to participate in the negotiations leading to that settlement
resnik's relatives weren't involved in the 1986 settlement
if soviet troops withdraw from afghanistan before there is an interim coalition government in place, rival afghan factions could become embroiled in unending civil strife, pakistan's acting foreign minister warned
in our opinion, the way things are being worked out by the soviets, it is going to lead to a bloodbath,'' the diplomat, zain noorani, told a news conference in london friday
he said hundreds of thousands of afghans could be killed if a political settlement does not precede a soviet departure, and called on the west to press moscow for an agreement on an interim government
president mohammad zia ul-haq's government in islamabad wants a transition government in kabul, the afghan capital, before it will sign an agreement leading to soviet withdrawal and the return home of more than two million afghan refugees now living in pakistan
noorani said that without an interim coalition government, islamabad believes the refugees will not return to afghanistan
we anticipate that under such circumstances more refugees will be coming into pakistan from afghanistan,'' he said
noorani, who met with foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe earlier friday, denied pakistan was trying to sabotage the chances of an agreement at talks in geneva between pakistan and afghanistan on how to end the conflict
he said islamabad wants soviet forces to leave, but also wants a lasting settlement
noorani said afghan guerrilla leaders and refugee and emigre representatives on monday would propose what he called a detailed framework of a coalition government
earlier this month, mikhail s. gorbachev offered to begin withdrawing the estimated 115,000 soviet troops in afghanistan on may 15 if pakistan signs an accord at the next session of the u.n.-sponsored peace talks in geneva that begin march 2
but gorbachev also said the soviets would not attempt to influence the composition of the kabul government after they leave
the soviet leader said all soviet forces could be withdrawn in 10 months if agreement is reached at geneva. the soviets later accused pakistan of trying to block chances of an agreement
pakistan's stand has some backing in washington and london, but western leaders have urged islamabad not to go so far as to jeopardize gorbachev's withdrawal pledge
soviet forces entered afghanistan in december 1979 and replaced one pro-soviet government in kabul with another. the soviet move was condemned by the united states, britain and other western governments
the soviets and afghan government soldiers have been fighting moslem guerrillas trying to overthrow the kabul government
the guerrilla groups maintain bases in pakistan and have received support from the united states, iran and pakistan
the british foreign office said in a statement friday following noorani's meeting with howe: ``there is a tremendous amount of sympathy and concern for pakistan. after eight years of occupation (in afghanistan), the soviet withdrawal is bound to leave a tremendous vacuum.''
a published report today says two men closely linked with attorney general edwin meese iii received $150,000 from a swiss businessman pushing an iraqi oil pipeline, but meese's lawyer says the attorney general didn't benefit in any way
the washington post reported that bruce rappaport of geneva sent the money in mid-1985 to franklyn chinn, meese's former investment adviser, and e. bob wallach, a close friend of meese for more than 30 years
sources familiar with the payment said wallach said the money represents his legal fee for his work on the pipeline proposal, the newspaper said. that work included getting meese's help in setting up a meeting for rappaport in june 1985 with then-national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane, the post said
the post quoted one source as saying the money was ``sent to chinn for the benefit of wallach.''
meese's attorney, james rocap, said friday he was aware of the payment but that ``it has absolutely nothing to do with mr. meese.''
none of it (the money) ever went to mr. meese,'' he said. ``none of it was ever used for the benefit of mr. meese.''
the post said the payment is not included on wallach's 1985 income tax return and was not reported by him until may 1987, when independent counsel james c. mckay expanded his investigation of the scandal-plagued wedtech corp. to include meese's dealings with wallach and chinn
wallach and chinn and a third man were accused in a federal indictment in new york in december of taking illegal payments from wedtech to influence meese. mckay has been conducting a separate investigation of meese's dealings with the two men
rappaport hired wallach in 1985 to try to drum up u.s. support for the proposed 540-mile pipeline through jordan that would run close to israeli territory. the pipeline never was built
the san francisco-based bechtel group, which was seeking to build the project, had enlisted the swiss businessman's help because of his close ties to israeli political figures. there had been concern that israel might attack the pipeline
secretary of state george p. shultz today said the soviet union must ``face up'' to its human rights problems if it wants to participate in a middle east peace conference
shultz specifically cited restrictions on emigration and religious practices, as well as a lack of diplomatic relations with israel
so they have some work to do that will make their presence at an international conference more acceptable from our standpoint and israel's standpoint,'' shultz told reporters on his air force jet flight from washington
the middle east is one of the topics on his agenda for the talks shultz is to hold in moscow sunday with foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze and on monday with general secretary mikhail s. gorbachev and shevardnadze
shultz is scheduled to go to the middle east next week to try to set up negotiations between israel and the arabs. he seemed doubtful that a peace conference would be the right framework
what is an international conference supposed to do if there is one?'' shultz said
but, he added, if the soviets ``continue to advocate seriously an international conference they have to face up to these problems that are posed by their lack of diplomatic presence in one of the key parties, and the immigration and other problems that i mentioned.''
shultz said he would not seek soviet backing for his efforts
we will talk around about the middle east, but we are not asking them for anything,'' he said. ``i think it will be more in the nature of information sharing.''
jewish emigration from the soviet union was nearly 800 people a month april through september of last year. it rose to over 900 monthly october through december. but in january, emigration dipped to about 650 to 700, and is at about the same rate this month
last year, applications were accepted from jews who did not have relatives in israel, but on jan. 1 the process was halted
the soviet union broke relations with israel after the 1967 mideast war, but sent a handful of diplomats to tel aviv last year
shultz said the soviets had imposed ``unwarranted'' restrictions on emigration and on the practice of judaism and other religions. ``so they have some work to do,'' he said
on another front, shultz backed pakistan's demand for a coalition government in afghanistan. he said it would make ``a contribution'' to stability as soviet troops withdrew from the country
shultz said the u.s.-backed afghan rebels would propose ``new ideas'' in geneva when negotiations for a settlement resume march 2
the soviets last week said pakistan was obstructing an end to the eight-year war in the country by insisting that a change of government in kabul precede the signing of a peace agreement
some 115,000 soviet troops are in afghanistan supporting the government in its war with the guerrillas. on feb. 8 gorbachev offered to begin a withdrawal on may 15 if an agreement is reached, and to carry it out over 10 months
the negotiations are being conducted by pakistan and afghanistan under the auspices of the united nations
the people's democratic party, which seized power in kabul in 1978, has presented its proposal for a future government to u.n. mediator diego cordovez. a u.s. official, who demanded anonymity, said it called for a dominant role for the kabul regime
shultz said the united states would suspend its military aid to the rebels provided the soviets ``cease similar supplies to the government forces.''
there has to be a symmetry there,'' shultz said
paul simon, who earlier had threatened to drop out of the democratic presidential race unless he started getting more votes, now says he's in the running ``until the finish line.''
the illinois senator said friday that he'd gotten so much support since he said he might drop out that it ``has convinced me that a great many americans want a clear-cut choice next november.''
this is a marathon race for the heart and soul of the democratic party, and i'm in it until the finish line in atlanta,'' simon told the minnehaha county democratic forum. the national convention will be held july 18-21 in the georgia capital
after placing third among democrats in this week's new hampshire primary, simon had said he would drop out of the race if he did not win south dakota's primary or minnesota's caucuses tuesday
a campaign leader for jesse jackson says a precinct caucus victory tuesday in minnesota, where about 96 percent of the population is white, would debunk the idea that jackson can't be elected president because he is black
the rev. thomas van leer made the statement friday at minneapolis north high school, where jackson talked to students about drug abuse. jackson made several campaign appearances in the twin cities friday, including a stop at an inner-city minneapolis church packed with lesbians and gays
i stood with you,'' the democratic candidate said. ``now make me a president.''
the rev. arlene ackerman, pastor of all god's children metropolitan community church, said jackson was the only presidential candidate to stand with gays and lesbians when they marched in washington, d.c., in october
national republican party chairman frank fahrenkopf says nevada republicans are ``a long way'' from determining their delegates to the gop convention despite a straw poll in which pat robertson's backers claimed victory
vice president george bush led nevada's gop presidential straw poll with 27 percent of the vote, but robertson forces claimed their candidate had won if undecided votes cast by robertson supporters were figured in
robertson's 15 percent of the vote thursday night placed him behind bush and senate gop leader bob dole, who had 22 percent, and ahead of rep. jack kemp who got 13 percent. but the robertson campaign urged followers to cast undecided votes, so the total of his support could have been higher than bush's
fahrenkopf, a nevada native, said friday the straw poll was non-binding and ``we are a long way from determining who the delegates are just at the state level. what happened in a straw poll at the nevada caucuses really doesn't mean a lot.''

