sikh gunmen killed two people at a bus stop outside amritsar today, raising to 25 the number of people slain in two days of bombings and shootings in punjab state, police and news reports said
the victims included 10 people shot to death then set ablaze in a farmhouse and 10 others who died in apparently well-planned bomb attacks in four cities in the northern state. more than 60 people were wounded in the bombings
an unexploded bomb was found today in a fifth city, batala, the united news of india reported. it said the four-pound tin of explosives was left in a store by a woman customer in the city 25 miles northeast of amritsar
the news agency also said two men were shot to death this afternoon at a bus stop on the edge of the sikh holy city
the latest killings brought to nearly 250 the number of people killed this year in punjab in attacks blamed on sikh militants, who demand a separate nation for their minority religion
in the village of sahsra, nine members of a farm family were killed with automatic rifles and revolvers friday night, along with a man staying at the house, police said
residents in the village 20 miles southeast of amritsar said about six sikh gunmen stormed into the home of farmer kewal singh while the family slept. the assailants set the bodies, the farmouse and its furnishings ablaze, the villagers said
the victims included the farmer, his wife, two daughters, four sons, a niece and a guest identified as sukhdev singh. police said earlier reports that 11 died apparently resulted from confusion
while sikh militants frequently claim their sikh victims are police informers, neighbors insisted kewal singh was only a simple villager
gurcharan singh, the village leader, said he was ``a poor farmer and tongawalla,'' or wagon driver
uni reported two other people were shot to death by sikh militants friday at bhuri kalan near amritsar and a man was killed near patiala, about 140 miles southeast of amritsar
friday's bomb attacks were in the cities of amritsar, patiala, gurdaspur and hoshiarpur and prompted police in new delhi to issue a ``red alert'' that the attacks might spread to the capital
sikh extremists have been fighting for a separate state in punjab since 1982. sikhs are a majority in punjab but comprise only 2 percent of the nationwide population of 780 million, more than 80 percent of whom are hindu
the sikh faith has elements of both hinduism and islam and was founded about 500 years ago as a peaceful alternative to the two warring religions
but the sikhs' 10th and final prophet, guru gobind singh, declared sikhism a warrior faith in which male adherents should all carry knives and bear the name singh, ``lion'' in punjabi. crash.</note>
