a militia commander today said his forces arrested several accomplices in the kidnapping of a u.s. marine officer who heads a united nations observer team, but that the mastermind had escaped
daoud daoud, the top military commander of the mainstream shiite amal militia in south lebanon, also that the kidnapping was well-planned in advance but that a series of snags slowed down the abductors' flight, giving amal time to seal the area
he said he believes lt. col. william r. higgins still is in south lebanon, although he was kidnapped wednesday
we have arrested several accomplices, but the leader of the kidnap operation has left the south,'' daoud told the associated press in an interview at his home in bedias, seven miles northeast of tyre
we know them all by name now, and we believe (lt.) col. higgins is still in south lebanon,'' he said
amal militiamen and u.n. peacekeeping troops have sealed off a 300-square-mile area around tyre, searching through cave-strewn valleys and olive and citrus groves
higgins, 43, heads a 76-man unarmed u.n. observer team that monitors border violations of a 1949 armistice agreement between lebanon and israel
the group is attached to the 5,800-member u.n. interim force in lebanon, or unifil, deployed in 1978 after an israeli incursion into south lebanon
the pro-iranian organization of the oppressed on earth on friday claimed responsibility for higgins' abduction, accusing him of being a cia spy. american and u.n. officials denied the charge
the pentagon said higgins, of danville, ky., had been a junior military aide to former u.s. secretary of defense caspar weinberger but that his abduction did not pose a major security risk to the united states
the first claim of responsibility for the kidnapping came thursday in a call from an anonymous man claiming to speak for a previously unknown group, the islamic revolutionary brigades
we believe higgins is still in south lebanon because the accomplice who was assigned to transport him to beirut after the abduction is detained by us,'' daoud said, refusing to identify any of the suspects or their affiliations
security sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said many of the 40 men detained have links to the iranian-backed hezbollah, or party of god, an umbrella organization for shiite extremists
hezbollah's voice of islam radio station, based in baalbek, in east lebanon, claimed today that 150 hezbollah members were rounded up in house raids in the tyre region
amal's men have stormed hezbollah's operations center in the south, seized documents, equipment and cameras. they also raided the house of hezbollah's south lebanon leader abbas musawi,'' the radio said. it made no mention of higgins
daoud said higgins' abduction was ``carefully thought out, planned and staged.''
he said among the detainees were those assigned to monitor higgins' movements, and ``they have confessed that they knew four days in advance that he was coming to tyre on wednesday.''
higgins was driving from tyre to unifil headquarters in the border town of naqoura when gunmen in a brown volvo car blocked the highway and seized him
the kidnappers ran into a chain of snags after the abduction. their first car, the brown volvo, got stuck in the mud. they made a bulldozer driver push them out, but the exhaust was broken and they had to move higgins to a white peugeot,'' daoud said
this (second) car collided with a truck loaded with oranges southeast of tyre. the kidnappers then moved higgins to a red mercedes and fled to their unknown hideout,'' daoud added
these snags cost the kidnappers about 1{ hours, during which we managed to seal off all exits from tyre region south of the litani river,'' daoud said
he said the mastermind had sent four other brown volvo cars speeding through several neighboring villages
he wanted to shake off any pursuers. however, the accidents gave us the needed time to seal off the area,'' daoud said
i am 60 percent certain that higgins is still south of the litani. it is very difficult for them to smuggle him out on foot through the valleys. nevertheless, we're keeping this in mind,'' he added
unifil spokesman timur goksel today said: ``we are maintaining road checks and heavy emphasis on collection of information. we believe he is probably still south of the litani,'' goksel said
in washington, president reagan said thursday that the united states will not withdraw americans from the u.n. observer group, despite the abduction. fifteen other nations contribute to the unit
in its type-written arabic statement, the organization of the oppressed on earth said higgins is ``one of the biggest spies planting daily terror in our land.''
the statement was delivered to a western news agency in beirut, accompanied by photocopies of two identity cards of higgins
the group, believed made up of shiite zealots, previously has claimed responsibility for hijackings, bombings and the abduction of 12 lebanese jews. it has claimed to have killed eight of the jews kidnapped in 1984
the soviets' top arms control official said his country is counting on secretary of state george p. shultz to arrive ready to explore new initiatives in u.s.-soviet disarmament talks
viktor karpov, a former arms negotiator who now heads the soviet foreign ministry's arms control department, said late friday that shultz's visit, which begins sunday, ``must set the pace for further soviet-u.s. dialogue.''
during the u.s. official's three-day visit, he is scheduled to talk with mikhail s. gorbachev and other top soviet officials about a proposed agreement to cut the superpowers' long-range nuclear missiles by 50 percent
the talks follow the dec. 8 signing of a treaty to ban superpower medium- and shorter-range nuclear missiles by soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev and president reagan in washington
in a special panel of the supreme soviet parliament earlier friday, two red army officials said that ratification of the dec. 8 treaty could save the soviet union more than $80 million and would free ``tens of thousands'' of soldiers from their present duties
marshal sergei f. akhromeyev, the military chief of staff, and maj. gen. vladimir i. medvedev were among top officials who spoke before the panel, which is considering ratification of the pact
those who spoke at the hearing at the kremlin endorsed the treaty, but akhromeyev said the soviet military is worried about nato moves to compensate for the weapons slated for destruction by the pact
the idea of compensation is wild,'' said the first deputy foreign minister, yuli m. vorontsov. ``a doctor who operates on a person to cure him of an ulcer does not then say, `what can i put in to compensate for the ulcer?'''
on feb. 9, the foreign relations commissions of the two houses of the soviet legislature created a special 10-member subcommittee to seek the opinion of experts and ordinary soviet citizens about the treaty
the treaty must be ratified by the supreme soviet's presidium to become law. but because it already has been approved by the ruling communist party politburo, passage is assured
friday's two-hour hearing seemed designed to assuage the fears of some soviets that their leaders made too many concessions in the treaty. a small group of foreign reporters was allowed to attend
those against are few,'' said chairman georgy m. korniyenko, summing up soviet public opinion. ``those who are against just don't trust the imperialists ... but then there are not a few who have concerns.''
under the pact, the soviet union must destroy 1,752 missiles, compared with 859 for the united states
but akhromeyev said that under the agreement, the soviets will eliminate 650 modern medium-range missiles, while the americans will destroy 689 new weapons, he said
u.s. defense secretary frank carlucci and other nato officials have said the west needs to modernize its battlefield nuclear weapons or improve its conventional arms to make up for the banned missiles
akhromeyev said there was ``not a word'' in the inf treaty that would bar such measures
akromeyev said 3 percent to 4 percent of the ``tens of thousands'' of military men to be released from their duty with the missiles would be put on pension, but that younger men could continue with their military careers
medvedev told the panel that missiles and other soviet military equipment worth $33 million to $41.5 million would be destroyed because of the treaty
he said the soviet union would save $83 million, and that military equipment used for the missiles that does not have to be destroyed is worth $250 million
the subcommittee adjourned without a date set for its next session. the panel will report back to the supreme soviet's foreign relations commissions, which must recommend whether the treaty should be ratified. information from berkeley putting quake at 5.1 on richter scale, corrects locator for hollister to 75 miles, sted 25 miles; picks up 4th graf, ``people living ...''</note>
a strong earthquake rattled across central and northern california early today, causing minor damage in this agricultural town and shaking people awake over a wide area, officials said. no injuries were reported
the quake measured 5.1 on the richter scale, said anthony lomax, spokesman for the seismology laboratory at the university of california, berkeley
he said the strong quake struck at 12:40 a.m. about seven miles southeast of hollister, a quake-prone city some 75 miles southeast of san francisco
in hollister, the tremor knocked products off store shelves, broke a glass door and set off burglar alarms across the city, said paul penn, emergency services coordinator for san benito county
but no injuries were reported, and power was not interrupted, he said
san benito county is known as one of the more seismically active counties in the country, so you get used to it,'' penn added. ``the last major one was superbowl sunday 1986.''
people living over a broad area reported feeling strong earth movement, with jittery residents in modesto, san francisco, and monterey calling authorities for reassurance
i was standing in a sturdy old building when i felt the ground begin to rumble, and lights began shaking,'' said gordon bock, a time magazine staff writer experiencing his first earthquake
i'm from new york. i've only read about these things,'' said bock, who was in asilomar, near monterey, when the temblor hit. ``my stomach is churning and my hands are still shaking.'' pickup. adds byline.</note>
the air force carried out a revenge attack on two swapo guerrilla bases in angola this morning, retaliating for a bank bombing that killed 18 people in namibia, the defense force chief said
gen. jannie geldenhuys said air force fighter aircraft successfully carried out attacks on south-west african people's organization targets in lubango and ongiva in southern angola
he said the attacks were in retaliation friday's bombing of the first national bank in oshakati, south-west africa, where 18 people were killed and 31 injured
geldenhuys said swapo, which has been fighting for 22 years against south african occupation of the territory, also known as namibia, was responsible for the lunch-hour bomb
a statement friday from the swapo office in luanda, angola, denied involvement in the bombing, and said it was part of a south african propaganda campaign to ``smear the name of swapo.''
the guerrillas fight in south-west africa, also known as namibia, from bases in southern angola that periodically are raided by the south african defense force
eight mirage fighters took part in the attack on two targets near lubango, 186 miles north of the namibian-angolan border; and five impala aircraft attacked targets at ongiva, 26 miles north of the border, the statement said
geldenhuys said the lubango targets were ``swapo's most important training center in angola, the tobias hainyeko training center, and a terrorist holding area about 10 kms (6.2 miles) west of there.''
he said swapo guerrillas receive training in the handling of explosives at the tobias hainyeko center, which he said, ``can be regarded as the breeding ground for terrorism against the inhabitants of south-west africa-namibia.''
swapo had launched a number of raids from ongiva recently on civilians in south-west africa, the general said
by these attacks the security forces demonstrated their willingness never to allow swapo terrorism to go unpunished,'' geldenhuys said. ``terrorists will be tracked down and destroyed.''
friday's bank blast was the deadliest in 22 years of war between the black guerrillas and the minority white government of south africa
among the dead in the blast in the far-northern town of oshakati were 10 women, three men and a child. all the victims were black, except for one white woman who was identified today in a pro-government newspaper as the wife of a member of a special police unit
four of the bodies were discovered in the rubble friday night, said the citizen newspaper
of the 31 people injured, 20 of them were black, said an army spokesman, cmdt. lieb bester
there was no immediate claim of responsibility for the blast, which destroyed the bank building. five people were injured when an explosion occurred in the street near the same bank a year ago
chris ball, managing director of the first national bank, flew to windhoek to visit the scene friday afternoon. he called the bombing ``a barbarous and senseless attack on the community of oshakati, achieving nothing.''
all those killed were civilians, bester said. most were believed to be local government employees who had just been paid
a police inspector, keirie du rand, said about 55 pounds of plastic explosive was used in the blast, which occurred shortly before 1 p.m. he said a fire raged for several hours after the explosion, hampering police access to the scene
oshakati is in north-central namibia, about 25 miles south of the angolan border. it is home to the largest military base in the region, a staging point for south africa's current military intervention in angola's civil war
swapo has claimed responsibility for numerous previous bombings in the territory, including a blast last month at a store at a military base in windhoek. ``kalikow agreed ...,'' to restore dropped word `less.'</note>
the new york post, the nation's oldest continuously published daily, gained a new lease on life today with approval by its unions of $22 million in concessions
owner rupert murdoch had said unless he was given $24 million in concessions he would close the paper. but he contributed $3 million to the deal, calling it a farewell gift
the agreement clears the way for murdock to complete a $37 million sale of the financially troubled tabloid, founded in 1801 by alexander hamilton, to real estate developer peter kalikow
the agreement was reached at 1:50 a.m. after nearly 16 hours of bargaining
i want to say at this time that i wish mr. kalikow great, successful publishing of the new york post,'' murdoch said in announcing the agreement. ``i ... hate to leave it.''
while murdoch had said the paper would close unless he obtained the concessions, he agreed to stop the clock as negotiations continued past his 2 p.m. friday deadline
kalikow agreed to a package that would save $2 million less than originally sought on condition the unions agreed to all other terms, according to howard rubenstein, a spokesman for both kalikow and murdoch
under the agreement, kalikow would save $10 million in the first year, $8 million in the second and $6 million in the third, minus a $2 million bonus in the final year, said theodore kheel, an adviser to the unions
in each of the three years, kalikow saves $7.5 million through employee buyouts and $2.5 million through employee pay cuts, kheel said. in all, 130 jobs from a work force of 1,200 will be eliminated
however, in the first year employees will not lose anything because murdoch will give them $2.5 million to restore the pay cuts, he added
in the second year, kalikow is to restore $2 million of the pay cuts and murdoch make up the difference with $500,000. kalikow agreed to provide $4 million in raises and $2 million in bonuses in the third year, kheel said
i don't think there's any question that without murdoch's contribution of $3 million, the paper would have definitely shut down,'' kheel said
kheel said murdoch referred to the $3 million contribution as a farewell gift
union leader george mcdonald thanked murdoch for the $3 million
the unions achieved their goal ``to save our jobs for our people and our families,'' said mcdonald, president of the allied printing trades council, an umbrella group for post unions
the agreement, to take effect march 7, is subject to verification by kalikow's auditors and union ratification, but murdoch said those were only formalities
murdoch said of kalikow: ``he's a very ambitious man, as well as being a wealthy one. i know that he is determined to make it (the newspaper) successful.''
the post faced financial problems from its earliest years but held on as paper after paper in the city merged, then shut down
murdoch bought the afternoon tabloid, the nation's oldest continuously published daily, from dorothy schiff in 1976 for about $31 million as he expanded his worldwide media holdings from australia and england into the united states
under murdoch, the paper turned from liberal to conservative on the editorial page, became splashy and at times racy
his efforts failed to turn the paper around. murdoch says he has lost nearly $150 million in 11 years of operating the post. he said friday that current losses were running $100,000 a day
earlier this month, murdoch announced he had reached agreement to sell the post to kalikow
the sale was prompted by congressional action late last year that blocked the federal communication commission from granting him another waiver to its rule against owning a newspaper and tv station in the same market. murdoch also owns wnyw-tv in new york
in boston, where he faces the same situation, murdoch has indicated he'd sell his tv station and hold on to the boston herald
a moderately strong earthquake today shook the mountains of the soviet central asian republic of tadzhikistan, but no injuries or damage were reported, the official soviet news agency tass said
the tremor occurred at 4:50 a.m. moscow time (8:50 p.m. est friday) and was centered 99 miles east of the republic's capital, dushanbe, tass said
it said the dushanbe seismic station measured the magnitude of the earthquake at 5 on the soviet scale. the soviet scale measures observable effects of an earthquake
tadzhikistan, with an area of 55,240 square miles, is known for farming and cattle ranching. rich deposits of coal, lead and zinc also are found in the republic, whose 1981 population was 3.4 million
