a lawyer for attorney general edwin meese iii said saturday that meese received no money or benefit from a reported $150,000 payment to two close meese associates in connection with promotion of an iraqi pipeline project
the attorney, james rocap, said he was aware of the payment but that ``it has absolutely nothing to do with mr. meese.''
swiss businessman bruce rappaport sent the money in mid-1985 to franklyn chinn, meese's former investment adviser, and e. bob wallach, a close friend of meese for more than 30 years, according to sources familiar with independent prosecutor james mckay's investigation of meese
rappaport was enlisted by the san francisco-based bechtel group, which was seeking to build the project
the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, quoted wallach as saying the money from rappaport represented his legal fee for his work on the pipeline proposal, including getting meese's help to set up a meeting for rappaport in june 1985 with then-national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane
rocap characterized as ``not a big deal'' the fact that wallach had been paid a fee through rappaport and that the $150,000 had been deposited in a trust account with chinn
ed meese never got any money from the pipeline project or from bruce rappaport. he never got any money from bob wallach with the exception of a few lunches,'' said rocap
the lawyer said that the only money meese got through his partnership with chinn was the previously disclosed stock profits that chinn earned for the attorney general through various stock trades
the washington post reported saturday that the payment was not included on wallach's 1985 income tax return and was not reported by him until may 1987, when mckay expanded his investigation of the scandal-plagued wedtech corp. to include meese's dealings with wallach and chinn
a federal indictment in new york accused wallach and chinn and a third man of taking illegal payments from wedtech to influence meese
rappaport hired wallach in 1985 to try to drum up u.s. support for the proposed 540-mile pipeline through jordan that would run close to israeli territory. the pipeline never was built
president reagan today asked congress to ward off election year pressure for increased spending and enact the $1.1 trillion budget presented earlier in the week
if congress upholds its commitments and stands firm against pressures for increased spending _ pressures that reach a peak during election years _ solid results will be forthcoming,'' reagan said in his weekly radio speech
if our proposed budget is enacted, deficit spending will have dropped from $221 billion in fiscal year 1986 to $130 billion in fiscal year 1989,'' the president said
he said consultations between congress and the white house before the budget submission _ which both branches have hailed as a method of avoiding budget fights as in previous years _ demonstrates ``responsible leadership expected by the electorate.''
reagan said the budget will ``keep the lid'' on spending, while recognizing that some increases are needed to avoid jeopardizing national security
he repeated his criticism of last year's budget process, saying late amendments to the spending bill required him to sign a package without the review it should have been granted, or face shutdown of the federal government
with the new budget, he said, ``we have an opportunity to put our fiscal house in order.''
reagan also repeated his assertion that his administration has presided over the biggest economic expansion since world war ii and once again hailed his administration's record on employment
