a regional ice cream company has won a trademark victory over giant mcdonald's corp., which claimed a frozen milkshake called ``quick thaw mcstraw'' was too much like its own trademarks
it's not often that the little guy wins over a fortune 500 company,'' said dennis roney, president and chief executive officer of oberweis dairy inc., parent company of roney ice cream co
roney announced friday that it has won a five-year trademark dispute with mcdonald's
the roney company, which makes ice cream and ice milk in this chicago suburb, filed in december 1983 for a trademark registration for ``quick thaw mcstraw.''
the name was a variation on hannah-barbera productions' quick draw mcgraw, and the hollywood animator gave the company permission to use the name, with limitations, roney said
mcdonald's opposed the registration, arguing that consumers would be confused by the use of mcstraw when it had so many trademarks using `mc' or `mac', roney said. mcdonald's, based in suburban oak brook, also argued that the roney frozen shake was similar to its own products
the department of commerce's trademark trial and appeal board ruled in favor of the ice cream maker
mcdonald's spokesman chuck rubner said the comnpany may appeal
here is the text of president reagan's weekly radio broadcast:
my fellow americans, this week i transmitted to congress our proposed budget for 1989. this budget fulfills the second year obligations of a bipartisan agreement i hammered out last november with the leaders of congress
we then, after arduous negotiations, agreed on a plan to reduce federal deficit spending by over $75 billion in two years. if congress upholds its commitments and stands firm against pressures for increased spending _ pressures that reached a peak during election years _ solid results will be forthcoming, and progress has already been made
if our proposed budget is enacted, deficit spending will have dropped from $221 billion in fiscal year 1986 to $130 billion in fiscal year 1989. as a proportion of gross national product, it will have been cut by more than half since 1983
the legislative and executive branches, by living up to our commitments of last november, are demonstrating the kind of responsible leadership expected by the electorate. the budget we've transmitted is true to that spirit
it reduces the level of deficit spending, while at the same time, holds the line against any general tax increase. it remains firm in our commitments to essential domestic programs. it also includes funding for the minimum defense program needed to keep our country safe and necessary to honor our commitments to our friends and allies
anything less would not only jeopardize our national security, but also dim prospects for further negotiated agreements with our adversaries
we've proposed a trim budget that keeps the lid on spending, and yet still recognizes that some increases are justified. for example, we're actually calling for congress to spend substantially more on education, combating aids, the war against drugs, and improving air safety, while keeping discretionary domestic spending within predetermined limits
the long-term solution to the plague of deficit spending, however, is not prudence this year or next. what's needed is reform that will bring discipline and accountability to the budget process
exemplifying the shortcomings, last year the federal budget was slapped together into a single behemoth bill and delivered to me hours before the federal government was due to run out of money. i was faced with the decision to either sign without time for careful consideration or see the federal government shut down
i pledged during the state of the union, after plopping down 43 pounds of paper sent to me by congress, that i would never sign another catchall continuing resolution. i'm pleased that at least 34 senators and a good number of congressmen, including many in the leadership, have indicated that they, too, do not want a repeat of last year's budget mayhem
make no mistake, we have the opportunity to put our fiscal house in order and to reform the budget process. we've proven time and again that by working together, partisanship can be put aside and progress can be made when the national interest is at stake
it took co-operation from both sides of the aisle. for example, to put in place an economic recovery program that has given this country the longest peacetime expansion in history, inflation and interest rates have been kept down. family income is up. and we created over 15 million new jobs since the recovery began. being mindful of the suffering that comes with unemployment, that last figure is a matter of particular pride for me. and as our economy is grown, unemployment has dropped to its lowest level since 1979. but that statement doesn't come near to describing the success we've enjoyed
today, more people have jobs and a higher percentage of our work force is employed than ever before. since the recovery began, we've created more new jobs than in all of western europe and japan combined. and even the meaning of unemployment figures is sometimes not fully understood
our 7 million unemployed citizens are often thought of as people who have lost their jobs, as they're sometimes described in the media. in fact, less than half of the unemployed are job losers. fifty-five percent are new entrants, mainly young people looking for their first jobs, re-entrants _ individuals who left the work force, perhaps to raise a family and are now seeking to get back in _ or job-leavers who've voluntarily left their jobs to change locations or occupations
we, of course, need to remain concerned about each and every citizen who is seeking work, and should not be satisfied until everyone who wants a job _ a good job _ has one
one person enduring the pressures and frustrations of unemployment is too many. that is why responsible federal spending and taxing policies _ policies that foster growth and expand opportunities for all our citizens _ are so important. that is what the budget that i have just sent to congress is all about
until next week, thanks for listening. god bless you
associated press writer vicki miller was aboard the california zephyr on her way to a skiing weekend in colorado when a fire broke out. this is her account of the incident
most people in the first coach car of an amtrak train were trying to sleep in the wee hours of saturday morning when the california zephyr pulled into the small station here to pick up passengers
the quiet was shattered by the sound of sirens, but no one knew what was going on until they began to smell smoke
there were no crew members in sight. one woman in our group, which was headed for a ski trip in winter park, colo., went to investigate. she returned to tell us calmly that there was a fire in a nearby car
it didn't sound serious, and jokes were tossed around while passengers in the car began to stir
we remained in the car, wondering if it was safe, reassuring each other that we would be warned of trouble
minutes later, a woman crew member ran through the coach, her face blackened with soot. she dashed outside and then returned, saying she'd barely escaped from the crew car where the fire apparently began
chattering with cold, she said she had no shoes and that her feet were cold. outside it was about 31 degrees
the woman left, but returned quickly to ask passengers for blankets. her voice was panicky as she told us people outside the train needed them
i glanced out the window and saw smoke billowing from the crew car two cars ahead. soon the faint smell of smoke drifted into our car and we decided it was time to get out
as we left the train, it became apparent that the fire was serious. some crew members, blankets drapped over their shoulders, appeared dazed. one man sat bent over on the steps leading to the upper deck of our coach car. others were visibly shaken
outside was a maze of fire trucks, hoses and rescue vehicles. firefighters on ladders attempted to cut into the crew car's windows with power tools
emergency personnel and volunteers carried stretchers to ambulances. an amtrak employee yelled to firefighters that he thought there were still people inside the car
soon, more people were helped from the car. many were dressed in bedclothes, and some men were bare-chested
by the time a spokesman announced that the train would proceed without the crew car and sleeper car, our group of six had decided to bail out of our weekend trip. we hitched a ride across town in the back of an ambulance, with another vehicle toting our gear
we turned our hopes from fresh powder to finding a rental car; after we got the last one in town, my companions headed back home
one person was dead, others were hurt. my traveling companions kept asking, ``why weren't we told whether we were in danger or were safe?''
acting gov. rose mofford is getting high marks in her role as temporary chief executive from many legislators but not from the man she replaced, impeached gov. evan mecham
mrs. mofford, a democrat and arizona's longtime secretary of state, became acting governor feb. 5 when mecham, a republican, was impeached by the house. she moved into the governor's office and will remain acting governor until the senate reaches a verdict
my lifestyle has changed,'' mrs. mofford, 65, told a group of mayors friday, saying she's switched her bedtime reading to subjects like the state budget or arizona's medicaid alternative program
when mecham was impeached he was considered legally ``disabled'' and mrs. mofford assumed all of his gubernatorial powers, including the right to sign bills and hire or fire state employees
mrs. mofford brought in her own volunteer staff and replaced one state agency head _ department of administration director max hawkins, who drafted mecham into the 1986 gubernatorial race and was widely blamed for many of mecham's problems. she also accepted the resignation of mecham's controversial washington lobbyist, fred craft
that angered mecham, who has moved his own staff to an office building in suburban glendale. in a letter to mrs. mofford last week, he complained that she was ``turning a temporary acting governorship into a complete disruption and replacement of my administration.''
may i ask you to recognize that i have only been accused and not convicted of any act,'' mecham said, adding that he expects to be cleared and return to the governorship
mrs. mofford replied to mecham, ``i am responsible for acting as the chief executive of this state ... i did not ask for this job, but i intend to discharge it to the best of my ability during these difficult times.''
lawmakers say they generally are pleased with the work of mrs. mofford, who many had hoped would act mainly as caretaker
mrs. mofford addresses problems in a calm, deliberate manner,'' said rep. jim skelly, a conservative republican who headed the house select committee on mecham's impeachment. ``that's a change. she's not going off half-cocked.''
haven't you noticed? there's a different air in state government,'' said senate minority leader alan stephens, a democrat. ``people aren't looking for the next bomb to drop.''
mecham faces a feb. 29 impeachment trial on allegations that he concealed a $350,000 campaign loan, misused $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by lending it to his auto dealership, and that he tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official
he is also scheduled for a march 9 criminal trial on six felony counts in connection with the $350,000 loan
if mecham is convicted in court or by the senate, mrs. mofford becomes governor in her own right
however, that would raise a new series of questions if it occurred before the may 17 recall election. attorney general bob corbin has issued a non-binding opinion saying that if mecham resigns or is removed before the recall, mrs. mofford would be subject to removal from office in the recall vote
rep. gary giordano, a republican who opposed mecham's impeachment, said he realized mrs. mofford was entitled to her own staff, but added, ``i don't think she had a particular mandate to bring in the babbitt administration.''
many of mrs. mofford's volunteer aides had worked for former gov. bruce babbitt, a democrat
but house minority leader art hamilton, a democrat, said he believes mrs. mofford is handling the job wisely
it's ticklish and it's difficult and it's like no other chief executive in this state has ever found themselves in,'' hamilton said
mrs. mofford pleased democrats and angered some republicans when she said one of her top priorities would be to seek creation of a martin luther king state holiday. mecham created a storm of controversy in january 1986 when he canceled a holiday for state workers on grounds it was illegally declared by babbitt through executive order
otherwise, there has been little controversy over her policies, including her statement that a tax increase probably would be needed to balance arizona's budget
i don't know all the problems that are facing us,'' mrs. mofford acknowledged friday. ``i know that there are criticisms out there, but i don't think that that will be the last time that i will ever be criticized.''
greek cypriots vote sunday in the second and decisive round of the most heated presidential election since cyprus won independence from britain 28 years ago
the outcome is wide open in the race between veteran right-wing leader glafcos clerides and political newcomer george vassiliou
the candidates, left in the race after they took the top two spots in the first round of voting last sunday, held their final mass rallies in nicosia friday night and fired verbal broadsides at each other
clerides, 68, topped last sunday's poll with 33.32 percent of the vote by the 363,000-strong electorate. vassiliou, 56, a millionaire businessman backed by the powerful communist party, akel, polled 30.11 percent
on paper, vassiliou goes into sunday's showdown ballot in the strongest position after the small socialist party, which polled 9.4 percent, announced it will back him
but sunday's ballot was thrown wide open after president spyros kyprianou, eliminated in the first-round vote, refused to back either of the frontrunners
kyprianou, leader of the centrist democratic party, diko, was seeking a third five-year term. he took 27.29 percent last sunday
he told the 91,000 greek cypriots who voted for him that they can back anyone they want
tens of thousands of flag-waving greek cypriots, many bused in from other areas, attended friday's rallies, held within 500 yards of each other in central nicosia, jamming streets for hours
both candidates stressed that sunday's poll will be the most crucial since the island became independent in 1960
cyprus has been divided since 1974, when the turkish army invaded to seized the northern third of the island, forcing about 180,000 greek cypriots to flee to the south
turkish cypriots declared their own republic in the north in 1983. turkey is the only country to recognize it
the partition of the island, and stalled efforts to reunite the rival communities, has been the dominant issue in the election. bread and butter issues have taken a back seat
clerides and vassiliou have taken a more conciliatory attitude toward reviving negotiations than kyprianou, a hardliner who has been widely blamed for blocking u.n. efforts to establish a federation
kyprianou said he would resume negotiations with the turkish side when it withdrew its 35,000 troops from northern cyprus along with the 65,000 settlers turkey shipped from the mainland
clerides and vassiliou have said they are willing to resume talks without such preconditions
the turks invaded, ostensibly to protect the turkish cypriot minority, after militant greek cypriots staged a short-lived coup seeking to unite the island with greece
that coup forced the president at the time, archbishop makarios, to flee the country. clerides, who was then president of parliament, stood in until makarios returned in december 1974
clerides has sought to attract wide support by pledging to form an all-party government of national unity to enter into talks with the turkish cypriots
to strengthen his strategy, clerides announced during a televised debate thursday night that he was resigning as leader of his democratic rally party to go into sunday's ballot as an independent
vassiliou rejected that as an electoral ploy, pointing out that the other three parties have rejected clerides's coalition proposal as unworkable
the two frontrunners, who had concentrated on knocking kyprianou out in the first round, have spent the last week slamming each other
vassiliou accuses clerides of harboring the extremists involved in the 1974 coup and of being a ``right-wing, anti-labor reactionary.''
the conservative leader has rejected the charges and accuses vassiliou of being a communist pawn. commission ^by malcolm ritter</byline>
people with aids who have begun their own trials of experimental aids drugs found support for their efforts saturday from members of the president's aids commission
the most exciting aspect of this project is that it originates from the aids community, empowering ourselves to participate in the research that may save our lives and dramatically expand the number of patients who have access to experimental drugs,'' said thomas hannon, administrative director of the community research initiative in new york
the project uses private physicians and their patients to test ways of preventing development of full-blown acquired immune deficiency syndrome, he said
while aids drug trials are usually done by government, universities and drug companies, the community based project will include areas of reseach that might otherwise be neglected, he said
several members of the presidential commission on the human immunodeficiency virus epidemic voiced support for the project after hannon testified at a commission hearing
i think what you're doing is introducing an element of competition into the realm of what to do abut the aids problem,'' said commission member john j. creedon. ``i commend you. i say , `right on.' ''
but commission member burton lee, a physician at the memorial sloan-kettering cancer center in new york, said the project's strategy of including intravenous drug abusers among test subjects was ``a bad mistake.''
they are unpredictable at almost the 100 percent level'' and their inclusion will create ``completely flawed material'' in research results, he said. some researchers say that intravenous drug users are poor research subjects because they often don't follow instructions and don't appear for follow-up visits
hannon disagreed, saying ``people with this disease have their lives on the line and are willing to cooperate.''
the project is sponsored by the people with aids coalition, said hannon, who said he has aids
the project, approved by the new york state department of health to sponsor treatment trials, already has five experiments under way, he said. most funding comes from the companies that make the drugs involved, he said
creedon, president and chief executive officer of metropolitan life insurance co., suggested the project also apply to the insurance industry for financial help
studies must be approved by the organization's institutional review board, which includes physicians, law professors, religious leaders and people with aids
another commission member, william walsh, told hannon to ``let us know as specifically as you can what we can do to get more support, more interest'' for such community-based programs
commission member beny primm, executive director of the addiction research and treatment corp. in brooklyn, n.y., offered to supply ``responsible intravenous drug abusers who are in treatment from my program any time you want.''
among the drugs being tested by the community project are pentamidine, being studied in 200 people with aids for prevention of pneumocystis carinii pneumonia, and erythropoietin for anemia brought on by the aids drug azt or the disease itself
another study in seven people will see if a parasitic infection called cryptosporidiosis can be treated with milk from cows that were injected with the parasite. the idea is that the cows' immune systems would create proteins called antibodies that would attack the parasite, and that the antibodies would be in the milk
a $750,000 trial, about to begin with funding from du pont co., will test a drug called ampligen
with money raised from the community, hannon testified, the project is testing al-721, an extract from eggs that hannon said thousands of people with aids are taking on their own. the project is studying its potential for fighting the aids virus and boosting the immune system, he said
the leader of a french basque terrorist group and four members of his organization were arrested saturday after a shootout with police, authorities said
philippe bidart, leader of iparretarrak, had been sought for more than six years. the former schoolteacher was convicted twice in absentia, once for the murder of two police officers, and is suspected in two other slayings of policemen
iparretarrak, which means ``those of the north'' in the basque language, is fighting for independence for the basque country in southwestern france and northern spain
it has been less active than the spanish basque terrorist movement eta but has claimed responsibility for dozens of attacks
about 20 gendarmes _ members of a police force under direction of the french army _ surrounded bidart and his companions in a home on the outskirts of bayonne, the largest city in the french basque region
as they emerged about 1 a.m., they were confronted by the gendarmes. two of the iparretarrak members, joseph etcheveste and pierre aguerre, were wounded by gunfire and taken to the local hospital for treatment. etcheveste was described as bidart's top lieutenant
bidart and the other two, philippe lascaray and jean-paul hiribaren, then surrendered
defense minister andre giraud sent a message of congratulations to the gendarmerie, saying the arrests were the result of a long effort ``accomplished in particularly delicate and often dangerous conditions.''
authorities said only one iparretarrak member remained at large, lucienne, fourcade, and they issued an appeal for her to surrender
no harm will be done to her. we known she never intended to kill anyone,'' the gendermerie in bayonne said. ``she cannot stay on the run by herself.''
bidart, 35, had been sought since nov. 7, 1981, when he was caught on camera during a bank robbery in saint paul les dax, a basque country town
bidart was convicted in absentia of murder in the march 19, 1982, slayings of two national policemen killed in st. etienne de baigorry, his hometown. he received a life sentence in that case and another life term for a conviction in absentia for the bank robbery
authorities say bidart also is believed responsible for two other attacks in which gendarmes died, one on aug. 7, 1983, and the other last august
during his six years in hiding, bidart gave one press conference in hiding and made one cassette recording played at the funeral of an iparretarrak member last june
here is the text of the democratic response, delivered by house budget chairman william gray of pennsylvania, to president reagan's radio address on saturday:
hello, this is congressman bill gray, the chairman of the house budget committee. two days ago the president sent congress his budget request for fiscal year 1989. but this year something is different. everybody is shocked at the calm on capitol hill
people have gotten used to a set pattern: the budget comes up, the battle lines are drawn, political bombs are dropped, the war begins. this time people wonder why no bombs are being dropped. what's different is the president's budget. the budget that arrived on my desk on thursday is more realistic than any of the other seven the president has sent to congress
in large measure, of course, this is due to the bipartisan agreement between the administration and congress at the budget summit last fall. that agreement established specific limits for the major areas of the budget, including defense spending and domestic programs
it also committed us to an equally important objective: real, permanent significant deficit reduction. the president's budget appears to meet the summit guidelines, which is why we're not seeing the kind of fireworks we've had in the past. let's give credit where it's due: in at least some areas the president has recognized that congress' priorities are also the priorities of the american people
instead of trying to cut aid to education by 28 percent, as he did last year, the president is proposing a four percent increase from the current funding level. instead of trying to cut back on the war on drugs, the president would increase spending by 13 percent. and to deal with aids, one of our most important health problems, the president is asking for a 40 percent increase in funds for aids research and education
but in other areas, this budget is out of line with america's needs and america's values. for example, the president's budget would spend more for homes in space than for the homeless here on earth. in fact, funding for the proposed space station would be almost $1 billion, but funding for the needs of the homeless would be only $219 million, far less than the amount authorized by congress
the president and his representatives have indicated that this year they want to avoid confrontational politics and acrimonious exchanges, the kinds of things that in previous years led to budget stalemate and huge deficits. well, we can all agree with that. the success of the budget summit and the prospect of continued administration involvement will, i believe, demonstrate that nothing is wrong with the budget process, nothing that can't be fixed by cooperation and compromise on priorities and policies
we proved that the process wasn't the problem when, in seven to eight weeks, with cooperation and compromise, we designed and implemented a two-year budget agreement. the spirit and willingness to compromise are the oil that makes the budget process work. we know that the economy has improved recently. inflation is down, and unemployment, after rising to records in the long recession, is back down to its 1979 level
but we democrats are concerned about the future. we cannot rest comfortably with economic gains built on a policy of borrow, borrow, spend, spend. the deficit is a problem we cannot escape by talking about process. since 1980, our national debt has more than doubled. by next january, it will be almost $2.8 trillion. that works out to $11,400 for every man, woman and child in the united states, and every year we have to pay the interest on that debt. we have made major progress, but we still have a long way to go
if we maintain the bipartisan spirit that came out of the budget summit, we can pass a budget that reduces the deficits and meets the needs of this nation. and if we maintain the spirit of conciliation that has been evidenced so far this year, we can make the budget process work and build a brighter future for the next generation, and an america with greater opportunity. this is congressman bill gray. committee chief; adds byline</note>
president reagan beseeched congress saturday to ``stand firm'' against election year pressure for expensive additions to his $1.1 trillion budget, but the chairman of the house budget committee called for more money to help the homeless
reagan, defending the spending package in his weekly radio speech delivered from camp david, md., said deficit spending will drop from $221 billion in fiscal year 1986 to $130 billion in the 1989 fiscal year, which his proposed new budget covers
if congress upholds its commitments and stands firm against pressures for increased spending _ pressures that reach a peak during election years _ solid results will be forthcoming,'' the president said
the new budget, sent to capitol hill thursday, was written after a series of consultations with congress on deficit-reduction goals and outlines of the amounts to be spent on broad categories
as a result, reagan said, the legislative and executive branches ``are demonstrating the kind of responsible leadership expected by the electorate.''
the budget, the president said, ``remains firm in our commitments to essential domestic programs. it also includes funding for the minimum defense programs needed to keep our country safe and necessary to honor our commitments to our friends and allies.''
he called it a ``trim budget'' that keeps the lid on spending, while permitting increases for education, the battle against aids and illegal drugs, and air safety programs
rep. william gray, d-pa., chairman of the house budget panel, echoed the president's praise for the budget consultations and the hikes for education, aids and narcotics programs
let's give credit where its due,'' gray said in the democratic response. ``in at least some areas, the president has recognized that congress' priorities are also the priorities of the american people.''
in other areas, this budget is out of line with america's needs and america's values,'' gray said
his only specific criticism of the package was a request for $1 billion to build a manned space station, compared with $219 million for programs to help homeless people, ``far less than the amount authorized by congress.''
the budget provides ``more for homes in space than for the homeless on earth,'' gray said
at the same time, he said, he expected differences to be worked out through compromise and cooperation
this year something is different,'' gray said. ``everybody is shocked at the calm on capitol hill. people have gotten used to a set pattern: the budget comes up, the battle lines are drawn, political bombs are dropped, the war begins.''
this time, he said, ``people wonder why no bombs are being dropped.''
what's different is the president's budget,'' gray continued. ``the budget that arrived on my desk on thursday is more realistic than any of the other seven the president has sent to congress.''
reagan, in his radio address, repeated his criticism of last year's budget process, saying late amendments to the spending bill required him to sign a hastily assembled package without review, or face the shutdown of the federal government
with the new budget, he said, ``we have an opportunity to put our fiscal house in order.''
reagan also repeated his assertions that his administration has presided over the biggest economic expansion since world war ii, and he once again hailed his administration's record on employment. 20th graf, the soviet, to delete incorrect date and to say obituary appeared a few days later</note>
the soviets have become more open about announcing their space failures, but failed to announce the destruction of a spy satellite last month and gave out sparse details about a rocket failure, space-watcher jim oberg said saturday
the official tass news agency reported that the upper stage of the proton rocket booster failed on wednesday and that on thursday ``the sputniks entered dense layers of the atmosphere and ceased their existence.''
according to u.s. space command, the largest chunk of debris from the mission re-entered the earth's atmosphere friday afternoon between saudi arabia and turkey, and a smaller chunk fell earlier near australia
besides the failure of the proton, with three satellites aboard, the soviets lost another satellite, cosmos 1,906, on jan. 31. the imaging satellite was launched on dec. 26 and was ``blown up to prevent the film and equipment from falling into the hands of western intelligence agencies,'' oberg said
since soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev came to power in march 1985, oberg said, the soviets ``have certainly released new material. but there remain severe limits. military stuff is clearly beyond the limit.''
still, oberg said, western technology can detect such events as the proton failure, and western news reports can force further disclosures from the soviets
penetrating the secretive soviet space program is nothing new for oberg, who has published his findings in a new book called ``uncovering soviet disasters: exploring the limits of glasnost.''
long before gorbachev's moderate reforms led to greater disclosure of problems in the soviet union, oberg had pieced together hair-raising tales of disasters that for decades went unreported in the state-controlled media
oberg has ``been working since childhood at this, watching their space program, looking for chinks in their secrecy, and driving through them.''
soviet secrecy can be dangerous, oberg wrote in his book. on oct. 24, 1962, a soviet space probe exploded into dozens of objects during the cuban missile crisis, the confrontation that brought the superpowers their closest to nuclear war
debris from the probe ``appeared without warning on american attack-warning radars in alaska,'' oberg wrote. ``the cuban missile crisis was at its height, and for a few moments the unannounced and unpredicted soviet space failure looked like the long-feared massive soviet (intercontinental ballistic missile) attack.''
the debris burned up as it entered the atmosphere. but, oberg said, the soviets have never publicly acknowledged the event
soviet media also have not reported on the most spectacular ``and probably the greatest disaster of the space age,'' the ``nedelin catastrophe,'' which on about oct. 24, 1960, killed scores of soviets including marshal mitrofan nedelin, the commander in chief of the soviet strategic rocket forces
the accident came three years after the soviets launched the first satellite, ``sputnik.'' operating in the strictest secrecy, the soviets launched two unmanned spacecraft on a probe to mars, but both fell back into the atmosphere and burned up because their upper stages failed
a third booster was loaded with fuel, and the order was given to launch. but the main rocket engine did not ignite. ``it just stood there on the launch pad, bathed in searchlights and fuming with clouds of supercold liquid oxygen,'' oberg wrote
nedelin made a fatal error and committed a gross violation of elementary rocket safety standards,'' oberg wrote. ``from the launch bunker, where he had prepared to watch the expected success, he ordered a team of engineers to inspect the rocket booster immediately. ...''
since he was an experienced combat commander, he would not send men into peril he himself avoided, so he walked out to the base of the rocket while the inspection was being made.''
although the main rocket failed to ignite, the uppermost stage continued to operate as though it were en route to mars, and at the time when it would have separated from the booster, fired its own rockets
a million pounds of kerosene and liquid oxygen flared up in a pyre which must have been visible for hundreds of miles,'' oberg wrote
the soviet press carried an official obituary of nedelin several days later, saying that he had ``died tragically in the line of duty'' in a plane crash
not a word has appeared since then in the official press, although writings smuggled out of russia or published by emgres have described the incident, and oberg pieced together the evidence
