the government has held separate talks with the rival opposition groups on reforming rules for the national assembly elections. the reunification democratic party favors a formula of electing more than one representative from each district
roh was catapulted to power after the two rival opposition groups split a majority of the votes during the dec. 16 election. treatment</head>
when an innocent bystander in an affluent los angeles neighborhood was killed in the crossfire of a gang gunbattle, local merchants asked for more police protection and quickly got it
the swift action following the jan. 30 incident sparked protest from many blacks and hispanics, who charged that similar requests from poorer minority neighborhoods fall on deaf ears
a week after the shooting local minority leaders publicized a new study to support claims that police react more slowly to emergencies in less affluent areas. police chief darryl gates released a letter friday from the study's author saying his findings had been misconstrued
the racial tug-of-war intensified last weekend when an off-duty black police officer was arrested as he stood on a street corner in an upscale neighborhood with six black youths. the officer said his group was conducting an informal ``sting'' operation to investigate alleged police harassment
none of those kids did anything except stand on that corner and be black _ and that was enough,'' said hawthorne police sgt. don jackson. police said jackson's group was blocking the sidewalk
gang violence fueled by drug trafficking has been a reality for years in the city's predominantly black and hispanic southside neighborhoods. drive-by shootings are commonplace, with innocent bystanders being killed by errant or ricocheting bullets
in one recent incident, a 67-year-old woman was killed in a drive-by shooting while she sat in a wheelchair in the doorway of her southside home
there were more than 300 gang-related murders in los angeles county in 1987. that figure may rise to 450 this year as gangs battle for control of the lucrative crack cocaine market, said michael genelin, head of the district attorney's gang division
and that's not the way it should be. we should be able to live normally,'' said barbara thomas, spokeswoman for the south central organizing committee, a group that claims a membership of 78,000 black families
gang violence has begun to move into more affluent, mainly white areas, illustrated by the jan. 30 shooting of 27-year-old karen toshima, who was caught in gang crossfire. she was killed in westwood village, a popular theater and restaurant district
when police stepped up patrols in the area, hundreds of southside residents demonstrated at lapd headquarters, charging that officials ignored daily death tolls in their communities
minority leaders publicized a just-released study ordered by the police commission and prepared by the public administration service in virginia. the study showed that police responded more slowly to crimes in poor areas than in the more affluent westside and san fernando valley, the leaders said
the police department then released a letter from peter bellmio, the principal author of the nearly 200-page report, that stated his findings had been misinterpreted
the letter said the actual conclusion was that the police department takes too long to respond to emergencies and does not significantly respond more rapidly in any of the city's geographical areas
bellmio said he was under contract not to comment publically until march 8, when he makes a formal report to the police commission
the deployment controversy has fanned other racial issues, such as the alleged harassment that prompted jackson to conduct his own ``sting.''
in an effort to prove that lapd officers were mistreating blacks, jackson and six friends gathered on a busy street corner in westwood, while an associate secretly videotaped the scene. officers arrested jackson on a misdemeanor charge and rounded up and frisked the others
police defended the arrest, saying jackson's group was blocking the sidewalk, refused to move when requested by officers and was dressed in attire similar to gang members'. jackson was released on his own recognizance pending a court hearing
more criticism of the police came monday when the rev. william johnson, of curry christian methodist episcopal temple, complained that when officers do patrol black neighborhoods, they come ``ready to do combat.''
mayor tom bradley, who is black, signed an ordinance wednesday that provided for the hiring of 150 more officers, increasing the force to its largest strength ever, 7,500 officers
we're determined to return this city to a drug-free, gang-free atmosphere,'' the mayor said
i've been telling the people of this city that we need hundreds more police officers,'' said gates, the police chief. ``we should focus on getting rid of the problems, and not on the complicated subject of deployment.''
some criminal experts say more officers won't make a difference in poor, crime-infested areas
historically, there's a resentment to an excessive show of force,'' said garrett capune, professor of criminology at the university of southern california and california state university
it has a racist overtone, you know; there seems to be more crime because there's more officers,'' he said. ``it becomes a sort of self-fulfilling prophecy.''
i don't know what these criminologists are all about,'' snapped city councilman nate holden, who represents a mainly black district. ``these guys can sit in some classroom and think what it's supposed to be like. but they haven't seen the real world. i resent them
let them come into the black community and see what it's like.''
a top pingpong player went to poland and took her son away from her ex-husband, then hid from polish authorities until she could sneak the boy into sweden, a newspaper said saturday
i have gone through hell, and the child has gone through hell,'' kaisa karlsson said in a telephone interview with the denver post from stockholm, where she and her son michael arrived friday
probably this night i can sleep,'' said karlsson's father, bohdan dawidowicz, also a top table tennis player, from his home in suburban aurora
karlsson, 26, has been fighting since 1983 to win custody of michael from her polish ex-husband, who was initially given custody in colorado and polish courts. she got the colorado ruling reversed, but the polish ruling stood and she took matters into her own hands a week ago saturday
she said she took her son away during her regular visit with him in warsaw, then hid in a series of homes, working her way from the warsaw suburbs to the port city of gdansk, the post reported
there they boarded a ferry for sweden late thursday
karlsson wouldn't say exactly how she got her son past polish police, who were looking for him
there are just too many people who could get in trouble,'' she said
karlsson and dawidowicz's battles with the polish government began shortly after dawidowicz decided to live in the united states in 1971 in the middle of an international table tennis tour
three years later, after going back to poland, they won permission for the whole family to come to the united states. she won tournament after tournament representing u.s. teams, and in 1978 became a u.s. citizen
in 1981, she married mitchell gaca, another polish immigrant. michael was born later that year. they were divorced in 1983, with custody initially given to gaca
karlsson battled back, but her travels on the table tennis circuit worked against her and in 1985 her ex-husband returned to poland with their son
the same year, karlsson introduced new evidence in her case and was awarded custody by an aurora court, but it was too late
karlsson and her father said they were disillusioned by the u.s. government's hands-off approach
the state department refused to intervene, saying polish law applied since gaca had gotten a polish court to award him custody
donna sherman, a spokeswoman for the consular division of the u.s. state department, said there is not much the government can do once a child is in another country's jurisdiction
we cannot do anything that violates the laws of that country,'' she said. ``we can arrange for meetings, to try and arrange some kind of conciliation, but we can't force it. we can't act as attorneys.''
karlsson, who has since married a swedish businessman, hopes to visit the united states this summer but says that in the meantime she and michael will relax in sweden
he needs a little rest. i think he'll be sticking around the house,'' she said
sikh gunmen set off a new wave of violence saturday in punjab state, killing 10 people and prompting police in the amritsar district and in new dehli go on red alert
the attacks raised the death toll in violence blamed on the separatist radicals to 32 since friday. at least 60 others were wounded
we are after the killers, the entire police force is on red alert,'' said amritsar district police superintendent mohammed izhar alam
road blocks were set up saturday throughout the farming state bordering pakistan, and punjab's 35,000-member police force was being aided by paramilitary troops in the search operations
in a related development, a hindu angered by the spate of killings entered a sikh temple and set fire to sikh holy book in wadala kala, a village 26 miles south of amritsar saturday, police said
we are worried, because this will give rise to tension,'' said police officer rajinder singh
the man, identified as atma ram, was arrested. singh said ram's younger brother had been slain by suspected sikh radicals last month
he was angry after he heard the news of the new killings. he went inside a gurdwara (sikh shrine) and set fire to the holy book,'' singh said
sikh militants have been fighting for a separate homeland in punjab since 1982. sikhs are a majority in punjab, but comprise only 2 percent of india's 800 million people, more than 80 percent of whom are hindus
the radicals want an independent homeland because they say the hindus discriminate against them
at least 250 people have been killed in sikh-related violence this year. last year more than 1,000 deaths were blamed on the separatists
among saturday's victims were two hindu farm laborers, a hindu trader and four sikh farmers. the remaining three have yet to be identified, police chief alam said
one person wounded in a bomb blast friday died of injuries saturday, hospital sources said
in the village of sahsra, nine members of farm family were killed with automatic rifles and revolvers friday night, along with a man staying at the house, alam said
residents in the village, about 18 miles southeast of amritsar, said about six sikh gunmen stormed into the home while the family slept
earlier friday, sikh bomb attacks killed 11 people. the bomb attacks were in the cities of amritsar, patiala, gurdaspur and hoshiarpur. the bombings later prompted police in new delhi to issue a red alert because of fears that the attacks might spread to the capital
on saturday an unexploded bomb was found in a fifth city, batala, the united news of india reported. the agency said the four-pound can of explosives was left in a store by a woman customer in the city 25 miles northeast of amritsar
police in new delhi advised residents not to pick up unknown objects and report movement of new people in their neighborhood
the sikh faith has elements of both hinduism and islam and was founded about 500 years ago as a peaceful alternative to the two warring religions
but the sikhs' 10th and last prophet, guru govind singh, declared sikhism as a warrior faith in which the adherents should all carry swords and the male should bear the name singh, ``lion'' in punjabi. say</head>
