a favorite of david's, according to one friend, is the group ``suicidal tendencies.'' a song on their latest album describes ``the maniac i'll meet. his love for me is like a father to a son. and now the maniac and i are one.''
the high school sophomore was arrested friday after an all-night manhunt in this city of 62,000 about 90 miles southeast of minneapolis
friends, according to krough, had heard david muse recently about wanting to hurt his family. they regarded that as an expression of typical teen-age alienation but never as a serious plan, the priest said
to most, david had a quiet magnetism at school, krough said. he was an avid bicyclist but not a ``jock.'' and he wasn't active in other extra-curricular activities at the 415-student parochial school, principal michael leahy said
there was a group of students he was the center of,'' krough said. ``i guess you would tend to call him an artistic, poetic kind of person, a deep-feeling person.''
about david and his friends, krough said, ``if there was ever a group of adolescents that fit the image of sensitive teens, that group would qualify.''
many of brom's friends wrote letters to be delivered to the olmsted county jail, and they defended him fiercely when questioned by reporters
the punk appearance he adopted the day of the killings, including shaving the sides of his head, dying his hair black and spiking it on the back of his head, seemed out of character to some
he wouldn't step on a flower,'' said schoolmate chris bromelkamp, whose locker is next to david's. ``he may have done something wrong, but there's a lot of people he touched.''
authorities were far from understanding what may have triggered the slayings, but sheriff charles von wald said one small piece came out in interviews with david's friends. the teen-ager and his father had an argument about a tape the boy had taken home, he said
also unexplained was how a boy described as an almost frail 130 pounds could commit the slayings with a 28-inch ax without anyone in the house escaping
chief deputy sheriff stan anderson would not comment on other details of the murders, such as where the weapon was obtained or why the suspect stayed in rochester after the killings
the victims were bernard brom, 41, paulette, 40, diane, 14, and rick, 11. the only family survivor other than david is his 19-year-old brother joseph, who has his own apartment in rochester
rochester is dominated by the mayo clinic and an ibm plant where the elder brom worked
mrs. brom had recently quit her job at the church to spend more time with her children, leahy noted
david did not appear to possess his parents' devout religious faith, krough said. ``david was a searcher,'' he said
roy acuff, ``the king of country music,'' celebrated his 50th anniversary on the grand ole opry by citing the fans of the long-running show
acuff, 84, received a standing ovation friday night when he appeared on the stage to mark his golden anniversary on the live program
this is a little special occasion for roy acuff,'' he told the audience after singing his best-known song, ``the wabash cannonball.''
i'm proud to have lived to see this day,'' he said. ``you are the ones who made roy acuff and the grand ole opry. have fun, i'm going to.''
moments before, when the curtain went up and the crowd rose, acuff playfully told the audience, ``sit down so i can sing.''
he later sang his version of ``blue eyes crying in the rain,'' a song willie nelson also turned into a hit
that was written for me by fred rose many, many years ago,'' acuff told the audience, which included representatives of rotary international from 22 countries. ``then willie nelson brought it back. he did a good job with it.''
acuff also saluted his dobro player, bashful brother oswald, who also was celebrating his 50th anniversary on the show
we haven't had a fight yet,'' acuff said
other opry stars joined in honoring acuff, a fiddler who came out of the east tennessee hills to become the opry's first genuine singing star
that's a long time, folks,'' singer del reeves said about the 50 years of performing. ``i hope he's here another 50.''
singer porter wagoner called acuff ``one of the grandest men in country music.'' singer connie smith dedicated her song ``once a day'' to him
johnny cash and his wife, june carter cash, were to have appeared on the show during a special segment honoring acuff, but canceled because both have the flu, opry officials said
the pry bills itself as the longest running radio show still on the air. it has never missed a broadcast since going on the air in 1925, meaning acuff has been on the program for all but 13 years of its existence
there are signs that child heart transplant recipients develop atherosclerosis and also have a worse survival rate than adults given new hearts, a transplant surgeon says
dr. d. glenn pennington, chief of the cardiac replacement service at st. louis university hospital in st. louis, said he has seen ``indications of development of atherosclerosis'' in child transplant recipients, and ``it may become more of a trend.''
atherosclerosis is the thickening of the internal lining of the blood vessels and the cause of coronary artery disease
as for survival rates, ``i think it is worse than adults,'' with infection the leading cause of death among children, pennington, a specialist in the use of artificial devices and in pediatric transplantation, said friday at an international conference on thoracic organ transplantion
he said children who have received transplants do not have worse problems with organ rejection than adults. but he said there is an increasing number of child transplants who need retransplantation because of progressive failure of the organs they have been given
i don't know what that means, but my suspicion is that if we transplant children in infancy we will probably have to retransplant at some point again,'' pennington said
there was encouraging news on transplants from a leader in transplantation for extremely young infants, dr. leonard l. bailey, of loma linda university medical center in california, who said some of his patients have exhibited an ``immune tolerance'' not seen in adults
as a result, several of the young recipients need only extremely small doses of the anti-rejection drug cyclosporine and may be withdrawn entirely from all drug therapy
my guess is that a number of the babies will be able to grow up without the need for immunosuppression,'' bailey said
cyclosporine is used in transplantation in combination with other drugs to suppress the body's immune system and keep it from turning against the donor heart
bailey said he believes the optimal therapy is diagnosis ``of heart disease in-utero, because that gives us a chance then from 35 weeks on to find a donor.''
he said that in his program's experience, transplants after more than the first few weeks of a child's life make for a ``much more difficult post-operative management problems. ... those who have been transplanted in the first month of life have really been a piece of cake.''
infants more than 3 to 3{ months old given transplants ``will reject with considerable vigor,'' requiring aggressive anti-rejection therapy, said bailey, who has performed heart transplants on the world's youngest infants, including a four-hour-old canadian boy last october. donor hearts</head>
the surgeon who transplanted a baboon's heart into an infant girl in 1984 says he's optimistic about the continuing research toward eventual use of animal heart transplants in humans
we're still really working vigorously in that area from all points of view, goats and sheep and primates,'' dr. leonard l. bailey said at a three-day international conference on thoracic organ transplantation that concluded saturday
researchers have turned to exploring the use of non-human organs for transplantation on either a temporary or possibly permanent basis, in part because of the lack of sufficient organ donors
in a controversial procedure in october 1984, bailey and his staff at loma linda university medical center transplanted the heart of a baboon into a 12-day-old girl known as baby fae
the child, born with a fatal heart defect, survived for 20 days before her body's immune system rejected the foreign-tissue transplant, or xenograft
rejection has been a major obstacle in xenografts
another problem area has been the ethical question of using a primate heart in humans, said dr. bartley p. griffith, of the university of pittsburgh
griffith, thoracic and cardiovascular surgeon at one of the nation's busiest transplant centers, said chimpanzees ``are almost too close'' to humans in terms of behavior and would raise a moral dilemma
nobody is talking about using chimpanzees, and yet they in fact are the most size-appropriate probably to use,'' he said
griffith added that baboons' hearts are small for human use and might eventually be used more appropriately as auxiliary hearts
bailey said the testing that has been conducted at the loma linda, calif., facility has involved a series of experiments, testing the ``xenograft bridge to allograft theory, and it's working out very well.'' an allograft is a same-species organ transplant
the testing, he said, includes using xenografts of green monkey hearts into baboons in temporary bridge-to-transplant situations
we still very firmly believe that a well-selected primate heart from a baboon will be virtually as good'' as a human allograft ``that may have no tissue match whatsoever and bear very little resemblance and genetic makeup'' to the original _ even as a permanent graft, he said
american banker and philanthropist david rockefeller unveiled a private non-profit foundation saturday that he said will aid hard-pressed farmers in this communist country
rockefeller met privately with polish communist leader gen. wojciech jaruzelski before formally inaugurating the foundation, which will raise pigs and export hams to the united states
it seems to me that what we all need to do is to find ways in which despite the ideological differences, we can work together,'' rockefeller said at a ceremony in warsaw's royal castle
organizers said the foundation brings poland its first new long-term western credits since the 1981 martial law crackdown and will serve as a model for western institutions wishing to provide financial assistance to the debt-stricken country
but the size of the credits, $2.4 million, is miniscule compared to poland's burgeoning foreign debt, now standing at $39.2 billion
the foundation for the development of polish agriculture is the result of the personal interest of rockefeller and the rockefeller brothers' fund, said leon irish, chairman of the foundation's organizing committee
its first project will be the development of swine production to increase exports of premium polish hams to the united states by 14 percent
the foundation will borrow money to import to poland high-protein feed concentrates from the united states for sale to polish farmers under a contract arrangement
the farmers will use the feed to raise swine more efficiently. the swine will be sold to polish meat processors in partnership with the foundation
hams resulting from the arrangement will be exported to the united states, with a portion staying in poland for domestic sale
proceeds from the exports will repay foreign loans and be used for other foundation projects, irish said
unlike other east bloc nations where cooperative farming predominates, private farmers control 75 percent of the farmland in poland and produce 80 percent of the crop
the foundation is to be governed by a council with 60 percent u.s. and western european membership and 40 percent private polish membership
two city ambulance workers face disciplinary charges because they waited for their sandwiches in a delicatessen before responding to a report of a heart attack victim 1{ blocks away, officials said saturday
the man died in the incident wednesday in the bronx
the emergency medical service said its investigation had substantiated allegations of delay. both crew members had been reassigned to clerical duties and faced disciplinary charges, it said
ems director james kerr said it was impossible to know whether the delay, which he said amounted to 5 minutes, had cost the stricken man his life. but he said ems policy requires ambulance crews to respond immediately
the crew had just ordered sandwiches to go when a man ran in into the deli at 8:30 p.m. wednesday and said someone had suffered a heart attack in the church of the mediator, kerr said
instead of leaving at once, the investigation showed, the pair waited for their sandwiches, kerr said. he declined to identify the crew or discuss possible penalties. bombing raid</head> casualties. picks up 7th graf pvs, `on friday ...'</note>
south african fighter planes flew revenge raids on guerrilla bases in angola at dawn saturday, a day after a bomb killed 18 people in a namibian bank
angolan authorities said several civilians were killed
more than a dozen mirage and impala aircraft attacked three bases of the south-west african peoples organization in southern angola, the defense force chief, gen. jannie geldenhuys, said in a statement
he said the attacks avenged the bombing friday of the first national bank in oshakati, south-west africa, where 18 people were killed and 31 injured. most of the dead were black government employees cashing their weekly paychecks
geldenhuys accused swapo of the bank bombing. the guerrilla group has been fighting for 22 years against south africa's occupation of south-west africa, also known as namibia
on friday, swapo denied involvement in the bank blast, the deadliest in namibia in two decades. it has claimed responsibility for other bombings in namibia
swapo officials in london declined to comment on saturday's raid
later saturday, angola's defense ministry said the air assault on lubango and onjiva left several civilians dead
a statement reported by the official angolan news agency angop said the exact number of victims had not yet been determined, according to a report monitored in lisbon
the angop report made no mention of swapo or geldenhuys' announcement
on friday, south african defense minister magnus malan and foreign minister roelof ``pik'' botha warned neighboring states that south african troops would undertake unannounced ``hot pursuit'' raids across borders to fight guerrilla groups
we have repeatedly invited them (neighboring states) to talk with us to sort our problems in peace. now they have demonstrated they are not interested,'' botha said, reacting to news of the namibian bombing. ``as far as i'm concerned there is no more talk of a regional conference _ not from our side. we're no longer interested in the neighboring states.''
geldenhuys said eight mirage fighters took part in the attack on two targets near lubango, about 190 miles north of the namibian-angolan border; and five impala aircraft attacked targets at ongiva, about 25 miles north of the border
geldenhuys said all the south african aircraft returned safely, but gave no estimate of casualties inflicted
he said the lubango targets were ``swapo's most important training center in angola, the tobias hainyeko training center, and a terrorist holding area about 10 kms (6.2 miles) west of there.''
an air force source told the associated press that the jets that attacked lubango were probably mirage f1-as, a french-designed fighter-bomber capable of carrying about 14,000 pounds of bombs
the impalas are a south african version of an italian aermacchi light attack craft. they can carry sidewinder air-to-air missiles and are able to carry about 4,000 pounds of missiles or bombs
the general said swapo had launched a number of attacks from ongiva on civilians in south-west africa
in 1971, the united nations ruled that south africa's occupation of namibia was illegal. but south africa has defied the court and continued its occupation
only about 70,000 of namibia's 1.3 million people are white, and the south african government has installed a multiracial transitional administration to run the territory's affairs
swapo has refused to negotiate with the transitional government, citing the u.n. resolution demanding free elections
south african and south-west african troops have been fighting for about five months in angola on behalf of the unita rebel movement, which is battling the marxist government in luanda. south african officials say they will not grant independence to namibia until the 40,000 cuban troops supporting angola's marxist government leave africa
all of south africa's black-ruled neighbors _ swaziland, lesotho, mozambique, botswana and angola _ have accused south africa of staging unannounced cross-border raids during the past 10 years, killing dozens of civilians as well as alleged guerrillas
south african officials have denied, refused to comment on, or ridiculed most of the claims, although they did announce a raid last year on livingstone, zambia
but military officials have acknowledged previous ``hot pursuit'' operations against swapo in southern angola
botha and malan presented their statement friday as a new get-tough policy against neighboring governments which, they say, allow the anti-apartheid african national congress, swapo and other guerrilla organizations to stage attacks on south africa from their territories
by law and custom in south africa, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
the organizer of a planned blood bank for chaste donors says he hopes to expand into a national network of christian blood banks, a plan one physician called a dangerous attempt to capitalize on fear of aids
dr. condon hughes said he hopes to open lifeblood, a christian blood bank that will not accept promiscuous donors, by early april. blood donors will be asked to sign a statement confirming they have abstained from sex or been faithful to a spouse since 1977
the blood also will be tested for aids and other blood-borne viruses, hughes said
my intention is to inform heterosexuals that if they have more than one faithful partner that they are at risk of developing a deadly disease ... and to provide blood from people who do not fall into that category,'' hughes said
but dr. ronald gilcher, of the oklahoma blood institute, said hughes inaccurately implies that lifeblood's supply will be safer than other blood banks
and u.s. food and drug administration spokeswoman susan cruzan noted that the fda's list of risk categories does not include promiscuous heterosexuals
what we see this doing is undermining the donor base ... confusing people, creating distrust and a lack of credibility,'' gilcher said. ``we think that is a dangerous thing.''
i commend what he's doing in the sense of trying to create a safer blood supply because that's what we're all doing, but the method by which dr. hughes is trying to do this i think is unsound,'' gilcher said. ``i think it's dangerous because it could create a lack of availability of blood products.''
gilcher said existing blood banks already screen donors and test donated blood
the blood supply is safe, but it's not 100 percent safe,'' gilcher said. ``there is no such thing as a zero risk. the public wants a zero risk, but it doesn't exist.''
gilcher said hughes' exclusion of heterosexuals who have had more than one partner since 1977 relies on the honesty of the donor and the honesty of the donor's sexual partner. he said it also dangerously limits the pool of potential donors
but hughes said he thinks chaste and faithful donors can supply the nation with blood
five percent of the nation provides the blood for the entire nation,'' hughes said. ``i am confident that there is 5 percent of the nation that is chaste. our goal is to identify those individuals and encourage them to give blood, take a stand for morality and administer the love of christ through blood donations.''
aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is an affliction in which a virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers. one method of transmission is through infected blood or blood products
the fda requires all blood banks to provide potential donors with information about aids and ask them to refrain from donating if they fall into certain risk categories
the fda constantly reviews categories,'' cruzan said. ``the category of promiscuous heterosexuals was discussed in 1986. epidemiologists concluded at that time that the heterosexual spread of hiv (the aids virus) was not a significant reason to exclude this category.''
hughes said he plans to sell blood on a first-come, first-served basis regardless of religion or sexual activity. for a fee, donors will be allowed to have their own blood frozen for their own use
the cost of the blood is going to be determined primarily by the number of donors that we have. we hope it will be comparable to the (non-profit) oklahoma blood institute. we may be at a disadvantage because we have to pay taxes,'' hughes said
a motorist whose heart was apparently bigger than his nose rescued an injured skunk saturday but could not find an animal hospital to help, police said
the man, whom police declined to identify, found the animal off interstate 393 and bundled it into his car. he first took the skunk to the fish and game department, but no one was there, so he went to the police, said lt. james fletcher
we couldn't find an animal hospital who would do something with an injured skunk,'' he said. the animal apparently had been hit by a vehicle and was badly injured, so police put it out of its misery, fletcher said
as for the good samaritan, fletcher said, the smell ``didn't seem to bother him. i was a little surprised.''
a sit-in launched by 200 university of massachusetts students at the start of a snowy holiday weekend seemed doomed by doubt and disarray, leaders of the little rebellion by minorities recalled
you do not take a building on a night before a major snowstorm that will close it anyway and which is going to be closed for an entire holiday weekend,'' michael thelwell, a black professor, said he warned the protesters at the start of the occupation
but by the end of the six-day occupation of new africa house, hundreds of white students had displayed their sympathy in rallies and vigils, money and supplies had poured in from around the nation and even the chancellor had expressed admiration for the protesters, who won several concessions from the school
we weren't organized. all we had were these five little demands,'' said jo ella costello, a negotiator for the group. ``but something had brought us all together. that was the fascinating thing. by the third day, we knew it was working.''
the takeover began feb. 11 after students met with chancellor joseph d. duffey to discuss the demands. troubled by recent acts of racial violence on campus, the protesters insisted on the disciplining of five white students accused of beating two blacks, and they demanded a stop to the encroachment of other school departments on new africa house, a third world center
tension had festered since an october 1986 beating of a black student by several whites following the boston red sox loss to the new york mets in the final game of the world series
the disorganized protesters refused to meet with duffey the morning after the takeover, but began forming committees to handle finances, security, media questions and negotiations, and they imposed strict procedures on meetings
the rules proved successful. ``we started voting on everything,' costello said. ``we even voted on which movies to watch.''
support began pouring in from the campus and beyond. the black faculty senate said members would risk arrest with the protesters if the chancellor called in police to remove them from the building, costello said
the massachusetts teachers association volunteered to strike in the same event, she said. some 500 white students staged a rally outside the building to lend their support
costello said she knew the protesters had won widespread support when she went to a nearby dormitory for a shower: ``they said, `you all from new africa house?' i said, `yeah. anybody got any soap?' they ran to get it. they'd give us deodorant, anything.''
costello was among four women and five men elected by the protesters to negotiate with the chancellor
a meeting scheduled for monday had to be postponed when duffey went to visit a brother who had undergone major surgery. the protesters sent the chancellor a card and duffey responded with a basket of fruit
we had old-timers with us saying, `my god, i've been going to sit-ins for 20 years and i've never seen anything like this,'' costello said
duffey and the students met tuesday and talked for more than four hours
but then the group that had been occupying the house was suddenly outnumbered by minorities returning to the campus from the holiday weekend
they were acting like we'd sold out,'' saidcostello
i was really hurt by all these people who hadn't been there the whole time. i asked them, `where were you?'''
the newcomers left early wednesday and the stalwart core voted to accept duffey's responses to their demands, which included timetables for the hiring of minority faculty and a promise to leave the new africa house in the hands of the third world community
costello said the agreement was a victory that will enhance the school's image among whites and blacks
i think umass will get the reputation of fighting racism,'' she said. ``this is terrific, what's happening here.''
relief services for about 260,000 palestinian refugees in lebanon will be cut to the minimum because of the kidnapping of two scandinavian employees of the u.n. relief and works agency, the agency said saturday
there will be noticeable changes in unrwa services and activities because of security problems and the lack of freedom of movement,'' said agency spokesman niall kiely
we feel agency staff, be they foreign nationals or locals, are under threat to their physical safety.''
unrwa employees jan stening, 44 of sweden, and william jorgensen, 58, of norway, were kidnapped feb. 5. unrwa said palestinians, acting independently of guerrilla factions, kidnapped the men for personal motives
kiely said only four of the 14 international staff assigned to lebanon remained in west beirut and ``they are very heavily involved in the search for stening and jorgensen.''
he said he was ``reasonably hopeful'' that the scandinavians would be released because ``there are no real setbacks'' in negotiations. he did not elaborate
kiely said unrwa has canceled a repair program for beirut's war-ravaged chatilla and bourj el-barajneh palestinian refugee camps ``because it can't be supervised.''
about 2,200 local relief workers serve with unrwa at field centers in lebanon
kiely said another impact of the kidnappings in south lebanon was that all unrwa transports between beirut and the southern port cities of sidon and tyre have been stopped both ways
he said agency operations such as schools ``have a certain momentum, so for the moment many services will continue to run as before.'' activist and family arriving in sweden.</note>
the government in estonia accused u.s. senators of trying to ruin soviet-american relations and scuttle nuclear disarmament by encouraging nationalist demonstrations in the baltic republic, tass said saturday
the official soviet news agency said the presidium of the supreme soviet of estonia issued a statement saying the senators are ``taking part in a new propaganda farce. they advocate a favorable attitude to anti-soviet actions planned to be held in estonia by some groups.''
such steps can further only one political aim _ to hamper the improvement of soviet-american relations and to undermine the nuclear disarmament process,'' tass said
the statement was the latest manifestation of a dispute between the government and nationalist activists, supported by western politicians, over the fate of the baltic states
the states, estonia, lithuania and latvia, were independent until they were incorporated into the soviet union in 1940. some residents believe their national identity and religious freedom are suppressed under soviet rule
moscow-based dissidents said some lithuanians demonstrated tuesday to celebrate the 70th anniversary of the declaration of independence from soviet russia months after the bolshevik revolution of 1917. wednesday is estonia's anniversary of independence, and activists say they plan protests there also
this month, 32 u.s. senators wrote to kremlin leader mikhail s. gorbachev asking him not to interfere with demonstrations and religious services in the baltics. the senators urged gorbachev ``not only to allow the lithuanian and estonian people to peacefully honor their national independence days, but also to take all necessary measures to guarantee that they do not become targets of state-sponsored harassment.''
estonia's presidium shot back that ``those who call into question the choice made by estonia in 1940, when it joined the union of soviet socialists republics as a full-fledged member, oppose the will of our people, the policy of perestroika, the principles of humanism and the policy of peace.''
perestroika is the name of gorbachev's wide-ranging program to reform soviet society
in a speech to the communist party central committee on thursday, gorbachev acknowledged the nationalities problem remains thorny. he said soviets must respect the language and culture of national groups but that nationalism aimed at ``self-isolation lead only to a spiritual blind alley.''
the presidium statement also acknowledged the nationalities problem, but said some people are taking advantage of the recent soviet campaign for openness ``as a means of kindling hostility among the nationalities living on estonian territory. this fully applies to the groups that emerged in estonia which try to put soviet estonia and its history in a bad light.''
tass did not say when the presidium of the supreme soviet of estonia, the republic's nominal parliament, issued the statement
last august, thousands of people demonstrated in estonia's capital and those of the other baltic states on the anniversary of a secret agrement between nazi germany and the soviet union the led to the soviet takeover of the baltic states in 1940
the u.s. government has never recognized the soviet incorporation of the baltic states
in a related development, an estonian political activist and his family of six arrived in sweden saturday after being expelled from the soviet union
about 30 exiles greeted rein metz, his wife and five small children at the airport
metz told swedish television at stockholm's arlanda airport he was the leader of a ``religious and political association.'' he said he expected ``30-40'' more members of his congregation could be forced to leave
i greet you in the name of jesus,'' he told some 30 exiles at the airport
last weekend two converted estonian buddhists arrived in sweden after given the choice of going to jail or leave the country. one of them, eke-part nomm, 22, said he had probably been forced to leave because he read an appeal to form an estonian independence party at a meeting in the city of tartu on feb. 2
a leader of the congressional iran-contra probe says he can't understand why vice president george bush remains reluctant to discuss his role in the affair months after president reagan opened the administration's books
i don't know why he's been so hesitant to acknowledge that he supported the president in it'' said arthur liman, chief senate counsel in the investigation. ``he was not a decisive factor.''
liman, 55, was on the hawaiian island of maui on thursday preparing to address tuesday's meeting of the federal bar council, an association of judges. he made the comments in an interview with the maui news newspaper
the vice president now talks about the fact that his conversations with the president were privileged and he can't reveal them,'' liman said. ``the reality of it is, the president waived executive privilege. i saw memos, diaries, other documents reflecting meetings attended by the vice president and the president
there was never any document withheld on that ground, either by the vice president or the president,'' liman said. ``all of the damaging evidence came as a result of the white house's production of documents.''
liman said evidence presented to the congressional committees shows the decision to sell arms to iran was made by the president, and the vice president supported him. liman said if bush had opposed the plan, it wouldn't have made a difference
the president heard arguments on both sides and made his own decision,'' liman said. to be friendly. pick up 3rd pvs, `but any...' edits thereafter to conform</note>
john demjanjuk's yearlong nazi war crimes trial was supposed to serve as a vivid history lesson to young israelis, but it gave way to lengthy technical debates that some say trivialized the horrors of the holocaust
demjanjuk, the second man to stand trial in israel on nazi war crimes charges, became more human to many israelis than adolf eichmann, the first, because he learned some hebrew and his family attended nearly every session
he chatted with police guards, laughed good naturedly during sessions and shouted the hebrew greeting ``shalom'' to bystanders as he was led handcuffed to and from court
he even tried to shake hands with a death camp survivor, who recoiled in horror and called demjanjuk a murderer
but any sympathy demjanjuk might have won was virtually undone by a stumbling defense team that seemed to move two steps backward for every step forward
for months before the trial ended last week, israelis stood in line to get a seat in the converted movie theater where five holocaust survivors recounted how a guard called ``ivan the terrible'' mutilated jews with sadistic pleasure before driving them into gas chambers at the treblinka death camp in nazi-occupied poland
but interest waned and frustration mounted when the survivors' emotional accounts of nazi atrocities were replaced by a time-consuming, often repetitive debate over the issue of identification
demjanjuk, 67, a retired ohio autoworker, maintains he is not ivan but an innocent victim of mistaken identity
this trial truly displayed the banality of justice,'' ephraim zuroff, a new york-born israeli and nazi hunter, said in an interview. ``there's no question that people got frustrated by the triviality and technicalities.''
hundreds of exhibits, even a paperclip, were submitted in an effort to determine the authenticity of a key piece of prosecution evidence, demjanjuk's alleged nazi identity card
six prosecution experts testified the card was authentic and an equal number of defense witnesses maintained it was forged
demjanjuk contended the document was fabricated by the soviet union to punish him for fighting in an anti-communist unit at the end of world war ii
for many israelis, there was a difference between eichmann, the man who masterminded adolf hitler's final solution, and ivan, who carried them out. eichmann was convicted and hanged in 1962
unlike eichmann, whom spectators glimpsed only as he was tried behind a bullet-proof screen, demjanjuk had a human dimension that intensified the emotion of the trial
the ukrainian-born defendant's wife, vera, his three children and 2-year-old grandson frequently watched the proceedings from front row seats and their anguish was recorded in israeli newspapers and on television
shame on you! you have no heart!'' mrs. demjanjuk screamed tearfully at prosecutors when the trial ended thursday and accused them of lying and failing to give her husband a fair trial
the three-judge panel, which has retired to review more than 15,000 pages of testimony and some 500 exhibits, is expected to issue a verdict in april
if convicted, demjanjuk faces a maximum penalty of death. but it is widely believed the sentence will not exceed life in prison
on thursday, one member of the audience, holocaust survivor mordechai fuchs, 63, displayed the pain of dozens of nazi victims who attended the proceedings over the year
waving a tattered photograph of his parents, three brothers and a sister killed at treblinka, he sobbed: ``the defense lawyers are liars. ... why does this have to be such a performance?''
but many israelis believe the attempt to probe into details showed the trial was fair
it wasn't a quick open-and-shut case,'' said toby greenwald, a cleveland-born israeli. ``no matter what the verdict, no one can ever say there wasn't enough time spent on detail. that's important, because people will ask whether jewish judges can be fair in a war crimes trial.''
some of his supporters, however, claimed demjanjuk did not get a fair hearing, partly because of his own faltering defense team and the trial's publicity. some witnesses watched others testify on israel television before they took the stand
demjanjuk, frustrated by his defense, fired mark o'connor of buffalo, n.y., his attorney of seven years, midway through the proceedings
several defense witnesses were discredited, including one who retracted her testimony and another who tried to commit suicide after her credentials were called into question
some of the defense arguments seemed bizarre. even demjanjuk squirmed uncomfortably in his seat when a defense expert claimed the soviet secret service used ``thought power'' to kill its enemies and inflict disasters on the west
demjanjuk's own contradictory version of his whereabouts during world war ii also appeared to hurt his case
until the defense began its case, i was not convinced of demjanjuk's guilt,'' said ehud offer, a 31-year-old israeli sculptor. ``but the defense itself has erased the doubts.''
fire officials and university of vermont researchers saturday picked through the rubble of a nationally known laboratory for maple tree research destroyed by fire
the laboratory at the university-affiliated proctor maple research farm was engulfed in flames friday night in a fire of undetermined origin, university officials said
frederick laing, an associate professor long involved in research at the farm, said efforts in recent years had centered on finding a cause for declines in maple syrup production in vermont and around the northeast
much of that research had been looking into whether acid precipitation, atmospheric pollutants carried into the northeast on winds out of the midwest, was to blame for recent maple production declines
laing said saturday that it was now ``generally agreed that it (acid rain) is one of the stresses'' causing the slump in maple sugaring. ``there's still some difficulty in assessing just how large a part it plays.''
the fire, which laing said destroyed between $200,000 and $250,000 worth of equipment, comes with this year's maple sugar season about a month away. it was unclear saturday whether the lab or some replacement facility could be geared up in time
rayburn levigne, a uvm assistant vice president for buildings and facilities, said while the cause of the fire was unknown, it was not believed to have been arson
possibly spooked by light at the end of the tunnel, deer have been shy about using four passageways recently installed for them under a new maryland interstate highway
the state highway administration built four corrugated steel culverts under sections of interstate 97 near annapolis in hopes of encouraging animals to cross under instead of over the roadway
researchers at the university of maryland's appalachian environmental laboratory in frostburg are trying to find out if animals are using the underpasses. so far they've found mink, mice, muskrat and raccoon, but no deer have ventured through the dimly lighted pathways
to us, the opening (at the other end) looks fairly large,'' said william r. gates, a graduate assistant working on the project. ``but for deer, it's like going into a cave or tunnel and they aren't used to going into enclosures.''
several other states have tried culverts, but little has been done to document their use
the state and federal highway administrations are funding the $210,000, five-year study in hopes of finding a way to reduce the number of animals killed on american highways
according to the federal highway administration, an estimated 200,000 deer die each year on u.s. roads. however, doug smith, an fha ecologist, said the number was a conservative estimate. more than 25,000 are killed each year on roads in states with high deer populations, such as pennsylvania
the study also aims to learn more about what happens to a wildlife area when it is bisected by a highway. the interstate cuts through woods near crownsville state hospital
researchers are observing tracks and using a wildlife surveillance system to monitor animal activity in the culverts. movement at the tunnel openings trips sensors on video cameras, which film the activity day or night
so far we had a deer enter the culvert and then come back out,'' gates said
recent flooding inside the tunnels might have discouraged some animals from using them, but gates said he suspected the culverts might not be large enough
three of the culverts are 15 feet high, 21 feet wide and about as long as a football field. the fourth is even longer, at more than 500 feet. perhaps the deer assume they cannot get through what they perceive is a tiny opening at the other end, gates said
the only evidence i have is that we have had several deer approach the culverts, but they have not gone in,'' he said
if the culverts prove successful, they would be a cheaper than bridges, which cost four to five times more to build and maintain, said william l. branch, environmental specialist with maryland's highway administration
the japan communist party has accused communist north korea of bombing a south korean airliner that vanished with 115 aboard off the coast of burma last november
the party, in an official publication obtained saturday by the associated press, stressed that communism has nothing to do with terrorism and that true communists should denounce such violence
we firmly believe that the north actually did it,'' wrote party central committee chairman kenji miyamoto in the publication
north korea has denied any involvement in the jet's disappearance, and accused seoul of engineering the incident to malign pyongyang
the korean air boeing 707, on its way from the middle east to seoul, disappeared on nov. 29
on jan. 15, a woman said in a public confession in seoul that she was a north korean agent and that she and a male north korean agent had planted a bomb on the aircraft during an earlier leg of the plane's flight
the woman, identified as kim hyon hui, 26, said kim jong il, son and heir apparent of north korean president kim il sung, had ordered the sabotage because he wanted to disrupt the 1988 summer olympics, to begin in seoul sept. 17
the north korean pair, traveling on forged japanese passports, left the plane in abu dhabi, its last stop before it vanished, flew to bahrain and were stopped for questioning at bahrain airport on dec. 1. both swallowed poison before being questioned. the man died but the woman survived. she was extradited to seoul on dec. 15
japanese communists have been at odds with north korean communist leaders since the early 1970s over ideological differences, often denouncing the personality cult surrounding kim il sung and jong il
the people of dixon are reading about life in dickson, siberia, thanks to the efforts of mayor james dixon and his soviet counterpart
this week, dixon received 100 copies of the dickson newspaper ``sovetsky taimyr,'' printed in english. ordinarily, the daily newspaper is printed only in russian
we want this issue to link us like a bridge over the cold ocean that lies between us. we want you to see ... that not so many things divide us after all,'' editor-in-chief albion brechalov wrote in a front-page story
the friendship between the two cities began in january, when the mayor of dickson, siberia, sent new year's greetings to the people of dixon, ill
mayor dixon replied, suggesting a citizen exchange visit, and he announced earlier this month that he had been notified that dickson's mayor, an interpreter and a journalist will visit dixon for a week, though no date has been set
the dickson newspaper tries to show everyday life in that siberian city, which is roughly a third the size of dixon, a community of 15,000 in north-central illinois. on the front page of the newspaper, dated november 1987, is a picture of three bundled woman eating ice cream bars
half of the newspaper contains carefully written letters from citizens expressing friendship and a hope for world peace. some also expressed opposition to the policies of president reagan, who spent his boyhood and high school years in dixon
mayor dixon says he is sending dickson 19 large photographs, taken by local amateurs, that show life in dixon
the government is sending tortilla-grams to remind illegal aliens that the deadline to apply for immigration amnesty is less than three months away
we're trying anything we can think of to get people the information,'' said jane friday, an immigration and naturalization service spokeswoman
the ins has printed 80,000 spanish-language reminders on 4-by-6-inch pieces of paper, and next week plans to send them to tortilla factories in brownfield, odessa and lovington, n.m., where they will be stuffed into packages
we have had lots of publicity in larger areas. the purpose of this grass-roots publicity campaign is to get out the word in the smaller areas,'' ms. friday said
the text of the inserts says: ``act now. take advantage of the legalization program. amnesty ends may 4, 1988. if you have lived in the united states illegally since before jan. 1, 1982, perhaps you qualify. for peace of mind, legalize your status. for more information, please contact your local legalization office.''
the bakeries agreed to include the reminders in their tortilla packages as a public service and at no charge to the government, ms. friday said
the ins has been using more traditional outlets _ churches, schools and public service broadcasts _ to remind people in metropolitan areas that the government's amnesty offer expires may 4
yuri and tanya zieman got bad news again last week. their latest application for an exit visa was turned down by soviet authorities
vladimir tufeld learned friday that he, too, had once more been refused
their disappointment was aggravated by the timing, for the latest rejection notices arrived on the eve of secretary of state george shultz's visit to moscow, an event many jewish ``refuseniks'' had hoped would help get them out
in the past, the soviets often have lowered emigration barriers just before high-level u.s.-soviet talks, but there is no indication shultz's scheduled arrival on sunday has had much effect
people are pinning so many hopes on him that i'm afraid it's going to be a very pathetic frustration for many,'' mrs. zieman said. ``there is nothing to pin your hopes on now.''
a senior western diplomat who watches trends in soviet emigration and other human rights matters, said, ``what had been some fairly steady but limited improvement (last year) may have come to a halt.''
as for freeing of political prisoners, ``the process has stopped'' following the release last year of dozens of religious, humans rights and nationalist activists, the diplomat said. he spoke only on condition he not be identified
observers say one possible reason the flow of jewish emigrants appears to have slowed from last year's unusually high levels is that the issue is receiving less official and public attention now
most of the best-known ``refuseniks'' have left in recent months, said one diplomatic analyst, and although thousands of would-be emigrants are left behind, they aren't as well organized and don't have as effective a voice as some of the jewish activists who have recently been granted exit visas
the ziemans first applied for permission to emigrate when their daughter, vera, was a baby. vera is now 11 years old and has grown up knowing she and her family could leave at any time. but while they wait, they are outcasts
yuri zieman, 50, lost his job as a computer programmer in the biomedical field as soon as he applied to leave and worked until recently as a janitor. the family's plight has taken on a new urgency since yuri suffered a potentially deadly aneurysm in the brain several weeks ago and doctors warned him not to risk the delicate surgery to repair the afflicted artery unless he can reach the west
although zieman says he never had access to state secrets, the only reason he and his family have been given for the authorities' refusal to permit them to leave is that theirs is a ``security'' case
tufeld's wife, isolda, was granted a three-month visa in december to enable her to have surgery for a brain tumor. she remains in johns hopkins university hospital in baltimore, md., after undergoing three operations last month, her husband said saturday
jewish emigration reached a peak of about 51,000 in 1979, but dropped after that as u.s.-soviet relations worsened. in 1986, fewer than 1,000 were allowed to emigrate. the number rose above 8,000 last year for the first time since 1979 but appears to have reached a plateau or declined since the u.s.-soviet summit in december in washington
some refuseniks blame soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's public annoyance at being questioned repeatedly on the subject. others fear the u.s. government has lost some of its persistence in the drive to improve relations and reach a strategic nuclear weapons accord with the kremlin
in the meantime, new groups of jews are forming to press their exit demands
one, calling itself the new wave, announced it will hold demonstrations every week in downtown moscow to protest the refusal of soviet authorities to recognize its members' eligibility for visas because they acknowledge they don't have immediate relatives abroad
another group, called the second generation, consists of young people whose parents have spent years trying unsuccessfully to leave the country. the children, many now in their teens or 20s, have grown up expecting that one day they would go to the west with their parents but now find they are barred, just as their parents were. include material from newsweek poll.</note>
richard gephardt's past has become his present, dredged up endlessly by democratic presidential rivals who ask whether his evolution on issues from abortion to busing is a troubling lack of conviction
the attacks on gephardt and his record could seriously damage the missourian's candidacy if voters come to perceive the six-term congressman as insincere in his beliefs, according to political professionals
it's clearly everybody's best shot at gephardt,'' says democratic pollster geoffrey garin
what voters are really looking for is somebody who says what he means and means what he says during the election year.''
gephardt has switched his positions on issues such as abortion and school busing since arriving in the house in 1977 to represent a blue-collar st. louis district
gephardt explains his changes as a natural evolution of his views and says they are unrelated to the start of his national campaign. but gephardt's democratic presidential rivals suggest they are flip-flops of political convenience
what i try to do in approaching issues is to do it from a practical point of view, to ask what will solve a particular problem,'' gephardt has said. ``i have strong beliefs about things _ arms control, central american policy, tax reform, trade, health care, social security and what have you _ but i don't come to those from an ideological viewpoint. i try to look at the facts of a particular issue.''
the attacks against gephardt heated up last week during a democratic debate in texas when sen. albert gore jr. mentioned several of gephardt's voting zig-zags and said, ``i'm going to lay it on the line, dick. the next president has to be someone who the people will believe will stay with his convictions.''
sen. paul simon employed a similar attack strategy against gephardt's voting record in television commercials aired during the new hampshire primary campaign. the ads asked voters whether they could trust a candidate like gephardt who had changed his positions
a newsweek magazine poll of 284 democratic leaders and politicians rated gephardt last among the party's seven presidential candidates. the poll, taken on feb. 17-19 and published this week, asked if the candidates have been ``generally consistent in their stands on issues or not.''
fifty-eight percent said gephardt had not been consitent, and 38 percent said he had, according to the newsweek poll. by contrast, former colorado sen. gary hart, who was sixth, was rated as inconsistent by 38 percent and consistent by 49 percent and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, who was first, received an 86 percent consistent rating and 5 percent inconsistent
gephardt has obviously been wounded by the way that simon basically drew out his record,'' says robert squier, a democratic political consultant
but squier contends it will be more difficult and far more expensive for candidates like gore to launch a similar tv offensive against gephardt in the south because of the large number of states participating in the super tuesday primaries on march 8
i would guess that the gephardt people feel like they have been through a near miss,'' says squier
here are some of gephardt's positions
_abortion: gephardt started his career in congress backing anti-abortion constitutional amendments but dropped his support in 1986, saying there was ``no clear agreement in the country'' on an amendment and that was hurting the chances for resolving the controversial issue. he says he continues to oppose federal financing of abortions but has pledged not to veto congressional appropriations of such money if elected president
_busing: gephardt sponsored a constitutional amendment in the 97th congress to prohibit forced busing of school children for desegregation, a position in line with the views of his mostly white working-class district in south st. louis. he says he no longer supports such an amendment because ``it's a completely different situation.''
the justice department and the courts are doing something very different which i think is working,'' says gephardt. ``today they use magnet schools, voluntary plans and other methods of trying to get schools integrated, and i think they're much more effective.''
_social security: in 1985, gephardt joined with conservative southern democrats in supporting a deficit-cutting package that eliminated cost-of-living increases for social security and other federal retirement benefits. the proposal was rejected in the house. in his presidential campaign, gephardt says social security should be taken out of the budget so it does not become entangled in deficit-reduction fights on capitol hill. he also says he would no longer support a freeze on social security adjustments
_defense: in 1981, gephardt reversed his long-standing opposition to the mx missile and b-1 bomber and voted for the weapons systems sought by president reagan. in later years, he renewed his opposition. gephardt says he was wrong in changing his position and did so to give president reagan a bargaining chip in arms control talks with the soviet union
gephardt supported former president carter's proposal for a neutron bomb and in 1982 backed a reagan push for production of new chemical weapons. as president, gephardt says, he would press for a ban on all nerve gas and chemical weapons. he also is supporting a liberal democratic proposal to ban nuclear tests
_taxes: gephardt, a critic of reagan's economic policies, supported the administration's income tax cut proposal in 1981. he initially voted against the gop plan because he supported a democratic alternative. however, he backed the tax cut measure on final passage as did several other democratic leaders, including house ways and means chairman dan rostenkowski. gephardt has defended his vote, saying: ``once we lost, the question was clear _ were we for a tax cut for the middle class or were we not.''
_education: in 1981, gephardt voted for a conservative republican proposal to bar the justice department from using federal money to block prayer and meditation in public schools. gephardt says his vote is consistent with his current view that ``you could have voluntary, silent prayer'' in schools. gephardt, who campaigns on the need for educational improvements, opposed establishing the education department. he also has abandoned his past support of tuition tax credits
leftist guerrillas on saturday vowed to launch more attacks on u.s. military advisers stationed in the country and claimed american personnel have become directly involved in combat
washington last year provided more than $600 million in aid to the centrist government fighting an 8-year-old war against marxist-led insurgents. most of the aid was military or war-related
commander roberto roca, a member of the high command of the farabundo marti national liberation front, said in an interview with the rebel radio station that u.s. personnel are becoming increasingly involved in combat and repression
he said that makes them more likely to suffer the consequences of insurgent activity
roca's statement, broadcast by the rebels' radio venceremos, did not appear to be a blanket threat against all americans in el salvador. he referred to the 55 military advisers here training salvadoran government troops and to what he said was a contingent of ``about 40 (american) civilians advising and directing the repression of the people's movement.''
this kind of personnel is also part of the counterinsurgency campaign and because of that it will find itself increasingly the object of popular combat,'' said roca
for us, the americans have always been those responsible for this war; they have always sustained the war against the salvadoran people,'' he said. ``consequently, the personnel they have fighting here is a military objective of our forces.''
he claimed the u.s. military advisers stationed at the headquarters of the 6th infantry brigade in usulutan, 70 southeast of the capital san salvador, took part in combat there wednesday
an estimated 600 guerrillas attacked the base and a nearby cotton cooperative in the rebel's biggest assault in 10 months. eighteen people died in the fighting
col. inocente montano, commander of the 6th brigade, said there were four u.s. advisers at the base when the rebels attacked. he said the compound was never penetrated and that the advisers were never in danger. but he added that ``they were ready, in case of incursion, to help repel the attack.''
regulations governing the conduct of u.s. advisers here prohibit them from participation in combat except in self defense
to the degree that the war's operation theater is widened, the american advisers, the american personnel in those places ... will find themselves increasingly up against direct military operations,'' said roca. ``that is to say their (the american) military personnel will be going home wounded, dead.''
sgt. gregory fronius, the only military adviser to die in combat here, was killed in march of last year during a guerrilla attack on an army base in the northern province of chalatenango
the rebels assassinated a u.s. officer here in 1983 and killed four u.s. marine embassy guards, two american businessmen and seven other people in a machine gun attack on a san salvador cafe in 1985
the dean of harvard college has warned students that anyone involved in racial incidents faces expulsion and other disciplinary measures, but says his comments are general and not provoked by any particular incident
in dealing with situations where harassment, discrimination or insensitivity come to light, the college is ready to respond firmly and with appropriate actions,'' dean alfred jewett said in an open letter to the harvard community
in cases where physical harassment of students by other members of the community occurs, there is a general principle that the harasser should be asked to leave the community,'' said the letter, published friday by the student newspaper, the harvard crimson
the letter was issued a week after minority students at university of massachusetts in amherst took over a campus building to protest campus racism. the students left the building wednesday after meeting with the school chancellor
in a telephone interview, jewett said the letter was issued to lay down principles in the wake of deliberations with a committee on racial relations that was set up last year
harvard and the committee of students and faculty members decided to ``come out with a series of messages that would alert the community to problems that might exist and do exist in some communities,'' jewett said. ``mine is the first statement.''
four white students were expelled for a year last fall after frozen fruit was hurled at a black student, who later received several racially derogatory telephone calls
jewett said ``we have had no major things'' outside of that incident. the decision to issue the open letter was made later, in december, but its publication was postponed until after exams
the crimson said questions of racism were raised earlier this month after students alleged that a professor made unspecified disparaging comments about blacks and indians during a course called ``the peopling of america.''
harvard officials who asked to remain anonymous said they were aware of the allegations but said no investigation would be made unless a formal complaint was made
harvard college, made up of harvard university's undergraduate institutions, has an enrollment of 6,400
south korea's overall trade surplus last year doubled to $6.26 billion from 1986, with a record surplus reached with the united states, the korea foreign trade association announced saturday
according to the final tally, south korean exports last year amounted to $47.28 billion, up 36.2 percent from a year ago, and imports rose 29.9 percent to $41.02 billion
the overall surplus in 1986 was $3.13 billion
south korea's trade surplus with the united states rose to a record $9.55 billion from $7.33 billion in 1986
exports to the united states reached $18.31 billion, up 31.9 percent from a year ago, while imports from the united states rose 35.7 percent to $8.76 billion
topping the list of south korean export items were textiles, at $11.71 billion. automobile exports amounted to $3.25 billion
the small left radical movement party said saturday it was endorsing socialist president francois mitterrand for re-election, even though he hasn't declared himself a candidate
the center-left party, which has two members in the 577-seat national assembly, decided at its national convention to support mitterrand in the april 24 election, said party spokesman emile zuccarelli
the possibility that mr. mitterrand will not be a candidate is so unlikely that it wasn't even worth our considering,'' zuccarelli told reporters
the socialists, by far the strongest leftist party, are waiting for mitterrand to announce his decision before making an endorsement. he is expected to make his plans known in the middle of march and is expected to be a candidate
public opinion polls indicate mitterrand has far more popular support than the best-known declared candidates _ premier jacques chirac and former premier raymond barre. the two conservatives are running neck-and-neck for second place
other declared candidates include jean-marie le pen of the extreme-right national front, andre lajoinie of the communists and pierre juquin, a dissident communist. none is given much chance of making the runoff, which will be held may 8 between the top two vote-getters unless one candidate wins more than 50 percent april 24
the radical movement was france's leading party before world war ii, with a progressive, anti-clerical program. it has gradually lost strength, and it split in the 1970s into the left radicals and the center-right valoisian radicals, who participate in chirac's coalition government. killings</head>
the military chief of staff put all troops and police in the manila area on full alert saturday to prevent disruption of second anniversary celebrations of president corazon aquino's rise to power
gen. renato de villa said he also placed the alert after the killings of at least six people on manila streets in the past two weeks, the government-run philippine news agency reported
authorities have blamed the ambushes and slayings on communist guerillas
de villa also ordered the arrest saturday of a navy captain linked to the 1986 murder of a leftist labor leader, but the officer refused to leave his home, saying the arrest papers were not in order
de villa canceled all military leaves and ordered his troops to intensify patrols and set up nighttime mobilecheckpoints, the agency said
the celebrations next week mark the feb. 26, 1986 civilian-military coup that placed mrs. aquino in power after ousting president ferdinand marcos, who now lives in exile in hawaii
the military said earlier this month that it uncovered plans by communist rebels to step up slayings in the manila area this year. more than 130 policemen and soldiers were killed in the capital last year
military field reports reaching manila saturday said at least six communist new people's army guerrillas were killed and one soldier wounded in clashes friday in surigao del norte and bukidnon provinces on the southern island of mindanao
in cebu city, 350 miles southeast of manila, police said they discovered friday the bodies of five people who they believed were executed by rebels on suspicion of being military informers
navy capt. rex robles meanwhile denied involvement in the november 1986 murder of leftist labor leader rolando olalia and refused to accompany arresting officers because they carried only a photocopy of de villa's arrest order, robles' lawyer told reporters
in the order, de villa said robles was being arrested ``in connection'' with the slaying of the charismatic chairman of the may 1st movement, one of the philippines' largest labor federations
attorney armando marcelo told reporters that robles challenged the government to present evidence of his involvement
the arresting officers left robles' guarded home after he refused to go with them, marcelo said. update with comments by ortega. pickup 8th pvs: `the cardinal ...' and edits thruout to trim</note>
future peace talks between nicaragua's leftist government and its contra rebels are likely to have a political hue the sandinistas never wanted
the government appeared to open the door to political discussions with its armed opponents by belatedly agreeing in principle last week to a proposal by the mediator of the negotiations, cardinal miguel obando y bravo, head of the roman catholic church in nicaragua
that proposal called on the contras to accept a cease-fire in exchange for four major concessions by the sandinista government. the concessions were something the contras had been seeking, and they were quick to accept the cardinal's plan
the government was called upon to grant unrestricted freedom of the press and a total, unconditional amnesty for political prisoners, renew a dialogue with its internal opposition and review its universal military conscription law
whether it was a tactical error or a considered response, the sandinistas delayed in taking a position that president daniel ortega has long and strenuously opposed. on innumerable occasions in the past, he has said he would never discuss political matters with the contras
we don't want to create the impression that we don't want a cease-fire and are being intransigent,'' said paul reichler, a washington, d.c., attorney who advises the sandinistas. ``at all costs, we want the negotiations to go forward.''
reichler's comments came in a chat with reporters friday after obando y bravo abruptly suspended the latest round of peace talks a day before they were supposed to end and obliquely blamed the sandinistas for the breakdown
ortega said saturday in managua that the cardinal's proposal ``was not rejected'' by the sandinistas and said his government ``is willing to continue the conversations.''
but a clarification was needed on the withdrawal of the contras to enclaves during the truce, ortega said at the close of a government meeting
he repeated that his government is willing to apply an amnesty once a cease-fire is in effect. referring to the military draft, he said ``it is logical that with the end of the war the military service will not require the current volume (of soldiers).''
ortega told the meeting on new economic measures aimed at fighting inflation that ``enemies of the revolution'' opposed the measures. he said the right, the extreme left and the opposition daily la prensa should be careful not to stir up insurrection
the cardinal said after his return to managua on saturday that with the suspension of talks, ``we have given time for reflection since there is a lack of trust between the two sides.''
appearances are of vital importance to both sides, with neither party wanting to be seen as the spoiler as long as there is any remaining chance the u.s. congress might approve additional military aid for the contras
in private talks with reporters, the sandinistas made it clear that they were initially surprised by the cardinal's five-point proposal, then disappointed by his abrupt cancellation of the talks
victor hugo tinoco, nicaragua's deputy foreign minister, said obando halted the negotiations friday afternoon before he had a chance to deliver the government's formal, written response to the proposal the cardinal put forth thursday
but tinoco insisted that he had discussed the government's position at length with the cardinal friday morning and had not been given any reason to believe that the cardinal was unwilling to continue the negotiations
the cardinal ``did not tell us he disagreed'' with the government's position, reichler told reporters later
in its written response, the government declared its ``agreement in principle'' with the cardinal's proposal, but carefully conditioned its answers to his requests that it reconsider its mandatory draft law and grant an unconditional amnesty to the thousands of political prisoners in nicaraguan jails
but before nicaragua's formal response was delivered, obando had canceled the talks, saying he was disappointed that both sides had not accepted his proposal, at least in principle. the remark was clearly aimed at the sandinistas
but late or not, the government's response clearly put such political matters as press freedom and amnesty on the bargaining table for further talks and, given the opening, the contras are likely to push for even greater concessions
the cardinal is expected to announce a time and place for a third round of face-to-face negotiations sometime this week. the first round of talks took place in san jose, costa rica, in late january, only a week before the house rejected president reagan's latest request for about $43 million in additional contra aid
but the administration is considering a new bid for military aid for the rebels, and as long as that possibility exists, both sides will be playing their cards cautiously at the bargaining table
reid g. miller is the associated press' roving correspondent for central america. he has been based in san jose, costa rica, since january 1984
new york post employees cheered and uncorked champagne saturday after news that owner rupert murdoch reached agreement with 10 unions to save the nation's oldest continuously published daily newspaper
it has been a nightmare, but thank god, we're still in business,'' said lenny higgins, president of the newspaper pressmen's union
the deal will enable murdoch to sell the post to real estate developer peter kalikow. it involves a $22 million cost-reduction package that fell into place just before 2 a.m. when murdoch said he would provide $3 million to the unions to satisfy the terms of his sale agreement
the unions had already agreed to concessions totaling $19 million and said they could not give any more
cheers, deep sighs and the fizz of champagne filled the post's fourth-floor newsroom when the agreement was announced. some employees had worn black to mourn the paper's possible death
i feel great,'' said jerry cronin, head of the drivers' union. ``i feel we salvaged something that at five (minutes) of two (o'clock) was gone.''
murdoch had set a 2 p.m. friday deadline for closing the paper, and extended it with time almost out
kalikow will take over the post for $37.6 million on march 7 pending rank-and-file ratification of the concessions and verification by his accountants of the details
his spokesman, howard rubenstein, said kalikow was considering editorial changes that could tone down the post's brassy style and was committed to keeping the paper operating
there will be some changes in the format and appearance of the paper but he's not yet ready to discuss the changes in detail,'' rubenstein said. many of the expected changes come from suggestions by post employees
the new owner will meet with union leaders immediately to discuss his plans, rubenstein said
he wants to assure them he bought the paper so it could continue being a powerful voice in new york city and that he did not buy it for the real estate,'' rubenstein said. ``he will try to make it a very new york paper
it seems his whole life now is involved with the post. he's gone into it with great vigor.''
kalikow faces stiff problems in a highly competitive market. the daily news and new york newsday are also fighting for tabloid readers and the new york times maintains a strong leadership in advertising revenue
the post was founded in 1801 by alexander hamilton and other investors and during its long history has come close to folding several times. the latest threat came from a federal law that forced murdoch to sell the financially troubled tabloid because he also owns a new york city television station, wnyw-tv
he had said the post was losing $100,000 a day and that he had lost $150 million since he bought it in 1976 for $31 million
after saturday's agreement was announced, murdoch said, ``i would do it all again. i ... hate to leave it.''
the $22 million package presented to kalikow will eliminate 130 of the 1,012 union jobs at the post, some immediately and some later over the three-year life of the deal. the paper has about 1,200 employees
i don't think there's any question that without murdoch's contribution of $3 million, the paper would have definitely shut down,'' lawyer and mediator theodore kheel said. ``i would give him the lion's share of the credit.''
the package to keep the post afloat consists of $22 million in lost jobs and pay cuts and $3 million from murdoch's news america corp. to restore the pay cuts. because of that contribution, no paycheck will be smaller for the employees who remain
kheel said murdoch referred to the $3 million he put into the settlement as his farewell gift to the post and its employees. other currency measures. pickup 14th graf pvs ``groups from...''</note>
president daniel ortega said saturday that the right, the extreme left and the opposition newspaper la prensa should ``be careful, because they can in fact provoke an insurrection that can destroy them.''
speaking at the closing of the leftist government's meeting on new economic measures, ortega said ``enemies of the revolution,'' including the political opposition, the u.s. government and la prensa, opposed new economic steps announced by his administration the past week
he called la prensa ``the daily of the cia.''
the opposition from both sides of the political spectrum and the superior council of private enterprise, ortega said, ``have said that the time for an insurrection has come.''
he said they should not ``be looking for five feet on the cat because they may find them. they should be careful, because if they put themselves on the side of the contras and the aggressors they are going to stir winds that can provoke tempests.''
the superior council of private enterprise is the most important private business organization in nicaragua
adding more teeth to the economic measures announced earlier, ortega announced one- to four-year prison sentences for speculators. he said taxi drivers and others who work in transportation would have their vehicles confiscated if they charged more than the official prices
he also announced a 10 percent reduction in the national budget and a tax exemption for 22,900 families whose housing loans were forgiven by the government
the exact amount of the budget is not known and he did not elaborate on where the cuts would be made
those and other measures announced the past week are ``to give the economy a push and fight inflation,'' he said
the sandinista government on monday created a new cordoba currency worth 1,000 times as much as the old one and pegged it at 10 to the dollar
it also raised salaries to five times what they were in december and authorized price increases of up to more than 50 percent on some basic goods
although the measures were designed to slow inflation, which was 1,500 percent for 1987, prices already were being hiked beyond the new official levels
ortega issued a decree that requires individuals and corporations to report any foreign currency holdings of more than $500
a stamped, signed copy of a report of the holdings to one of the country's banks will be legal authorization for the owner to keep the money, said the decree issued friday. reports must be filed within 15 days but are not required if the funds are deposited in state-owned banks
failure to follow the rules will be considered a currency violation, punishable by one to three years in prison under a 1981 law
another decree authorizes the government's central bank to investigate large deposits of old cordobas if there are suspected of being linked to illegal activity
groups from sandinista defense committees, civilian neighborhood organizations, accompanied by police, have raided storerooms of alleged black market businesses and public markets to confiscate goods and force vendors to sell at official prices
ortega compared the economic measures to ``a strong medicine'' for a sick person
as long as the war doesn't end, we are going to try to have the patient recover to better confront the aggressor,'' he said
the contra rebels, which have been supported by the u.s. government, have been fighting more than six years to overthrow the sandinistas. advisory. woman was widowed just twice, not five times; three other marriages ended in divorce.</note>
