a roofer who apparently was trying to break into a bank by shimmying down an air vent was trapped upside-down in the vent for five hours saturday, police said
raymond mention of bayshore suffered minor injuries to his right arm and collar bone and bruises on his face, said officer thomas sorriano, a suffolk county police spokesman
this is the first time in my life i've ever been so glad to see a bunch of cops,'' mention told his rescuers
employees of the long island savings bank in islip arrived at work at 8:45 a.m. and heard a man calling for help, sorriano said
when the officers reached the roof, they found a roofer's belt and tools, the vent, and then discovered mention's feet ``wiggling up in the air,'' said officer mark ryan
he told them he tried to get in feet first and when he couldn't, he tried head first,'' ryan said. ``he had nothing to hold on to and fell in.''
the officers kept mention talking while they tried to get the blood circulating in his legs and pry him from the curve in the 2-foot-by-2-foot vent where he had become lodged, he said
when he was finally freed, mention asked for the time, was told it was 9 a.m., and said he had been stuck for five hours, ryan said
mention was taken to southside hospital, where he was treated and released into police custody. the roofer was charged with criminal mischief; other charges were pending, said sorriano. arraignment was scheduled for sunday
mildred seydell, a globe-trotting journalist who interviewed benito mussolini and covered the scopes ``monkey trial,'' died saturday. she was 98
ms. seydell, a resident of the suburban atlanta town of roswell, once said she ``much preferred to set the stage for adventure rather than the table for dinner.'' her work as a writer and columnist for hearst publications, including the now-defunct atlanta georgian newspaper, took her around the world
she wrote ``talks with celebrities,'' including an interview with the italian dictator mussolini, for universal news service and 27 hearst papers. she also covered for hearst the 1925 tennessee trial of john scopes, a teacher indicted for illegally teaching the theory of evolution
ms. seydell was a columnist for the atlanta georgian from 1926 to 1939, the year the paper closed
born mildred woolley in atlanta, she married paul seydel, a chemist she met while studying at the sorbonne in paris, in 1910. she added an ``l'' to seydel and adopted the name for her writing
she is survived by two sons, grandchildren and great-grandchildren
