a flash rainstorm caused floods and mudslides that left at least 70 people dead saturday. as many as 95 others were feared dead after an avalanche of mud and boulders crashed into a nursing home
firemen used surfboards and the navy used amphibious vehicles to rescue people stranded by the storm, which began late friday night and left about 3,150 homeless
state health director jose noronha said at least 70 died and 80 to 95 more were feared dead. the same number of victims was reported by civil defense spokesman bruno avila, who said the death toll could be even higher because of mudslides in poor shantytowns that line mountainsides in this city of 5.6 million
the four-hour downpour dumped 4.88 inches on rio and left many streets under 5 feet of water
mayor roberto saturnino braga declared the city a disaster area, called in all off-duty municipal doctors and canceled a post-carnival parade of champions scheduled for saturday night
there is nothing to celebrate now. there is only sorrow,'' said martinho da vila, a popular samba composer who performed in the famous carnival festivities here a week ago
the vila isabel neighborhood, whose samba school won this year's top carnival prize and which celebrated wednesday with an all-night victory party, was one of the most rain-battered zones in the city
state troopers were sent out to prevent the looting of stores and stop holdups of drivers whose cars had broken down in the high water
avila said most of the 70 deaths occurred in poor slum areas, where housing is precarious and drains and sewers often nonexistent
james lewis, a rescue work coordinator in the mayor's office, said: ``we are accustomed to tragedies in our slums, but this was too much. something definitely must be done to protect slum people from rainstorms.''
a mudslide knocked down one three-story wing of the three-wing santa genoveva hospital, a social security nursing home in santa teresa, a well-to-do mountainside neighborhood. there was little hope that the estimated 80 to 95 elderly patients there would get out alive
there is so much wood and concrete there we don't believe anybody could survive,'' avila said
at sundown the rescue efforts were called off for the day
it was awful. all my friends were dead in an instant,'' maria teixeira, one of 350 patients evacuated from the two other wings of the hospital, told a tv interviewer as she lay in a stretcher
boulders and mud left by the storm held up rescuers for three hours on their way to the nursing home
old people were left standing in the rain and chill all that time. i don't know how they endured it,'' lewis said
the storm, accompanied by near nonstop thunder and lightning, knocked out telephones and international communications and stopped commuter trains
even the fire department and civil defense were without phones for a while and had to rely on radio to coordinate rescue work
earlier this month, rain caused flooding and mudslides that killed about 206 people and drove 13,000 from their homes in rio de janeiro state. the hardest-hit spot then was petropolis, a mountain resort 40 miles north of the city of rio. limits</head> extradition limits with britain, quotes, details, background.</note>
a court saturday ordered the extradition of a prominent irish republican army activist to northern ireland. prime minister charles haughey, citing a separate case, welcomed limits on extraditions to britain
owen carron, 34, a former member of the british parliament and a leading member of sinn fein, the ira's legal political wing, had been sought since he jumped bail on a weapons charge in northern ireland two years ago
police arrested him friday night in the southwestern county of sligo, about 20 miles from the northern ireland border, after an officer recognized him
the district court in sligo ordered carron extradited to british-ruled northern ireland but gave him 15 days to appeal the order. the court ordered that he remain in custody pending appeal
in dublin, haughey said saturday that a british court's refusal to free six irishmen accused of ira bombings showed the need for restrictions on the extradition of terrorist suspects to britain
dublin inserted new conditions dec. 1 for extradition to britain. the measures include the requirements that british authorities produce evidence on warrants in all extradition cases, and that the irish attorney general approve all extraditions
britain has a ``historic inability ... to comprehend irish feelings and sensitivities,'' haughey said in a speech to the annual conference of the governing fianna fail party
britain long has criticized the irish republic's reluctance to extradite suspects sought for trial in connection with irish republican army actions. the ira is fighting to end british rule in northern ireland and unite the protestant-dominated province with mainly roman catholic ireland
haughey said the need for restrictions was exemplified by the case of six irishmen sentenced to life in prison for ira's bombings of two birmingham pubs in 1974 that killed 21 people
britain's court of appeal upheld their convictions last month, rejecting arguments that new evidence undermined the confessions and forensic findings that sent them to prison
the wisdom of, and the necessity for, the effective safeguards provided in our extradition legislation has been clearly confirmed,'' haughey said. ``these safeguards are now in place and it is on the basis of these safeguards, or not at all, that extradition will proceed.''
carron's case was not affected by the legislation because warrants seeking his extradition were issued in november, before introduction of the new regulations
carron came to prominence in 1981 when he was the election officer for bobby sands, who launched a seven-month ira hunger strike at belfast's maze prison that year
sands, who was elected to the british parliament while behind bars, and nine other ira members starved themselves to death during the protest over prison regulations. when sands died, carron won his parliamentary seat
the royal ulster constabulary, northern ireland's police force, had been hunting carron since he jumped bail in january 1986 on a charge of possessing a soldier's rifle. he had been released on bail to run as a sinn fein candidate in special elections to the british parliament
after being defeated in the election, carron failed to report back to jail
port-au-prince, haiti (ap) _ an opposition leader who led two unsuccessful invasions during the duvalier family dictatorship left the country saturday after spending six months holed up in an embassy, said haiti radio inter
bernard sansaricq, who was granted political asylum by the argentine embassy after the haitian government accused him of urging peasants to revolt, boarded an eastern airlines flight bound for miami at 5 p.m., the independent radio station said
sansaricq, head of the national peoples party, was driven to the airport in an argentine embassy limousine, accompanied by four carloads of haitian soldiers, the radio said
president leslie manigat, in an address on state television friday night, promised safe conduct ``for all of those in political asylum.''
sansaricq, in his mid-40s, was the only person known to have been in political asylum in haiti
he was accused aug. 3 last year of attempting to provoke a revolution in jeremie, his hometown, on the tip of haiti's southwestern peninsula. after a shootout with soldiers, he and several supporters fled into the surrounding hills and disappeared for three weeks
the military claimed he arrived with a group of armed men and distributed weapons to peasants in the town
sansaricq denied the charges. sansaricq said in a radio address from the argentine embassy on aug. 25 that he had been armed only with a revolver, for which he claimed to have a license
he said he went to jeremie to attend a trial of people accused of taking part in a massacre in 1964. sansaricq said hundreds of upper class mulatto families and suspected opponents of dictator francois duvalier were massacred by soldiers and the tontons macoutes, duvalier's secret police
the government has never acknowledged the killings
sansaricq, whose entire family was slain in the massacre, said the army wanted to kill him since his testimony would have implicated high ranking officers, including defense minister williams regala, a reserve army brigidier general and former member of the military-run junta
sansaricq, who at one time owned a gas station in south florida, led foiled invasions in 1963 and 1982 during the 29-year dictatorship of francois duvalier and his son, jean claude. he lived in miami from the early 1960s until 1986, when jean-claude duvalier fled into exile in france
the 1963 invasion occurred in jeremie. he escaped, but 12 colleagues were captured and shot by a military firing squad. in 1982, he landed on the island of la tortue on haiti's northern coast. eight people died in the 1982 invasion and sansaricq and others were rescued by the u.s. coast guard
an earthquake rattled central colombia saturday evening, sending people in bogota's high-rise apartments and office buildings fleeing into the streets
there were no immediate reports of injuries from hospitals, fire stations and police stations, according to the colombian radio network rcn
the tremor measured 5 on the richter scale and the epicenter was in the andes about 50 miles south of bogota, said the geophysical institute of the andes, according to rcn
the earthquake at 5:52 p.m. lasted three seconds and slight aftershocks were registered 12 minutes later, a spokesman for the bogota institute said in the rcn report
the richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on seismographs. every increase of one number means a tenfold increase in magnitude
an earthquake of 5 on the richter scale can cause considerable damage in the local area
