a black teen-ager sent to death row at age 15 was convicted saturday of murder in a retrial brought after the state supreme court overturned his original conviction by an all-white jury. the prosecutor said he would not seek the death penalty again
ronald ward, 18, showed no emotion and even smiled faintly at the jurors as they filed out of the courtroom
the crittenden county circuit court jury deliberated nearly 13 hours over two days before finding him guilty in the 1985 deaths of three whites
though he was convicted of capital murder, prosecuting attorney scott hunter said he would not ask the jury to impose the death penalty. as a result, ward was automatically given life in prison without parole, the only other possible sentence for capital felony murder
the fact that he has been on death row for 2{ years was a factor in the decision,'' hunter said
he also said he considered the length of time the jury spent in deliberations. ``i felt like i could not call upon this jury to do more than they've done.''
ward's attorneys, samuel turner jr. of west memphis and joseph b. brown jr. of memphis, tenn., said a notice of appeal would be filed immediately. the attorneys maintain that ward was illegally fingerprinted before his arrest
the state supreme court overturned the original conviction last year, noting that an all-white jury convicted the 15-year-old black boy of killing the three whites
the retrial jury had eight whites and four blacks
