attorneys for boston university have asked a judge to have coretta scott king release tapes of conversations between her late husband, martin luther king jr. and others, recorded secretly by federal investigators
the motion, filed in suffolk superior court on friday, also asks for correspondence between king and his colleagues
the action, which mrs. king's attorneys charged was a form of harassment, was the latest round in the legal fight between the school and mrs. king over an estimated 83,000 documents involving her husband which are now held by bu
king, who had earned a graduate degree from the school of theology in 1955, donated the papers to the university in 1964
mrs. king has filed suit, saying the documents should be in the martin luther king jr. center for nonviolent social change in atlanta, and contending the university had mishandled or lost some of the papers
bu trustees decided unanimously to oppose the suit
mrs. king's attorneys said they would oppose the request for copies of the secretly recorded tapes
it seems they're inquiring into things, including dr. king's personal life and perhaps mrs. king's, that have nothing to do with this case,'' said boston attorney james o'brien, one of mrs. king's lawyers
we are going to object to the request for tapes,'' he said. ``i think it's harassment.''
o'brien and rudolph pierce, who also represents mrs. king in the suit, said they did not believe mrs. king had copies of the tapes
i don't know at the moment if mrs. king, or the estate, has that information. i would doubt it,'' said pierce
published reports in the 1970s indicated that a package of the tapes was sent anonymously to mrs. king
beginning in 1964, the fbi bugged hotel rooms where king was staying. tapes implicating king in alleged extramarital sexual activity were made available to reporters, members of congress and then-president lyndon b. johnson. in 1977, a federal judge ordered the tapes sealed for 50 years
melvin b. miller, a bu trustee who law firm is handling the suit for the university, said he believed mrs. king had some of the tapes
of course she has some of them,'' he said
he refused to say why the university wanted copies of the tapes for the lawsuit
we are entitled to seek documents we believe will be admissible evidence in this case,'' miller said. ``whatever we ask for we believe will further our position.''
we could make an argument for its appropriatenesss in a court of law,'' miller said. ``if you think we're going to discuss the strategy of our case in the press _ that's a bit much.''
japanese and u.s. officials failed to reach agreement on opening some japanese construction projects to american firms, u.s. officials said saturday
japan recently offered to allow foreign participation in six large public works projects, but u.s. officials said saturday the proposals were not enough. the officials held an unusual weekend news conference at the u.s. embassy, but spoke on condition of anonymity
michael farren, deputy undersecretary of commerce for international trade, is heading the u.s. delegation
the six projects are expansion of the tokyo international airport at haneda, construction of a new airport in hiroshima, a bridge across the akashi strait near osaka, a highway along ise bay, the development of a coastal area along the tokyo bay and work at osaka port
a great many american firms have expressed tremendous interest in gaining access to japanese markets,'' said one official. ``but the kind of things we called for in the way of construction services on this list would only open door to a very narrow range of american construction firms
we've come to a judgement that the list (of the six projects) is not sufficient'' he said
the officials said the talks will probably continue in washington, where prime minister noboru takeshita met with u.s. leaders on an official visit last month
access to the japanese construction market has been a major trade issue in recent years between the two countries
japanese companies won about $2.3 billion in contracts in the united states in 1986, while u.s. firms did about $500 million in business in japan, according to construction officials
japan has opened only two semi-public projects to u.s. builders _ the tokyo bay bridge and the multi-billion dollar kansai international airport project
the u.s. congress last year passed legislation prohibiting foreign companies from taking part in u.s. public works projects for one year if their countries bar participation of u.s. firms in their public works projects. on tal victory, kasparov loss. picks up 5th pvs: `the championship ...' adds byline. corrects ages of georgiev to 22 sted 23 and tal to 51 sted 52</note>
world champion garri kasparov lost saturday in the quarterfinals of the world chess blitz championship, but soviet colleague mikhail tal won the sport's richest tournament ever
i played badly as you saw,'' said kasparov, 24, of the soviet union. he spoke briefly to reporters after his morning loss to bulgarian kirel georgiev, 22
tal, 51, who won his first major soviet competition in 1957 and the world championship in 1960, defeated soviet rafael vaganian 3.5-0.5. vaganian, 37, had defeated georgiev in the semifinals
the blitz match is a fast-paced chess game in which each player has only five minutes' playing time. the results do not count in competition for the world chess title
in the six-game final, tal stormed to a 3-0 lead before agreeing to a draw in the fourth game to seize the title
tal, ranked no. 6 in the world, told reporters that he never expected to win and said ``my opponents played too hospitably.''
it's the beginning of a second career for tal,'' said american grandmaster larry evans
in 1960, tal, then 23, became the youngest world champion in history until kasparov gained the title in 1985 at age 22
but tal lost his title in 1961 to mikhail botvinnik, another soviet
kasparov's debacle began in the first of a four-game series where he had a queen, a bishop and a king verses goeirgive's lone king, a position where many beginners would have little difficulty in winning
but kasparov, the tournament favorite, stunned the audience by stalemating his opponent, ending the game in a draw
in the position, georgiev's king could not move, but unlike a checkmate, it was not attacked
as kasparov made the hideous error, there were gasps from spectators and he held his head in his hands
in the second game, kasparov pressed too hard for victory, blundered and lost
their third encounter was drawn and georgiev checkmated the world champion in the fourth as kasparov overreached, desperately searching for a victory
the championship offered a total prize fund of 75,000 u.s. dollars. tal won $37,500 for four hours work, the highest prize ever offered for a single chess tournament
on friday, former world champion anatoly karpov of the soviet union, ranked no. 2 in the world, was eliminated from the blitz competition
the blitz championship ended the monthlong world chess festival in the port city on canada's east coast
the premiers of romania and bulgaria met saturday in bulgaria to discuss ways of ending repeated chlorine pollution along their border, the official bulgarian news agency bta said
premier georgi atanassov of bulgaria and his romanian counterpart constantin dasalescu met in the northern bulgarian town of rousse, the news agency said
there have been repeated reports in the official bulgarian media of dense clouds of chlorine gas from a chemical complex in giurgiu in southern romania drifting over the danube river to rousse and forcing residents to stay indoors
chlorine is a greenish-yellow poisonous gas which has a suffocating effect
last year, bulgaria and romania set up a joint commission charged with taking measures to end the repeated chlorine pollution in the border area
the warsaw pact allies agreed to have teams of experts from both countries measure air pollution in the two cities and determine its sources, bta said
atanassov informed dascalescu of measures taken by bulgaria to ``decisively purify'' the air in rousse and proposed an intergovernmental convention for the protection of the environment in the danube region, bta said. injured. subs 21nd graf to end, bgng `the victim...', with 4 graf to add dead crew member's occupation, update detail on number of victims, how many are crew members, other detail.</note>
passengers aboard amtrak's california zephyr complained that they received no warnings or instructions from crew members when a smoky fire caused by a defective heater in a crew car killed one man early saturday and injured 19 people
it's a miracle that there wasn't some kind of panic,'' said sara bentley, of fremont, neb., a passenger in the first coach car behind the passenger sleeper, which was coupled to the crew car
i think the worst thing was that they didn't let anyone in our car know whether we were in danger. we couldn't find out if our car was safe.''
amtrak spokesman john jacobsen said the fire aboard the 14-car westbound train carrying 294 passengers and a crew of 18 was reported about 3 a.m. as the train was pulling into hastings for a scheduled stop. hastings fire chief jim mitera said the blaze was under control about 90 minutes later
an electrical short in the wiring of the crew car heating unit caused the fire, deputy state fire marshal chuck hoffman said at an afternoon news conference. he said the heater was in a storage area under the crew sleeping quarters and that the short ignited the car's wood floor
state fire marshal wally barnett said the wiring showed wear and tear but did not say amtrak was negligent
adams county attorney gary anderberg said an autopsy showed that the amtrak employee died of smoke inhalation
amtrak investigators, who did not attend the news conference, were on the scene by late saturday morning
the crew car and the passenger sleeper were disconnected from the zephyr, which travels from chicago to salt lake city, then splits into sections that proceed to oakland, calif., los angeles and seattle, jacobsen said from his office in washington, d.c. the rest of the train pulled out of hastings about 9:30 a.m. after some crew members were checked at the hospital and returned, he said
robert ballard, his wife, helen, and 11-year-old grandson robby were in a deluxe sleeper en route to a colorado ski trip. he said they opened the compartment door and found the hallway filled with smoke
we just woke up and smelled smoke,'' said ballard, of flint, mich
mrs. ballard, who suffers from asthma, was admitted to the hospital for observation, her husband said
the thing i can't understand is we heard no smoke detectors going off,'' ballard said
jacobsen said there are no smoke detectors on the train because ``no one has invented one that works reliably.'' because smoke detectors are so sensitive, the constant vibrations of trains would set them off, he said
jacobsen said he could recall only two train fires and that because they are so rare there has not been a market for smoke detectors designed for trains
jacobsen said the rest of the train was not in any danger from the fire, and that there is no fuel or propane in any of the passenger cars
bentley and another passenger, mike casuscelli, also of fremont, said no crew members told them to evacuate, but they and a number of other passengers decided to leave the train after seeing fire trucks arrive. some crew members and passengers from the sleeping cars milled around outside the train, many of the men shirtless or wearing only long underwear
normally, you don't want passengers to get off as long as the rest of the train is not in danger,'' jacobsen said. ``it is safer to keep people on the train.''
a female crew member ran through bentley's car, asking passengers for blankets for the injured. she said the woman's face was covered with soot and she was shoeless
the crew car is designed for amtrak service attendants who are with the train from the beginning to the end of the trip. jacobsen said it was divided into two sections, one for baggage and one with small bedrooms
the victim, identified as chef cesar arguelles, 70, of chicago, was one of seven crew members on the car, jacobsen said
nine crew members and three passengers remained saturday evening in mary lanning hospital, where they were being treated for smoke inhalation, anderberg said. all were listed in satisfactory or good condition
three crew members, one passenger, two policemen and an ambulance attendant were treated and released, anderberg said
hastings, a town of about 18,000, is in south-central nebraska
supporters of massachusetts gov. michael dukakis saturday accused missouri rep. richard gephardt of running a television advertisement that distorts the governor's views on agriculture
the ad, which first aired across the state friday night, said dukakis would not take a stand on a family farm bill sponsored by gephardt and ended with a barb at dukakis' much-criticized suggestion that iowa farmers consider raising belgian endive, a salad green
at a news conference, minnesota agriculture commissioner jim nichols, who supports dukakis for the democratic nomination for president, said the governor's farm plan would work well for midwestern states
although dukakis praised massachussetts farmers's efforts to diversify by raising endive, he recognizes that nationally, ``we need a fair price in the marketplace, and supply management,'' nichols said
but after the news conference, gephardt's south dakota campaign issued a statement contending dukakis ``has repeatedly denounced supply management for farmers.'' the statement included a boston globe article quoting the governor as saying that controlling production would be ``incredibly complicated and very bureaucratic.''
but, state rep. robert duxbury of wessington, a state co-chairman for the dukakis campaign, said,``mike dukakis has laid out a very thoughtful agriculture policy for family farmers and ranchers. he favors credit relief, supply management and fair market prices for farmers.''
state sen. roger mckellips of alcester, another state co-chairman, called the ads ``a new low in south dakota presidential politics'' and urged their removal. procedure; no pickup.</note>
a brain-dead baby whose body was kept alive in hopes of tranplanting his organs was removed from life-support machines saturday after no suitable recipient could be found, officials said
meanwhile, a child born saturday with the same fatal defect in san antonio, texas, was placed on a respirator and flown to california to be enrolled in loma linda university medical center's donor program
the babies were born without most of their brain and skull, a fatal condition known as anencephaly
the child known as baby john was born tuesday and declared brain-dead thursday at loma linda. officials had hoped to keep the baby's body on life-support machines for up to seven days, hospital spokeswoman anita rockwell said
by saturday, ms. rockwell said, ``physicians of four waiting liver recipients of baby john's same blood type refused the liver because of its progressive deterioration over the past 36 hours
despite a worldwide search, no infant of the same blood type needing a heart has been found
out of respect for the brain-dead infant and with the consent of his mother, dr. joyce peabody removed the artificial life support from baby john and his cardiac activity ceased at 2:15 p.m.''
anencephaly is fatal, usually within days after birth. an infant's healthy organs can only be transplanted if organ damage is prevented by maintaining the infant on life-support from birth
the first anencephalic child considered by loma linda hospital for the pioneering procedure was the child of brenda and michael winner of arcadia, calif. but the baby was stillborn on dec. 22
the use of such infants as organ donors has raised controversial ethical issues, and loma linda is the first hospital in the united states to develop a medical protocol allowing such transplants
the national right to life committee has denounced the procedure and complained that doctors have failed to do enough to ensure that organs weren't removed from live children
one of the hospital's 13 heart transplant patients under age 4 received the heart of an anencephalic baby earlier this year from a donor child in canada
if the texas baby is declared dead within seven days, and one or more of her organs successfully transplanted, it would be the first time that the procedure has been tried using an anencephalic baby born in the united states
the infant, 6-pound, 1-ounce evelyn keys was put on a chartered plane in texas en route to loma linda. she was born with only a brain stem, said robert mcnaughton, wilford hall medical center spokesman in san antonio
evelyn is the first child of airman first class todd keys, 21, and his wife, judy, 22. democrats</head>
sen. bob dole of kansas was the favorite among minnesota republicans while gov. michael dukakis of massachusetts was the leader among democrats surveyed in the latest minnesota poll
the poll results, published in the sunday editions of the star tribune, said dole received support from 42 percent of the republicans surveyed while vice president george bush was favored by 32 percent. former television evangelist pat robertson was third with 11 percent and u.s. rep. jack kemp of new york was favored by 5 percent. ten percent gave other responses
among democrats, dukakis was favored by 29 percent, followed by u.s. rep. richard gephardt of missouri at 18 percent. jesse jackson was third with 14 percent, followed by former colorado sen. gary hart at 11 percent and illinois sen. paul simon with 9 percent. nineteen percent gave other responses
the poll of 800 adults randomly selected statewide from households that have telephones was taken feb. 10-14, or about 10 days before the state's precinct caucuses
the poll has a margin of error of 3.5 percentage points, the newspaper said
the newspaper said the poll makes no attempt to predict how candidates will perform in the precinct caucuses because the survey was not confined to those likely to attend precinct caucuses
a simon statement issued by his minnesota campaign office said, ``there's no way any poll can get a realistic picture of how active, independent-minded (democrats) will divide tuesday night.''
simon finished second in the iowa caucuses, which were won by gephardt, and came in third in the new hampshire primary, where dukakis came in first and gephardt was second
dole won the iowa caucuses while robertson finished a surprising second ahead of bush, who bounced back to win the new hampshire primary over dole. kemp finished third in new hampshire
the minnesota poll found that dukakis and gephardt are stronger with middle-aged and older minnesota adults, while hart and jackson find more of their support with younger adults
bruce babbitt's last stop on his way home from 18 months of campaigning for the democratic presidential nomination was to tell a cheering crowd at his national campaign headquarters saturday that it was good to be home
i got a call a week ago from a neighbor of mine who said, `bruce, you may be hot stuff out there in the rest of the united states, running for president of the united states, debating on television all the time, but you better get home because you're fence is falling down and the dog is wreckin' my lawn,''' babbitt told about 1,000 of his supporters
babbitt, the former governor of arizona, officially dropped out of the race thursday after disappointing showings in the new hampshire primary and the iowa democratic caucuses
babbitt said he and his wife, hattie, were going to spend some time getting reacquainted and re-establishing their roots in arizona
i want you to know one thing: wherever we go, our roots will always be in arizona, he said.''
babbitt said he would be jumping into the fray of the gubernatorial recall election, but not as a candidate
i want to take the time in the next month or two to try and get back into the swing of what it is that's going on here, to rejoin our fight here in arizona,'' he said
babbitt, introduced to the crowd by acting gov. rose mofford, who has replaced impeached gov. evan mecham, said, ``i'm going to join you in whatever way i can to make sure the change is permanent.''
he said he has been asked about his future plans and that he hasn't ruled out anything except running for governor of arizona, adding that there were plenty of good candidates
it's all of you that gave me this opportunity. it was a great run. i hope that i come back having reflected the spirit of arizona, our traditions, honor, on all of us. i'm glad to be home. thanks very much,'' babbitt said
asked what he had learned from 18 months of campaigning, said: ``i think most of all, a tremendous sense of faith and confidence in the future of america
it's an incredibly diverse country, full of people just bursting with energy, with optimism, who are really thirsting for some leadership.... 1988 is going to be important, because we will have a transition, and we've somehow got to capture a spirit of challenge, of truth-telling, of a kind of willingness to tell the american people the truth and get this economy moving.''
soviet cosmonauts will carry a u.s. commercial project into space for the first time in a deal approved by the government, an attorney for the project said saturday
payload systems inc. of wellsley, mass., received a two-year license from the commerce department earlier this month to contract with the soviet space agency to perform protein crystallization experiments aboard the soviet space station mir, said mark s. mcconnell, a washington attorney who handled the company's negotiations with the commerce and defense departments
the company, a consulting firm, was founded in 1984 by byron k. lichtenberg of the massachussetts institute of technology. he was the first american non-astronaut to fly aboard the space shuttle in december 1983
the experiment will use the weightlessness of space to grow large, regular protein crystals, which are useful in the development of new drugs, mcconnell said saturday evening
to my knowledge, it is the first time that the u.s. government has approved commercial activity in the soviet space program. certainly we've had joint missions, government-to-government,'' he said
since the explosion of the challenger space shuttle in january 1986, american companies have been left with few alternatives for space projects
even when the shuttle was flying it provided only a limited amount of time in space. with the shuttle down, the only american option is (a plane) flown in a parabolic flight path that gives only a few minutes of weightlessness,'' mcconnell said
u.s. officials were concerned about the possibility of transferring sensitive technology to the soviet union, but mcconnell said, ``we created a situation that absolutely minimized that.'' he said the commerce department issued the license after getting from the pentagon
there will be extremely limited training given to the cosmonauts. they will be doing no more than turning some dials on a box, the contents of which they will not know about, and monitoring environmental conditions in the space station,'' he said
he said the soviets were satisfied with the arrangement, adding, ``their goal from what i could tell is to promote commercial uses worldwide of their station.''
the u.s. government has been reluctant to permit american companies to hire the soviets to launch satellites and mcconnell said the soviets viewed the crystallization project as their best shot at working with a u.s. firm
he said payload systems has reached an agreement in principle with the soviets, but still was negotiating over details
he said the company would not attempt to sell the crystals grown in the first flight
they're just trying to see if it works for commercial purposes,'' he said
according to the new york times, which carried a story on the project in sunday's editions, the first flight will be sometime next year
the newspaper said payload systems refused to discuss the terms of the contract. it added, however, that the soviets in the past have offered to carry western experiments for between $10,000 and $15,000 a kilogram
calls to company officials seeking comment were not immediately returned saturday night
president reagan's budget, released thursday, provides $1 billion to build a u.s. space station by the mid-1990s. earlier this month reagan unveiled a national policy for commercial activity in space. it provides for the government to lease space aboard a space module that will be carried aloft by the space shuttle and left in orbit
figure skater brian boitano won the united states' first gold medal of the winter olympics on saturday, beating canadian world champion brian orser
orser took the silver and viktor petrenko of the soviet union was third for the bronze
boitano's win gives the united states one gold; one silver, also won saturday; and one bronze as the olympics ended its first week
boitano, the 1986 world champion and a four-time american titlist, took the long program with a sensational exhibition of freestyle skating
the 24-year-old from sunnyvale, calif., who was fifth in the 1984 olympics, depicted the various stages of a soldier's life to music from the film ``napoleon.''
he successfully performed all eight triple jumps, including two in combination, and drew a standing ovation from the sellout crowd at the olympic saddledome
he also won over five of the nine judges, who gave him eight marks of 5.9 and one perfect 6.0, from the czechoslovakian judge for artistic impression
orser, 26, also came in second at the 1984 winter olympics in sarajevo, losing the gold to another american, scott hamilton
earlier saturday, speed skater eric flaim won the first silver medal for the united states. andre hoffmann beat flaim by .06 seconds, giving east germany its second gold medal of the day and leading another soviet-bloc day at the olympics
the only other u.s. medal was a bronze in pairs figure skating won tuesday night by jill watson and peter oppegard
the soviets now have 14 medals, including five golds; and east germany has 10, including six golds
leftist guerrillas said friday they will shut down road and highway transport nationwide next week as part of their protest against the government's election plans
the 24-hour transport ban, set to begin at 12:01 a.m. monday, is the first scheduled by the rebels this year. the announcement, made on the rebels' clandestine radio venceremos, said the action was part of the guerrilla campaign against legislative and municipal elections scheduled for march 20
the traffic bans have been effective in the past, especially in the war-torn east. motorists stay off the roads, fearing reprisal by the guerrillas
also friday, the armed forces said five guerrillas and two soldiers died in combat near the town of la laguna, 55 miles north of the capital. six government soldiers were wounded, they said
radio venceremos claimed guerrilla forces inflicted 23 casualties on government troops in thursday's clash at la laguna. it did not distinguish between dead and wounded and did not report rebel losses
in another attack, rebels assaulted the local civil defense headquarters, the mayor's office and the telephone office in san jorge before dawn friday, according to sources in the town 95 miles southeast of san salvador
the sources, reached by telephone, said five civil defense militiamen were killed and two wounded. they had no information on guerrilla casualties
the guerrillas caused extensive damage, according to the sources, who spoke on condition of anoymity
guerrillas of the farabundo marti national liberation front have pursued a steady campaign of economic sabotage as part of their 8-year-old war against the u.s.-backed government
in addition to the regular declaration of traffic bans, the campaign includes the blowing up of utility poles, attacks on power stations and raids on farms and warehouses containing coffee, cotton and sugar _ the country's main export crops
there were seven guerrilla-imposed transport strikes last year. three violators of the strike were killed, about 30 were wounded and 160 vehicles were destroyed or damaged
the insurgents on wednesday carried out their biggest attack of the year, assaulting the base of the 6th infantry brigade and a cotton cooperative in usulutan, 70 miles east of the capital
the rebel radio said the assault marked the beginning of a campaign designated ``armed struggle is the alternative to the new electoral farce.''
leftist parties have not participated in elections held during the war, saying that their candidates' safety could not be guaranteed
thai and laotian forces began a truce in a disputed border area friday, pulling back from the hilly ground where hundreds of comrades had been killed since november, thai officers said
after the cease-fire began at 8 a.m., two parallel rows of thai and laotian flags were planted to mark a zone two miles deep that soldiers are forbidden to cross, said the army chief of staff, gen. charuay wongsayant
military officials of both sides agreed to the cease-fire wednesday after two days of talks in bangkok. the disputed area is about 240 miles north of bangkok between thailand's northern province of phitsanulok and sayaboury province in laos
col. rithee rungkaputi, chief of civilian affairs for the 3rd army region, said a half-hour skirmish occurred on a contested hill an hour before the truce began, with no casualties. he said it there probably was a delay in commmunicating the cease-fire order
rithee also reported a heavy artillery exchange and two ground battles wednesday and thursday, while military teams from the two countries were meeting in bangkok
foreign minister siddhi savetsila of thailand told reporters friday that foreign ministry officials had been sent to france seeking help in resolving the problem. both sides claim the area on the basis of recognized maps and a 1907 french-thai treaty
the official laotian news agency kpl quoted maj. gen. thonglay kommasith, deputy head of the army's general political department, as saying the talks in bangkok ``paved the way toward negotiations, a diplomatic channel to solve the lao-thai border problem.''
thonglay participated in the bangkok meeting. the dispatch said he spoke at a news conference thursday in vientiane
the agreement calls for the governments to hold talks within 15 days after the truce begins to determine the frontier line
prime minister margaret thatcher has announced plans to shift 70,000 of britain's 580,000 civil servants out of government ministries and into a dozen new agencies run by private-industry-style executives
the new agencies will take over such duties as issuing passports and drivers' licenses, forecasting the weather and printing government documents
mrs. thatcher told the house of commons thursday that ``in general'' the new agencies planned in the next 12 months will stay part of the civil service, accountable to the government and parliament
but she indicated some may eventually become private companies, saying: ``insofar as they become totally outside the civil service they will not, of course, be accountable'' to government scrutiny
she did not elaborate but said the 12 were ``the first suitable candidates,'' indicating more changes are in the pipeline
the british domestic news agency press association said the plans herald the biggest civil service shake-up this century
the daily telegraph said the government aims to eventually separate the civil servants responsible for carrying out executive functions from the minority responsible for formulating policy
the possibility of some of the new agencies eventually being turned into private companies drew criticism from the opposition labor party
some civil service trade unions also attacked the restructuring plans, saying the changes could lead to a decline in pay and working conditions for their members
the government has said its aim is increased efficiency. the 12 new agencies will take control of 12 services currently run by central government departments. they include:
_ issuing passports, currently one of the jobs of the home office
_ running the government stationery office which prints government documents. that is currently one of the jobs of the office of the chancellor of the exchequer, nigel lawson
_ running the meteorological office, which provides weather forecasts for the armed forces, television and radio, farmers and other clients and is presently run by the ministry of defense
_ managing the royal parks in and around london, now done by the department of the environment
_ issuing driving permits, one of the jobs of the department of transport
the plans announced by mrs. thatcher follow a report by her efficiency unit headed by sir robin ibbs, an executive of the industrial chemicals group imperial chemical industries. it called for agencies run by executives, not ministers, to take over the day-to-day executive functions of government
mrs. thatcher came to power in 1979 pledged to cut back the growth of big government. her conservative administration has followed a program of selling off state-owned companies to private owners
millionaire industrialist victor posner began serving part of a sentence for tax evasion friday by handing out rolls at a soup kitchen
he's being introduced to everybody on a first-name basis,'' said barbara smith, spokeswoman for camillus house, a shelter for the needy
the 69-year-old miami beach tycoon, who declined requests for interviews, was received ``in just the same way as any other person who comes here to work as a volunteer, although i realize he's not a volunteer,'' ms. smith said
u.s. district judge eugene spellman last week sentenced posner to work 5,000 hours of community service over five years. he also must pay $3 million to help the homeless and $4 million in back taxes, penalties and interest
posner had faced up to 40 years in prison after pleading no contest last sept. 29 to evading more than $1.2 million in federal taxes by inflating the value of land he donated to a bible college as a tax exemption
posner, whose net worth was estimated at $240 million in 1984 by forbes magazine, will work one day a week for the next eight weeks at the downtown shelter
posner, accompanied by his attorney, edward bennett williams, began his five-hour shift by taking a tour of the shelter and meeting other workers
he worked at an entrance gate, admitting people to the cafeteria and making sure it did not exceed its capacity of about 100
when several news photographers tried to take his picture, posner went inside to serve rolls to people coming through the food line, which serves 700 to 900 needy people each day
several of the men who went through the food line said they knew about posner's background and found him to be friendly
he shook hands with me. he's a very nice guy,'' said brote harris. ``i said, `come on, papa, shake my hand. i'd like to shake a millionaire's hand.'''
posner, wearing a white shirt and clear plastic gloves, chatted with other workers as he handed out rolls. the meal also included hot chicken, string beans and rice
nicaragua proposed friday that canada and five western european countries take part in efforts to verify compliance with a central american peace plan
foreign minister miguel d'escoto told a news conference that foreign observers would form permanent mobile units in each of the five countries covered by the peace plan
the mobile units, he said, would be in place for a year and be allowed to make on-site inspections without prior notice to ensure the countries were meeting terms of the agreement
d'escoto suggested that representatives from canada, spain, italy, sweden, norway and west germany be members of the verification panel
the countries, he said, ``have shown their willingness to take part in this type of activity in order to achieve and guarantee peace in central america.''
the presidents of nicaragua, costa rica, el salvador, honduras and guatemala signed the peace plan last aug. 7
d'escoto said he offered the proposal at a verification meeting of the central american foreign ministers wednesday. the officials met for 10 hours in san salvador, the capital of el salvador, but failed to agree on ways to determine compliance with the peace plan
they called for further talks in guatemala by march 15
the peace plan calls for cease-fire negotiations between governments and insurgents in el salvador, guatemala and nicaragua as a first step toward democratic elections
it also calls for political amnesties and a ban on all outside military assistance to rebel groups
a kurdish inmate died friday, 12 days after he and 600 other prisoners began a hunger strike to protest prison conditions, the independent hurriyet news agency reported
it identified the inmate as mehmet emin yavuz, who had been sentenced to die for carrying out terrorist acts as a member of the outlawed kurdish labor party. his death sentence was awaiting parliamentary approval
yavuz died in a hospital in diyarbakir military prison where he was taken along with six other inmates after their health deteriorated during the hunger strike that began feb. 8, the agency said
the semi-official anatolia news agency reported later friday that the diyarbakir inmates stopped the hunger strike hours after yavuz' death
the government announced thursday that it agreed to improve prison conditions. however, the inmates and several relatives continued the hunger strike friday, contending that conditions remained unchanged, hurriyet said
most of the inmates belong to the kurdish labor party, which seeks to set up an independent marxist state in parts of southeastern turkey
foreign minister bernardo sepulveda denied in a strongly worded protest note that mexico allows its territory to be used by leftist rebels to threaten the government of el salvador
the government of mexico in no case allows the use of mexican territory by the groups of the fmln-fdr (farabundo marti national liberation front _ democratic revolutionary front) to develop activities that have repercussions and attempt against the stability of the salvadoran government,'' sepulveda said in a note to foreign minister ricardo acevedo peralta of el salvador
the note, released thursday afternoon, was in response to a protest note acevedo peralta sent to mexico earlier in the week
the fmln links five guerrilla groups that have been fighting el salvador's u.s.-supported government for the past eight years. the fdr is its political ally
the groups' joint political-diplomatic commission maintains an office in mexico city, as does clandestine rebel radio venceremos
sepulveda said the office is allowed because mexican law establishes ``protection for political exiles who enter national territory and the constitution guarantees for all people who are in the territory liberty of association, transit and expression of ideas.''
a foreign ministry source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said sepulveda decided to make his response public because the salvadoran government released its note to the press. ``that goes out of normal diplomatic channels,'' the source said
relations between mexico and el salvador were tense in the early years of the salvadoran civil war, especially after then-president jose lopez portillo recognized the rebels as a legitimate political force in a joint mexican-french declaration in 1981
the friction has eased during the administration of president miguel de la madrid, who succeeded lopez portillo in december 1982
mexico helped form the contadora group seeking peace for central america in january 1983, along with panama, colombia and venezuela
one of four leaders of the extreme left group direct action who have been refusing food for 81 days was acquitted friday night on charges of attempted murder
nathalie menigon and the other two defendants in the case, regis schleicher and jean-francois gailhac, were found innocent by the special assizes court. the court, which has judges serving as the jury, was established last year for terrorism cases
the three were accused in the january 1982 shooting of alain carpentier, then a leader of a squatters movement in eastern paris
carpentier testified friday that he did not know the three defendants, and said police had tried to get him to say the direct action members were his assailants
i don't understand what you want of them,'' carpentier said. ``i'm the victim, and i can tell you they had nothing to do with this affair.''
police investigators told the court they considered the defendants suspects after questioning carpentier's friends and family
prosecutor daniel barreyre said in his closing argument that the shooting was part of direct action's effort to gain control of the squatters movement. he asked for 15-year sentences for each of the three defendants
ms. menigon and three other direct action leaders, joelle aubron, georges cipriani and jean-marc rouillan, have been on a hunger strike since dec. 1, demanding an end to their solitary confinement. they are being fed intravenously against their will
all four were convicted feb. 12 in a lower court of criminal association and given 10-year sentences. ms. menigon was convicted wednesday, also in the special assizes court, of attempted murder of two policemen
authorities say all of direct action's leaders are now in prison
several human rights groups have urged the government to meet the hunger strikers' demands, but justice minister albin chalendon said he will not yield to what he called blackmail
the parents of baby m have failed to reach an out-of-court settlement on surrogate mother mary beth whitehead-gould's visitation rights, sending the matter back to court, it was announced friday
superior court judge birger m. sween on friday set a hearing for march 28 to determine the terms under which mrs. beth whitehead-gould may visit the child she bore under a $10,000 contract and lost in the landmark court battle
mrs. whitehead-gould is allowed to visit the child for two hours every tuesday pending sween's decision
the state supreme court on feb. 3 banned surrogate motherhood for pay, voided the $10,000 contract, and reinstated her right to visit the baby, now legally called melissa stern
the court said a superior court judge must decide the conditions for visitation if mrs. whitehead-gould and the child's father, william stern, failed to reach an agreement
we did talk and it did not work. we cannot settle the case,'' said gary n. skoloff, an attorney for the sterns. he declined to disclose the positions of both sides
mrs. whitehead-gould's attorney, harold j. cassidy, said in a statement friday night the sterns had not negotiated with the child's best interest in mind
it is in the best interest of melissa that she have the opportunity to know and love and respect her mother,'' he said. ``until mr. and mrs. stern learn to accept this simple fact, there cannot be further discussions.''
the baby m case began when the sterns signed a contract with mrs. whitehead-gould for her to be artificially inseminated with stern's sperm and bear them a child
after the child was born, mrs. whitehead-gould decided she couldn't give up the baby. the sterns sued to get the child back
on march 31 superior court judge harvey r. sorkow upheld the contract, terminated mrs. whitehead-gould's right to the baby, awarded custody to the sterns and let stern's wife, elizabeth, adopt the baby
the supreme court, in its 7-0 ruling, overturned all but the custody decision. attorney's name to higaki sted hikagi.</note>
a real estate magnate was sentenced to 15 years in prison friday for sending his estranged wife a bomb in a flower basket that injured her and a co-worker
peter pilaski, 54, received the same sentence given to his homosexual lover, 28-year-old shaun small, who testified pilaski supervised the bomb's construction and had him deliver the device in a bellhop's uniform
pilaski was convicted in december of conspiracy, making and possesing a bomb, and aiding and abetting in an explosion that damaged federal property and caused personal injury
melanie pilaski, 42, and a co-worker were injured in when the bomb, hidden in a basket of dried flowers, exploded at a u.s. general services administration building
the german-born pilaski, speaking in a heavy accent, maintained his innocence and told u.s. district judge robert schnacke the only time he saw the bomb used in the 1986 attack was when the government displayed a replica at his trial
i never wanted to hurt my wife. i still don't. ... i have a lot of feeling for her. i still do,'' he said as his voice cracked and tears filled his eyes
he said the prosecution drew a distorted picture of him ``as a cold-blooded murderer.''
small had testified pilaski suggested that he make the bomb and gave him detailed instructions about its delivery to mrs. pilaski, who had filed for divorce a month earlier after 20 years of marriage
small, who had donned a wig, heavy makeup and a uniform to deliver the bouquet, was convicted of using a bomb to damage federal property and cause personal injury
defense attorney paul higaki jr. said pilaski will appeal
pilaski could have received up to 45 years in prison and a $1 million fine. assistant u.s. attorney john lyons had asked for a 20-year sentence, arguing pilaski played a bigger role in the bombing
higaki said that parole authorities can review both men's sentences and release them at any time, but that pilaski might not survive any substantial term because of health problems that include a heart condition
small had testified that pilaski had become increasingly hostile toward his wife's drug use and alcoholism, that he vowed that she would regret her decision to seek a divorce and that he ordered small to assemble a bomb
pilaski was an impoverished west german seaman in 1955 when he immigrated to the united states, sponsored by small's parents. he made a fortune in real estate and hired small, then a teen-ager, as an apartment manager in 1976
mrs. pilaski testified that pilaski and small had been lovers and went on regular cocaine binges, and that her husband's relationship with small contributed to the breakup of their marriage
several anti-government activists planning to attend a weekend meeting of rural solidarity, the outlawed farmers' union, were detained by police friday, opposition spokesmen said
the group, modeled after the outlawed solidarity independent trade union, is planning a meeting sunday in the southeastern polish city of rzeszow, said opposition spokesman janusz winiarski
rural solidarity leaders have called a national meeting to mark the seventh anniversary of the rzeszow-ustrzyki agreements signed in february 1981 in which the government officially recognized rural solidarity
wladyslaw frasyniuk, a regional leader of solidarity in the southwest city of wroclaw, was detained around 6 p.m. friday by uniformed and plainclothed police, said his wife krystyna
police later telephoned their home and said without explanation that frasyniuk was being detained for 48 hours, mrs. frasyniuk said
another regional solidarity leader, stanislaw weglorz, was detained in his home city of lublin, in eastern poland, said opposition spokesman janusz winiarski
briefly detained was janusz stepniak, from near lublin, a leader of rural solidarity, said winiarski
stepniak was warned against attending the meeting
after the december 1981 imposition of martial law, rural solidarity, like other opposition groups, was banned by the government although some members have continued their activities
the world bank, a major source of credit for poor countries, late friday announced a five-year general capital increase
president barber b. conable said the capital increase of $74.8 billion will enable the bank to lend money to developing countries at the rate of $20 billion a year by the early 1990s
the world bank, owned by its 151 member countries, lent a record $14.2 billion in the fiscal year ending last june
agreement of the shareholding countries on the new capital opens the way for ``stronger world bank support for the developing countries'' and demonstrates ``the confidence of our shareholder governments in the bank,'' said conable
it was the bank's third general capital increase in its 44-year history. earlier general increases, in 1959 and 1980, approximately doubled the authorized capital. the latest increase will raise the bank's authorized capital to $171 billion
each of the 151 member countries contributes capital in proportion to its holding of shares, with the united states the largest shareholder with about 20 percent
only a small part of the capital is actually paid in cash. friday's announcement said this would be 3 percent, with the remaining 97 percent to be on call if needed to secure world bank borrowings
the guarantees of participating governments enable the world bank to borrow money in private capital markets and to invest the proceeds while waiting to disburse it to poor countries
last september, the bank sold a record $750 million offering of 10-year notes in the u.s. market at 9.91 percent after earlier selling issues of world bank dollar and yen bonds outside the united states. it registered $1.1 billion profit in the year ending last june 30
leftist guerrillas attacked a convoy of peruvian troops in the andes and killed 10 soldiers and two civilians, defense minister enrique lopez said friday
the assault thursday near a road construction site on the outskirts of huancavelica, a state capital 155 miles southeast of lima, was the most devastating in a wave of attacks by shining path guerrillas this month
a group of army personnel were the object of a cowardly attack by delinquent subversives,'' the joint military command said. lopez and the joint command declined to elaborate on how the rebels mounted the raid
lopez said the troops were traveling in civilian vehicles from huancavelica to the road construction site to provide protection to government workers
the mao-inspired shining path has been fighting for eight years to topple the government and install a marxist state
a year ago, the guerrillas exploded a mine near huancavelica that killed 10 soldiers and four civilians. one week ago, in a nearly identical attack, rebels killed 10 soldiers and wounded 14
since early february, leftist guerrillas have killed five telephone company workers, bombed and derailed two ore trains and bombed the office of royal dutch shell and five other private offices in lima
huancavelica, one of peru's most impoverished and isolated regions, is under a state of emergency to counter rising guerrilla violence
the government says more than 10,000 people, including troops, police, guerrillas and non-combatants, have died during the shining path insurgency
world experts ended a three-day meeting friday without completing a draft protocol on controlling nitrogen oxide pollution, suspected of being a main factor in widespread forest damage in europe and north america
environmentalist groups allowed to attend part of the closed-door meeting expressed deep disappointment
we can only conclude that the international community is prepared to condemn the environment to an acid future,'' said andrew kerr, an observer for greenpeace
the meeting of experts from 25 nations was sponsored by the u.n. economic commission for europe. commission spokesman hans lassen said it now was up to the governments to complete the protocol, adding that it was still hoped the protocol could be signed before the end of the year
lassen said three major areas of disagreement remained, requiring ``political decisions'':
_when would a freeze on emissions take force and from what level should they be reduced by a proposed 30 percent
_would the united states be entitled to an ``emission credit'' _ meaning a reduction by less than 30 percent _ in view of efforts it has already taken unilaterally to control pollution
_by what year should unleaded fuel be available in all countries parties to the protocol
acid rain begins with sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxide pollution from smelters, power plants and vehicle exhaust. it travels long distances in the atmosphere and is transformed into sulfuric and nitric acid before falling to the earth in rain or snow
it raises the acidity of lakes and rivers, killing off fish, and has been blamed by some environmentalists for stunting forest growth
sources close to the meeting said seven countries _ canada, west germany, switzerland, austria, denmark, sweden and the netherlands _ called for a freeze on nitrogen oxide emissions at the 1987 level by 1990
the united states, britain, france, norway, finland as well as the soviet union and its allies reportedly favored a freeze by 1994 at the level of 1987 or later, with a reduction several years later
canada strongly opposed the u.s. proposal for a credit clause in the protocol, the sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity. canada reportedly argued that the concept of using past actions to control air pollution to permit future increases in national emissions was contrary to the spirit of the agreement
greenpeace has demanded a 75 percent cut in emissions throughout europe
adam markham, the observer for the world wildlife fund, complained that the draft protocol that was emerging ``virtually has no teeth.'' markham said it was increasingly likely that a group of countries, including west germany, switzerland and scandinavian countries, will seek a separate accord _ outside the protocol _ that would call for speedier measures
a twin-engine plane skimmed over rush-hour traffic friday and crashed on a freeway access road, killing all three people aboard and spewing flaming debris that destroyed two parked cars, authorities said
it looked like it was going to attempt maybe to come onto the freeway, but as soon as it got over the freeway, it just nosedived,'' said victor armendariz, who was at a stop light. ``there's not much left. it's just charcoal.''
the gulfstream commander 680 went down in moderate snow and light fog after takeoff from el paso international airport shortly before 9 a.m., national transportation safety board spokesman tommy mcfall said
from the eyewitnesses we talked to, (the plane) didn't have any power on the way down. it was silent,'' said police sgt. john loy
the victims' identities were not immediately released. the plane's destination was not available
the plane apparently developed landing-gear trouble and was trying to return to the airport when it crashed onto the interstate 10 access road, mcfall said. the cause of the crash was under investigation
the man known as the ``grand puppeteer'' for his high-level personal connections dashed investigators' hopes friday that he would detail what he knew about the collapse of the nation's largest private bank
licio gelli is accused in italy of masterminding a group involved in right-wing terrorism, subversion and spying. he was the grandmaster of the p-2 (propaganda due) masonic lodge, which italian officials linked to tax evasion, bribery, conspiracy to topple the government and other spectacular crimes
but his extradition wednesday from switzerland came on grounds he would only face charges of fraudulent bankruptcy in the 1982 collapse of banco ambrosiano
gelli had written to magistrates in milan and expressed his willingness to discuss the collapse of the bank, but he refused to talk to them when they visited him in jail in parma friday, said officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity
in 1981, gelli fled italy after police raided his office and found a list of purported p-2 lodge members. the list included cabinet ministers, journalists, businessmen and generals. the scandal toppled the government of premier arnaldo forlani
gelli was arrested in switzerland in september 1982 when he tried to withdraw funds from a frozen account at a geneva bank. he was sentenced to two months in jail for entering the country illegally
in 1983, while awaiting extradition to italy, gelli escaped and reportedly hid in south america for four years
he surrendered to swiss authorities last september, reportedly suffering from heart problems. he was convicted and sentenced to two months in prison for paying a guard a $20,000 bribe to help him escape
a fast-moving freight train struck a car and cut it in two, killing all four occupants at a desert crossing friday, authorities said
three airmen from edwards air force base were among those killed by the train traveling about 50 mph, los angeles county sheriff's deputy roger hom said
investigators said the gate on the side of the crossing the car entered was found in the up position, while the other gate was down
they said they were unable to conclude whether the first gate had failed to come down, came down late, or was down when the car approached and the driver bypassed it
a government council recommended friday that emergency rule be extended in nine provinces to help combat kurdish insurgents, the semi-official anatolia news agency said
the emergency rule would include turkey's largest city, istanbul, and the southeast provinces of bingol, diyarbakir, elazig, hakkari, mardin, siirt, tunceli and van, the news agency said
the national security council, a powerful advisory body of cabinet members and top military commanders, announced its recommendation after a meeting friday, anatolia said
government troops and kurdish guerrillas seeking autonomy have fought since 1984. an estimated 10 million of turkey's 52 million people are ethnic kurds and most live in the rugged terrain of east and southeast turkey
if the recommendation is approved by the one-house parliament, emergency rule in those provinces will be extended for four months as of march 19, when a four-month period of emergency rule expires
under emergency rule, civilian officials may impose curfews or bar or censor a publication. it differs from martial law in that emergency powers are assumed by civilian officials instead of military commanders
the national council of churches said friday that continued israeli occupation of territories taken in the 1967 six-day war ``is unacceptable.''
the status quo cannot, and should not be maintained,'' the council said of the rioting on israel's west bank and gaza strip
declaring that ``the israeli military response to the palestinian uprising has been disporportionate and often brutal,'' with more than 50 people killed and hundreds wounded and beaten, the council said:
it is time for the parties to the conflict _ israel, the chosen representatives of the palestinian people and affected arab states _ to negotiate an end to the painful impasse.''
the statement was adopted by the 49-member executive committee of the council, which includes most u.s major protestant and eastern orthodox denominations
the government raised gas prices 32 percent friday in a new tax to help retirees, whose monthly stipends have declined in value in the nation's economic crisis
president raul alfonsin and congress proposed the gas tax last month as a way to help finance a 40 percent increase in the monthly pensions of retirees to 300 australs, or about $52
economy minister juan v. sourrouille said friday inflation for 1988 was expected to exceed 100 percent. the inflation will come despite the planned sale of some debt-ridden state companies and programs to push export sales and increase income tax collections, he said
inflation stood at 175 percent last year, more than double the 82 percent rise in 1986. blame was placed primarily on debilitating strikes, low prices for exports and high losses from state-owned companies
last week, argentina and the scandanavian carrier sas signed an agreement in which sas will buy 20 to 40 percent of state-owned aerolineas argentinas, which is heavily in debt. under the accord, sas has until may to determine its ownership share
a doctor and former hospital board chairman was indicted friday on charges he defrauded pharmaceutical companies of nearly $2 million by falsifying test results on experimental drugs
dr. robert a. fogari, 46, of saddle river, invented data and patients, enrolled ineligible patients in the clinical studies and failed to report adverse affects the drugs may have caused, federal prosecutors said
the drugs tested were anti-inflammatory treatments for arthritis
one of the drugs was feldene, a leading seller for the pharmaceutical company pfizer, which used fogari's test results in its advertising, said assistant u.s. attorney paul weissman
fogari, who has a practice in jersey city, also was charged with obstruction of justice for allegedly inducing witnesses to lie to investigators and a grand jury
he was accused of defrauding the companies, including johnson &amp; johnson, pfizer, upjohn and warner-lambert, from 1977 to 1985, when the food and drug administration barred him from performing trials
for part of that period, fogari was chairman of the board of managers of jersey city medical center, where he was a board member until last year. he also was chief of rheumatology at that hospital and president of the medical staff at st. francis hospital in jersey city, u.s. attorney samuel a. alito jr. said
pharmaceutical companies use doctors to perform clinical trials and pay them on the basis of the number of patients and office visits and the procedures performed
fogari did not return a telephone call to his office. his attorney, a. patrick nucciarone, said in a statement he is convinced his client will be exonerated
experimental drugs cannot be sold in the united states unless approved by the fda, which reviews clinical data provided by the company before allowing their sale
pharmaceutical companies provide the drugs free to physicians conducting the clinical trials. the doctors in turn are required to follow study guidelines, keep accurate records and provide them to the fda for review
officials involved in a widely publicized bribery and corruption case tried in slovakia have been expelled from the communist party, the ruling politburo announced friday
an announcement by the state news agency ctk said the presidium also chided legal and judicial organs in the republic of slovakia for a slow approach to the case, which was reported in the west and in czechoslovakia's state-run media
the trial focused on stanislav babinsky, former head of a catering and supply enterprise in dolni kubin in western slovakia. he was sentenced last summer to 14{ years in jail on charges he misappropriated $382,000 in state property
babinsky and his associates were accused of paying bribes, giving away art work and antique furniture and arranging sex parties in order to attract development aid to dolni kubin, a mountainous agricultural region near the polish border
there were persistent but unconfirmed reports that high government and party officials were involved in the scandal
friday's statement from the communist party's ruling presidium, or politburo, said functionaries had been expelled from the party, while other unspecified ``comrades were accused falsely'' in connection with the case
every inconsistency or regard for the position of individuals or even attempts to shield functionaries or leading workers ... create distrust in the party,'' the statement said
communist party leader milos jakes stressed when he took over the party leadership from president gustav husak in december that corruption in official ranks must be combated. news digest: trye, lebanon _ lebanon-kidnap, a0476; jerusalem _ isrtael-violence, a0411; undated _ political rdp, a0442; morrisville, n.c. _ plane crashes, a0473</note>
