an extract of snake venom shows promise as a treatment for stroke victims, according to researchers looking for ways to dissolve blood clots before brain damage can occur
the treatment, called ancrod, is derived from the venom of the malayan pit viper. doctors have given it to 10 patients, and although the results are still preliminary, the therapy appears to help
this is a drug that shows potential,'' said the study's director, dr. charles p. olinger, of the university of cincinnati
supreme court justice anthony m. kennedy's first full week in a new judicial career may attract more public scrutiny and speculation than did most of his 12 years as a federal appellate judge
the ``fish bowl'' experience begins when the high court's newest member joins his eight colleagues in taking the bench at 10 a.m. est monday and starts hearing arguments in cases under study
what will be kennedy's first question from the bench? will he, as justice antonin scalia did two years ago, quickly establish himself as an aggressive interrogator of lawyers appearing before the court?
the soviets have become more open about announcing their space failures, but failed to announce the destruction of a spy satellite last month and gave out sparse details about a rocket failure, space-watcher jim oberg said saturday
the official tass news agency reported that the upper stage of the proton rocket booster failed on wednesday and that on thursday ``the sputniks entered dense layers of the atmosphere and ceased their existence.''
according to u.s. space command, the largest chunk of debris from the mission re-entered the earth's atmosphere friday afternoon between saudi arabia and turkey, and a smaller chunk fell earlier near australia
president reagan contends in his annual economic report to congress that his tax and budget policies helped turn economic despair into hope during his administration
the report issued friday also downplayed problems associated with the $2.4 trillion national debt and record trade imbalances during the reagan years
separately, on wall street the dow jones industrial average finished at a six-week high, rising 28.18 points to 2,014.59. the widely-followed indicator had not closed at such heights since it stood at 2,051.89 on jan. 7
market watchers attributed the rally to an increasingly optimistic market outlook, due partly to signs of strength in the manufacturing sector of the economy
in an eight-page introduction to this year's economic report, president reagan said the country was in much better shape than when he took office seven years ago. the president said the attitude toward the economy had shifted to hope from the despair that prevailed in the early 1980s
the past five years of sustained and vigorous growth in production, income and employment did not occur by accident,'' the report stated. ``they were shaped by government policies explicitly directed toward fostering the inherent dynamism of the private sector.''
during a separate press briefing, beryl sprinkel, the president's chief economic adviser, said the united states had produced 2{ times the number of jobs as the other top six industrialized countries combined since the end of the 1981-82 recession
addressing the nation's $400 billion foreign debt, sprinkel noted that the net payments to foreigners needed to service the country's foreign debt represented just 0.1 percent of the $4.6 trillion u.s. economy
sprinkel predicted an improving trade deficit would provide about half of the country's overall economic growth this year, which the administration is forecasting will slow to a 2.4 percent from 3.8 percent in 1987
sprinkel also said recent signs of economic slowdown did not point to a recession in 1988. he said the recent string of three consecutive declines in the index of leading indicators signaled slower economic growth in the first half of 1988 but not a recession this year
sprinkel discounted recent big declines in the key housing construction sector during december and january, attributing them to a too-restrictive monetary policy pursued by the federal reserve in the months before the october stock market collapse
in facing a proxy fight over four seats on its board of directors, gillette co. might also be facing a referendum on its future as an independent company, analysts say
gillette said friday it would resist an attempt by coniston partners to place four representatives on board seats up for election at the company's annual meeting in april, including the seat of chairman colman m. mockler jr
coniston, which holds a roughly 6 percent stake in the giant personal products maker, is attempting to pressure gillette into a restructuring or merger that would boost its share price
gillette rose 25 cents to $38.87{ a share in new york stock exchange trading friday
coniston pursued a similar strategy last year in leading the successful campaign to break up allegis corp., leading analysts to predict the battle over gillette would be long and bitter
coniston i don't think is going to go away any time soon,'' said deepak rap, who follows gillette for the investment firm merrill lynch &amp; co
mockler, who also is gillette's chief executive and president, said gillette would continue resisting coniston in the belief that the company would function best as an independent business
gillette cited its 1987 financial results, which reflected a 12 percent rise in sales and a doubling of operating profit, indicated that its business strategy was working
andrew shore, of the investment firm shearson lehman hutton inc., said proxy fights were difficult to win, but in this case gillette management would have its hands full
the company has rebuffed several buyout offers from revlon group inc. dating back to 1986. the latest _ a $47-a-share, or $5.4 billion, offer _ was spurned late last year
in addition, a major restructuring that it undertook after turning down a $4.12 billion revlon buyout offer in november 1986 may not have boosted gillette's share price enough to suit major investors who remain wary about the strength of the stock market in the wake of october's crash
gillette's recent stock price in the high-$30 range is well below the high-$40 to low-$50 range analysts estimate is the company's acquisition value
it's really a referendum, like a vote for coniston is a vote for the sale of gillette,'' said shore. ``that's going to be very difficult for shareholders to turn down.''
revlon must have gillette's consent to launch a takeover of the company under terms of a 10-year standstill agreement it signed in november 1986, when gillette bought out revlon's nearly 14 percent stake in the company after spurning the $4.12 billion offer
nevertheless, revlon chairman ronald o. perelman reportedly remains interested in acquiring gillette
shore said that in addition to opposing coniston's slate of directors, gillette could take other defensive measures including the issuance of more stock, a leveraged buyout, a recapitalization or a ``white knight'' merger with a friendly suitor
even its candidates win election, coniston would be unable to take control of gillette's board because only a third of the seats are up for election in any year. but analysts say a coniston victory could pressure the board to consider a merger
keith gollust, a principal in the partnership, contended the proxy fight was mandated by gillette's takeover defenses, which essentially gave its board unilateral power to accept or reject any merger offers
